<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PenthouseSuit     08-26 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Penthouse Suit,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Overturns Judge's Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Friday overturned a
judge's ruling that a Virginia savings and loan pay Penthouse
International Boardwalk Properties Inc. nearly $130 million for
allegedly sabotaging a loan.
   The decision, released Friday, also overturned an order that
Dominion Federal Savings and Loan Association pay $7.65 million in
damages to Queens City Savings and Loan, the lead lender in a $97
million loan package for an Atlantic City casino-hotel project.
   Penthouse President Robert Guccione spent more than $60 million
on the casino project, but sought extra financing in 1983. Dominion
Federal promised to provide $35 million in funding although it was
barred by law from making a single loan of more than $18.5 million.
   U.S. District Judge Kevin Duffy accused Dominion Chairman
William Walde in a July 31, 1987, decision of launching a cover-up
after a third lender pulled out of the deal.
   The appeals court, however, said in its 67-page opinion: ``There
was no evidence establishing that Dominion intended not to proceed
and there is an abundance of evidence to indicate just the
opposite.''
   Dominion Federal announced the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
decision. Reporters could not obtain copies late Friday.
   The McLean, Va.-based lending institution had posted a $50
million bond while awaiting the appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
