<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBI-Capitol     08-26 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Capitol,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Searches State Capitol Offices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents searched half a dozen
state Capitol offices belonging to lawmakers or their aides as part
of an apparent corruption probe, the FBI and a state senator said
Thursday.
   Sen. Joseph Montoya, the Democratic chairman of the Senate
Business and Professions Committee, and Assemblyman Pat Nolan, the
Republican floor leader of that chamber, confirmed that their
offices were among those searched by the FBI. But both denied
involvement in any improper activities.
   The FBI refused to reveal the names of the lawmakers or even the
subject of the investigation, but a Capitol source, who spoke on
the condition that he not be identified, said all of the parties
named in the search warrants were involved in the passage of a bill
involving investment banking regulations.
   A Senate aide who received one of the search warrants, chief
sergeant at arms Tony Beard, said the warrants specified documents
related to a vetoed bill involving investment banking law.
   At least one office was searched for more than three hours,
sources said.
   ``What I can tell you is that anything I have received in the
way of contributions or honoraria is always done as prescribed by
law,'' said Montoya, who confirmed that federal agents searched his
office.
   Montoya also confirmed that agents were seeking information on
the investment banking law bill.
   ``I guess they wanted to check things out,'' he said, adding
that agents were seeking information about two measures that passed
through his committee.
   ``The FBI executed warrants Wednesday on the offices of six
legislators and legislative assistants,'' said Terry Knowles,
special agent in charge of the Sacramento FBI office. ``The
searches were in connection with an ongoing investigation,'' and
were conducted late Wednesday, he added.
   A Capitol employee said a team of about 30 federal investigators
from the FBI and U.S. attorney's office served search warrants on
the lawmakers' offices.
   ``All I know is some agents came in last night and served some
warrants. There were no arrests, no obvious scene. I can't tell you
who (was served),'' the source said.
   ``My office and the offices of several members from both parties
were searched last night by the FBI. It is not clear to me yet what
the object of the investigation is, but I am confident that when
the investigation is completed, my office will be completely
cleared,'' Nolan said in a written statement.
</TEXT>
