<DOCNO> AP880826-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PiningSwine     08-26 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pining Swine,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boar Owner Making Whole Hog Effort to Sell Swine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH FALMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 800-pound, lovesick boar named
Walter who's been hogging too much of his owner's attention lately
has been put up for sale, but so far there have been few offers for
the pining swine.
   ``A guy wanted to know if I would deliver him to Nova Scotia,''
said owner David Dewees, who is asking about $300 for Walter.
``There really haven't been any serious offers.''
   The trouble with Walter is that he's doubled in size since a
friend gave him to Dewees about 6 months ago and is ``desperately
in need of female companionship,'' according to the classified
advertisement Dewees ran this week in the Cape Cod Times.
   ``He's just rooting up the fences and is constantly looking
around and you can just tell by the noises he's making that he's
desperately looking for females,'' Dewees said.
   Walter eats like, well, a pig, putting away close to five
gallons of garbage a day, Dewees said.
   ``I feed him mostly garbage and of course the green stuff from
the garden that's left over and he loves it all,'' he said.
Neighbors bring their children to watch Walter at the trough.
   ``It's a huge, awful sight to see him eat,'' Dewees said.
   A cabinetmaker and construction worker who used to raise pigs,
Dewees says he won't have enough time this winter to look after
Walter, whose currently living at a nearby farm along with four
sheep and two horses.
   Walter, a blend of Hampshire and Poland China, is about 5 feet
long and has chewed through the planks of his pen with his 4-inch
tusks.
   Dewees said selling his porcine pet for meat isn't likely to
bring home the bacon because mature boar meat generally isn't good
for anything more than catfood.
   However, Walter isn't naturally boorish, even though he has made
mistaken advances to the back of a pickup truck and was turned down
for the local fair because there wasn't a pen strong enough to hold
him, Dewees said.
   ``He's really a very gentle fellow. He never has been aggressive
as far as meanness is concerned. He really needs companionship.''
</TEXT>
