<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BatHouse     08-26 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bat House,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bat Colony Chase Owners From House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A colony of more than 2,000 bats has
chased a couple from their home of 15 years, and one of them says
``it's too scary'' to move back until they're sure the winged
invaders are gone.
   After dark each day, Lorraine and Steve Disburger watch brown
bats flutter in and out of the yellow wood-frame house. They said
they haven't been able to find anyone to help them solve their
problem, largely because they have trouble getting people to
believe them.
   ``I'll never forget the night we left,'' Mrs. Disburger said
recently. ``I couldn't sleep. I was too scared. You could hear
them. It was one of those hot nights and it was like the house was
breathing.
   ``We had the lights on bright,'' she said. ``The bats were right
in the next room. Then one lit on Steve's leg. That did it. We went
outside and slept the rest of the night in our camper. The next
morning I begged my mother-in-law to take us in.''
   That was July 15, and they haven't been back to their central
New York home since except to do laundry and grab a few possessions.
   Disburger used heavy plastic to seal off the unfinished
second-floor room that seems to be the colony's nursery. But his
wife doesn't want to go near the house if she can help it.
   ``It's too scary,'' she said.
   She said she's been frustrated in trying to get help from pest
control experts, local and state health officials and legislators.
   The Disburgers have tried ultra-sound, mothball crystals and
smoke bombs to get rid of the bats. The only weapon that worked was
a tennis racquet, but smashing a bat creates possible exposure to
rabies and disease carried by the flying mammals.
   On Thursday, Stephen Frantz, a zoologist with the state Health
Department's Wadsworth Center for Laboratories and Research who
specializes in rodent and bat diseases, visited the Disburger home.
   ``Judging from what I've heard, it's certainly a problem,''
Frantz said before the visit. ``The large number of bats reported
is unusual, but not rare. This year, there seems to be more people
with serious problems.''
   The couple said they noticed more and more bats starting to
appear at the house about five years ago. They'd disappear in the
winter but would come back in spring, she said.
   The Disburgers tried their best to plug up their old house.
They'd sit in the camper at night and watch the entrances and exits
used by the bats. Disburger had ladders ready all around the
exterior; he'd run and get some insulation and plug a hole.
   The couple said they expect to spend up to $4,000 to rid their
house of the winged varmints. That includes scattering the colony,
plugging all the holes and putting on a new roof.
   Frantz said he was thinking of sealing up most of the holes in
the house, then installing one-way exits in the remaining ones.
When the bats leave at night to feed, he said, they won't be able
to get return.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
