<DOCNO> AP880826-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SpyRing-Glance     08-26 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spy Ring-Glance,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Germany Has Long History Of Spy Scandals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Spy Ring, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist spies have been operating in
West Germany since its founding in 1949. Here are some of the more
recent spy cases, as well as some of the more notorious ones:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 28, 1988 _ West German federal law authorities announce
the arrest of 10 people who are accused of working for the Soviet
KGB. Chief Federal Prosecutor Kurt Rebmann said the roundup marked
``an important penetration of the KGB spy network.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 31, 1987 _ Margaret Hoeke, a secretary for five West German
presidents, is sentenced to eight years in prison after admitting
she gave state secrets to a KGB agent because she was lonely and
loved him. The information she handed over included sensitive
correspondence between U.S. President Reagan and West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1985 _ Hans Joachim Tiedge, head of a West German
counterintelligence unit responsible for catching East German
spies, defects to East Germany.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1976 _ Lothar-Erwin Lutze and his wife Renate are among 16
people arrested in an espionage crackdown. The Lutzes had passed
NATO documents to East Germany since the 1960s. Then-Defense
Minister Georg Leber resigns over the scandal. The Lutzes are later
released to East Germany in a spy swap.
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1974 _ Guenter Guillaume, a top aide to then-Chancellor Willy
Brandt, is exposed as an East German agent. The resulting scandal
forces Brandt to resign. Guillaume gets a 13-year prison sentence
but is released to East Germany in an East-West spy exchange six
years later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a BC-Theater     08-26 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negro Ensemble Presents `Mississippi Delta'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three fine actresses take all the parts in
``From the Mississippi Delta,'' a strong, evocative evening of
theater by Endesha Ida Mae Holland at off-Broadway's Theater Four.
   The presentation by the Negro Ensemble Company has nine
sections, stronger than vignettes, which weave individual lives
through a Mississippi Delta small-town tapestry from the early
1950s into the 1980s.
   Humor and personal tragedy are well-balanced in the play which
begins with a prologue of reminiscenses. In the first ``chapter,''
``Calm, Balmy Days,'' Latanya Richardson plays a white grandmother
who takes an 11-year-old black girl, played by Brenda Denmark, home
to babysit her granddaughter, played by Gwen Roberts-Frost. The
grandmother then calls the babysitter into the bedroom so her
husband can rape her.
   This is followed by the evening's strongest section, ``Second
Doctor Lady.'' Miss Richardson plays Ain't Baby, a name she
received when she no longer was the baby in her family. Now
middle-aged, she is a wonderful midwife. With the other two
actresses narrating dramatically and playing children peeking
through a back window, Ain't Baby delivers a breech-birth baby.
   ``The Water Meter'' is the funniest section of the evening. A
white meter reader tells a gullible old black woman that if anybody
steps on her ground-level meter her water bill will skyrocket. The
old woman has a pile of bricks and a notoriously bad aim so
children and drunks enjoy the challenge.
   Then northern Civil Rights workers arrive and a black girl
cooperates with them. Whites burn down her mother's shack with the
mother inside. It ends with a preacher praying the mother into
heaven and the girl going north to college.
   The playwright, a native of Greenwood, Miss., has a Ph.D. from
the University of Minnesota. She is associate professor of American
studies at the State University of New York in Buffalo.
   Edward Smith, founder of the Buffalo Black Workshop, directed.
Steven Perry designed the set, the back of which is the spare frame
of a house. The first Manhattan production of the play was at the
Henry Street Settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bishop-Democrats     08-26 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishop-Democrats,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Quits Democratic Party Over Abortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Connecticut's top Roman Catholic cleric
has ended his longtime affiliation with the Democratic Party and
reregistered as a Republican because of the Democrats' stances on
birth control and abortion rights.
   Archbishop John F. Whealon of Hartford announced his decision to
quit the Democratic Party in his weekly column in ``The Catholic
Transcript,'' the archdiocesan weekly newspaper appearing Friday.
   Whealon didn't say in his column that he had registered as a
Republican, but he made the switch last week, according to
officials in the office of the West Hartford registrar of voters.
   Whealon complained the Democratic platform drafted during the
recent national convention ``is in favor of contraception and
abortion, financed by the government.''
   He said the Republican Party platform expressed support for the
family and opposed abortion.
   ``In 1860, the Democratic Party was on the wrong side on the
moral question of slavery. It is on the wrong side of the more
serious moral question of abortion. Therefore, reluctantly, I am
unable in conscience to remain a registered Democrat. Feeling
abandoned, I hope that the Democratic Party regains its moral
principles and soul,'' the archbishop wrote.
   Whealon had been registered as a Democrat in Connecticut since
1969.
   ``I had no idea what his political affiliation was, and I don't
know that anyone else did either,'' Democratic State Chairman John
Droney said Thursday.
   ``We're glad to have him aboard,'' said Pauline Kezer, vice
chairman of the state Republican Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
