<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Israel-Army,0113</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Appoints New Intelligence Corps Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brig. Gen. Oren Shachor has been appointed the
army's chief intelligence officer, the second highest position in
the intelligence corps, the army command said.
   The 42-year-old Shachor has held several intelligence-related
posts since joining the military in 1964, the army said Thursday.
   He fought in the 1973 Middle East war and during the 1982
invasion of Lebanon. In 1986, Shachor was appointed head of the
army's liaison unit with foreign armies.
   Shachor, who will officially be given the new posting today,
succeeds Brig. Gen. Giora Zorea and will serve under Maj.-Gen.
Amnon Shachak, head of the intelligence corps.
