<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--TombFound     08-26 0121</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Tomb Found,0123</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ancient Phoenician Tomb Discovered On Italian Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANT'ANTIOCO, Sardinia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Phoenician tomb from the sixth
century B.C. has been discovered on this island off the southern
coast of Sardinia, archaeologists say.
   The tomb, untouched by grave-robbers, was located in the past
few days during an excavation in the necropolis of the ancient town
of Sulci.
   The tomb contained the remains of five bodies, 60 vases, one
golden earring, a number of glass necklaces and three stone
scarabs, said archaeologist Paolo Bernardini.
   He said it is believed to be one of the oldest tombs ever found
in Sulci.
   The Phoenicians were an ancient sea-trading people who colonized
areas of North Africa as well as southwestern Italy.
</TEXT>
