<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 3rdLd-Writethru a0815 08-26 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0815,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South, North Korea Resume Talks, Trying To Break Stalement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs with talks ending, next meeting scheduled
after Olympics. Pickup 3rd graf pvs `The five-member...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea and North Korea failed again
today to clear the way for full-scale talks on sharing the Olympics
and on a non-aggression pact and said they will not meet again
until after the Games.
   The two sides, after more than three hours of discussion, failed
to resolve any outstanding issues. The South proposed they meet
again in October after the Olympics. The North proposed a meeting
Oct. 13, which was accepted by the South.
   The decision not to meet until October appeared to indicate the
two sides had given up on efforts to work out an agreement on the
Olympics, which end Oct. 2.
   But South Korean officials would not rule out a last-minute bid
to try to get the North to participate in the Games in Seoul.
   The five-member delegations of lawmakers from each side smiled
and shook hands as the meeting opened in the South Korean building
at the Panmunjom truce village, 35 miles north of Seoul. The site
straddles the Demilitarized Zone, the neutral DMZ which divides the
two Koreas.
   Chief delegate Park Joon-kyu of South Korea urged the communist
North to agree to hold parliamentary talks in the North's capital
of Pyongyang next Monday to resolve the Olympic question.
   He noted that the Olympic flame was due to arrive in the South
on Saturday and time was running out before the Games begin on
Sept. 17
   ``The attention of the entire world is now focused on the
question of whether the grand festival of national reconciliation .
.. will be held or not,'' he said.
   The chief North Korean delegate, Chon Kum Chol, said talks
should be held as soon as possible, but still insisted that a
non-aggression pact should top the agenda. He said full-scale talks
should also stress the Olympics.
   Chon said the dispute over the North's call for representatives
of social and other groups taking part in the parliamentary talks
could be put aside and settled at the actual talks. But he held
fast that the full parliaments of both sides take part in the
negotiations.
   The talks began Aug. 19, ended in stalemate Monday and resumed
Friday only because their top delegates met Wednesday.
   South Korean officials said Thursday the negotiations would bog
down unless North Korea changes its ``unrealistic'' positions.
   ``It is up to North Korea. We have done enough and nothing more
to give,'' said one source close to the South Korean delegation,
who asked not to be identified.
   The two sides differ widely over an agenda and the size of the
parliamentary talks.
   North Korea is demanding a meeting of the full legislatures of
both sides, involving nearly 1,000 members, plus dozens of
representatives of all walks of life.
   South Korea is seeking a smaller meeting of up to 30 delegates
from each side, saying that a large group cannot effectively tackle
sensitive issues.
   Also in dispute is a North Korean demand that the two
legislatures publish a joint declaration of non-aggression, calling
for the withdrawal of 42,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea.
South Korea considers the U.S. military presence essential to its
defense.
   North Korea called for urgent talks on sharing the Sept. 17-Oct.
2 Olympics, but South Korean officials said it seemed more
concerned about issuing a joint declaration of non-aggression.
   South Korean officials say there is virtually no hope for North
Korea to take part in the Olympics. They say North Korea is trying
to keep the current talks alive as long as possible to distract
world attention from the Olympics.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics unless it is
made a co-host. The International Olympic Committee has rejected
the North Korean demand, saying that the Olympics are awarded to a
single city and cannot be shared.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
capitalist South Korea at the end of World War II in 1945. They
fought the Korean War from 1950 to 1953, which left more than a
million people dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
