<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Italy-Drugs,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Seize 230 Pounds Of Cocaine, Arrest 76 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in five countries and two
continents have cracked a drug smuggling ring based in Milan,
arresting 76 people and seizing 230 pounds of cocaine, officials
said.
   Police said Thursday the cocaine is worth nearly $15 million.
The arrests and drug seizures took place during a four-year probe
that involved police in Italy, Argentina, Chile, Switzerland and
Austria, they said.
   Guglielmo Muntoni, the magistrate heading the investigation,
told a news conference that the drug trafficking ring smuggled
cocaine into Milan on flights through Zurich or Geneva, on a train
from Paris or by car from Spain through France.
   He said the last arrests came Wednesday night in Milan, where
police arrested two Uruguayans and seized 13.2 pounds of cocaine.
   Muntoni said the investigation used telephone taps, surveillance
and the monitoring of bank accounts.
</TEXT>
