<DOCNO> AP880826-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC--Suicides     08-26 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC--Suicides,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Recommends Ways To Handling `Cluster' Suicides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communities should be prepared ahead of time in
case they are struck by multiple suicides, since there is
``extremely compelling'' evidence that one can lead to another, the
Centers for Disease Control says.
   ``The middle of a crisis is no time to work out who's supposed
to be doing what,'' said Dr. Patrick O'Carroll, a CDC specialist in
suicide research.
   Being prepared is one of 10 recommendations the federal agency
issued Thursday to help communities deal with ``clusters'' of
suicides.
   The recommendations stem from a conference held in New Jersey
late last year to enable communities that have not seen outbreaks
of suicide to learn from those that have.
   On March 11, 1987, four Bergenfield, N.J., teen-agers killed
themselves in a garage in an apparent death pact. Within six days,
four more teen-agers were dead in the Chicago suburbs, and
officials said those suicides probably were triggered by reports of
the New Jersey deaths.
   Rule No. 1 in the CDC recommendations: Be ready to take action.
   ``When the problem does arise with suicide clusters, there is
usually a great deal of confusion,'' O'Carroll said in an interview
Thursday. ``This confusion can lead to different sectors of the
community working at cross purposes.''
   The CDC said public and mental health agencies, schools,
government, police, suicide hotlines and even the news media should
cooperate in advance to make plans for their community.
   Then, if a suicide cluster appears to be developing, the
community should work together to cope with its grief while
watching other troubled youths to prevent further deaths, the
report said.
   Though there are as yet no definitive studies of
suicide-prevention approaches, ``I would never advocate doing
nothing,'' O'Carroll said. He said there is ``extremely
compelling'' evidence that suicides can trigger more suicides.
   Only about 5 percent of the 5,000 teen suicides a year in the
United States are believed to be part of ``clusters,'' O'Carroll
said, but those clusters present the best opportunity for action.
   The response to suicide in a community ``has got to be gauged
according to the situation,'' O'Carroll said.
   For example, the suicide of a student at home during a weekend
would not call for ``some kind of enormous SWAT-team approach'' in
school Monday morning, he said. In that case, quiet discussion
would be in order.
   But if three or four suicides occur in a matter of days, ``and
the community is going crazy, in that situation you will do far
more harm than good by trying to play it low-key,'' he said.
   Among other CDC recommendations:
   _Avoid glorifying the victims and their deaths, and minimize
sensationalism.
   _Identify those at high risk and refer them to counseling.
   _Arrange for timely and accurate information flow to news media.
   _Identify elements that might increase suicide attempts and
alter them; i.e., block off places where suicide attempts are
taking place.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0048 </DOCNO>
