<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Airbus     08-26 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Airbus,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air France A320 Flight to Amsterdam Forced To Turn Around</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Airbus A320 jet that suffered mechanical
problems on its inaugural flight in April returned to Paris after
warning lights indicated a fire on board, landing gear problems,
and a computer failure, an Air France spokesman said.
   Air France Flight 914, bound for Amsterdam with 81 passengers,
took off Thursday from Charles De Gaulle Airport about 4 p.m. and a
few minutes later, warning lights indicated failure of the plane's
computers, the spokesman said.
   The A320 is equipped with a ``fly-by-wire'' system that controls
the plane's engines through computers rather than cables.
   A second set of lights indicating a fire in the toilet also
illuminated without apparent cause, the spokesman said, speaking on
condition of anonymity in keeping with company policy.
   As the plane prepared to land, more lights flashed, warning that
the landing gear failed. The pilot made a pass over the airport and
Air France technicians visually confirmed that the landing gear was
in place. The plane landed without further incident, the spokesman
said.
   The passengers went on to Amsterdam aboard other flights.
   The plane, the ``Ville de Paris,'' was the first of the
sophisticated A320s to be delivered to Air France after the plane
was certified for flight on Feb. 26.
   The same plane was delayed because of mechanical problems on its
inaugural flight over Paris in April with then-Premier Jacques
Chirac on board. The half-hour delay led to discussions in the
French press about the wisdom of letting the premier fly on the new
aircraft.
   In June, three passengers were killed when an A320 crashed
during a low-altitude demonstration flight before thousands of
people at an air show in eastern France. An investigation is under
way into the cause of the accident.
   Developed over four years at a cost of nearly $2 billion, the
A320 has been touted by the European consortium Airbus Industrie as
the fastest-selling plane in aircraft history.
   Airbus has received more than 500 orders or letters of intent to
purchase the plane from 21 countries, including the United States,
Canada and Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
