<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeSillers     08-26 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeSillers Spared Jail; Lawyer Says She's Unfairly Maligned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maria DeSillers is an unfairly maligned woman who
handled donations for her dying son as best she could, according to
the lawyer who successfully battled contempt motions that could
have put her in jail.
   The court-appointed curator for Ronnie DeSillers' estate sought
a contempt ruling because Ms. DeSillers has refused to hand over
financial records and items allegedly bought with some of the
$690,000 in donations for the boy.
   But Dade Probate Judge Francis Christie dismissed the contempt
motions Thursday, saying that if Ms. DeSillers gave up the records
they might ``incriminate her'' in criminal probes under way in Dade
and Broward counties.
   ``I'm very happy,'' said Ms. DeSillers, who while awaiting the
ruling gave her age as ``33, the same as Christ when he was
crucified.''
   Curator Karen Gievers, appointed by Christie in March after Ms.
DeSillers' handling of the donations was questioned, contends that
about $200,000 may have been misspent on such purchases as a used
BMW worth $13,500, a diamond-and-sapphire ring, a diamond-studded
gold cross, clothing, furniture and 18 gravesites.
   Lawyers for Ms. Gievers had no comment after Christie's terse
ruling but later requested an emergency hearing today on their
requests to seize disputed belongings of Ms. DeSillers. Also, they
want the judge to strike her $150,000 claim on her son's estate,
said Frank Johnson, another of her attorneys.
   Defense lawyer Roy Black argued during the two-day hearing that
Ms. DeSillers enjoyed a Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination and shouldn't have to give up financial records
or the disputed purchases.
   He also said some of the donations were expressly for his
client's personal expenses.
   ``I'm not saying people gave it for Maria to buy jewelry. If she
bought a pickup truck for $20,000, which is what they cost today,
nobody would have criticized her,'' he told the judge.
   ``You'd think this was `Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous.' This
is not a woman who deserves to be humiliated,'' said Black, adding
that his client was unfairly portrayed as ``greedy and grasping''
when she gave thousands of dollars to poor families with sick
children.
   Ronnie, 7, died in April 1987 at Children's Hospital of
Pittsburgh while awaiting his fourth liver transplant. His plight
made national news after $4,000 raised by his classmates for the
operation was stolen from a school closet.
   Among the donations was $1,000 from President Reagan and
$200,000 from Miami Beach industrialist Victor Posner. About a
third of the donations remain, frozen in the boy's estate.
   Shortly before the ruling, Ms. DeSillers' former fiance, Jose
Castillo, was handcuffed and whisked away as he stepped out of the
courtroom where he had sat supportively behind Ms. DeSillers.
   Castillo hocked two IBM computers, monitors and printers worth
$4,000 at a Broward County pawn shop, Abbey's, which he and Ms.
DeSillers have often used in the past, said Metro-Dade Detective
Barry Garafola. One of the computer sets had been stolen in a March
robbery, and the other has not been traced.
   As he was led away, Castillo termed ``ridiculous'' charges of
grand theft and another of dealing in stolen property. Detectives
could not say if Ms. DeSillers was involved.
   Her handling of the money came under question when the
Pittsburgh hospital sued for the $262,000 balance of the boy's
bill. She refuses to pay, claiming Ronnie received improper care
there, a charge the hospital denies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
