<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     08-26 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Orders Recall of More Than 600,000 GM Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Motors Corp. is recalling more
than 600,000 1983 Oldsmobiles and Buicks to replace an emissions
control component that may have stopped working.
   The Environmental Protection Agency said Thursday a defective
thermal vacuum switch causes the cars to exceed federal standards
on emission of gasoline vapors and carbon monoxide.
   The agency said 613,582 vehicles, all with 5-liter engines, are
involved in the recall. They are the 1983 Oldsmobile Cutlass
Supreme, Cutlass Cruiser, Delta 88, Ninety-Eight, Toronado and
Custom Cruiser, and the 1983 Buick Le Sabre, Estate Wagon, Electra
and Riviera.
   GM said that after years of contact with gasoline the rubber
compounds used to make the vacuum switch deteriorate and allow fuel
vapor to be burned by the engine.
   The defective switch has no effect on the operation of the car,
would take less than one hour to replace GM said. The EPA estimated
the time of repair at 20 minutes.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hotel Chain Drops Ban on Ethnic Hairdos, Starts Recruitment Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hyatt Hotels Corp. which has been hit by
complaints from several employees, says it is dropping its ban on
cornrow hairstyles and has initiated a program to encourage more
minorities to enter the hotel and resort management industry.
   There have been several instances, including one highly
publicized incident in Washington, of Hyatt employees complaining
that prohibiting the tightly braided hairstyle discriminated
against blacks, who consider cornrows part of their ethnic heritage.
   Officials of the District of Columbia Human Rights Office said
Thursday t news conference with Hyatt executives that because of
the policy change it has decided not file a complaint against the
chain.
   ``They (Hyatt officials) exhibited a spirit of cooperation like
no other we've seen,'' said Maudine Cooper, director of the office.
``There were policies against cornrows, but Hyatt has since
eliminated that policy.''
   Hyatt said that as part of the settlement with the city, it was
creating a nationwide college scholarship program in which selected
students at 20 historically black colleges and universities will
have the opportunity to participate in a 10-week paid summer
training program designed to attract minorities to hotel and resort
management.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Envoy Claims Noriega `Weaker By The Day'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition leader claims public support for
Panama's military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega is deteriorating
dramatically.
   ``Noriega's government is weaker by the day. The regime is
fighting for its survival,'' said Ambassador Juan B. Sosa at a news
conference on Thursday to mark six months to the day after Panama's
upheaval began with the failed attempt to oust Noriega as commander
of Panama's Defense Forces.
   Sosa said that a combination of factors had led to a ``dramatic
deterioration'' of Noriega's public support.
   Sosa, who continues to serve as Panama's ambassador to the
United States, retains control over Panama's embassy despite the
Noriega government's attempt to replace him, said public opposition
to Noriega was evident earlier this month when hundreds of
thousands of Panamanians turned out for the funeral of former
President Arnulfo Arias.
   The United States continues to recognize Sosa as Panama's
ambassador and maintains that President Eric Arturo Delvalle, who
was ousted the day after his abortive attempt to fire Noriega, is
the legitimate authority in Panama.
