<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MarilynQuayle     08-26 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marilyn Quayle,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle's Wife: Controversy Is Media Made</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The controversy surrounding Dan Quayle's service
in the National Guard is ``a total creation of the media,'' says
the wife of the Republican vice presidential candidate.
   Marilyn Quayle makes her comments in an interview with Barbara
Walters for the ABC News program ``20-20,'' to be aired tonight,
and in today's editions of The Washington Times.
   ``I anticipated they (the media) would try their hardest to
knock Danny and they have certainly exceeded my wildest dreams,''
Mrs. Quayle told the newspaper in an interview from Boonville, Mo.
   Asked why she thought people are reacting so strongly to the
question of whether Dan Quayle pulled strings to enter the National
Guard at the height of the Vietnam War, Mrs. Quayle said in the
television interview: ``I don't think people are. I think it's a
total creation of the media.''
   Mrs. Quayle added that it had ``crossed her mind'' that
journalists are out to get George Bush's running mate.
   ``I can't substantiate that,'' she said in the television
interview recorded Wednesday. ``I think part of it is just the fact
that there were so many members of the media down in New Orleans
with nothing to do. And they decided they would find a story. And
they looked wherever they thought they could and dug something up.''
   ``They are supposed to be the news gatherers, the disseminators
and not the destroyers,'' Mrs. Quayle told the newspaper.
   She added that her biggest chore has been shielding her three
children _ Tucker 14, Benjamin, 11, and Corinne, 9 _ from the
coverage on television and in the papers and keeping their spirits
high.
</TEXT>
