<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-26 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Tumble, Dollar Slips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plummeted while the dollar also lost
ground in Tokyo trading Friday following key interest rates hikes
in Europe the previous day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 70.77
point-winner Thursday, lost 305.03 points, or 1.09 percent, to
close at 27,565.41.
   The dollar, which opened at 133.58 yen, down from Thursday's
133.76-yen finish, closed the week at 133.50 yen, down 0.26 yen. It
traded mainly between a range of 133.35-.73 yen during the day.
   Dealers said share prices were lower across the board in
cautious, thin trading because of speculation that the United
States might hike its interest rates in response to a round of
European rate hikes on Thursday.
   ``To make things worse, now is the end of the month, when the
trading (in Tokyo) normally slows down,'' said one stock dealer,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   West Germany's Bundesbank raised its discount rate by 0.5
percent to 3.5 percent Thursday to support the mark and curb
inflation. France, Switzerland, the Netherlands and Austria also
raised their official rates, and Britain signaled an increase in
commercial rates.
   The weak dollar in Tokyo widely was attributed to dollar-selling
following a recovery by the mark after the Bundesbank rate hike and
the U.S. currency's subsequent relative decline.
</TEXT>
