<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ChessDefector     08-26 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chess Defector,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romania's Top Chess Player Asks Asylum, Says Romanian Officials
Harassed Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania's top chess player says he has asked for
political asylum, contending Romanian officials harassed him after
he refused to play a tournament in a city he says is contaminated
with radioactive waste.
   ``The (Romanian Chess) Federation wanted to force me to do
things which were against the interests of my health and my
family,'' Mihai Suba told a Thursday news conference in the British
capital, where he is playing a tournament. ``They tried to get to
this point by blackmail, by threatening me.''
   ``It's not a pleasure,'' the 41-year-old chess grandmaster said
of his defection. He has also asked for asylum for his 14-year-old
son Christian, who is accompanying him.
   ``It's a necessity. It was unavoidable. I think it was the last
opportunity, at least with somebody of my family,'' he said.
   His wife, Sanda, 39, and a 9-year-old son, Viktor, remain in the
Romanian capital of Bucharest. He said he hoped his wife would
eventually be able to join him in London.
   He said Romanian authorities tried to punish him because he
refused to compete in a tournament in the Black Sea resort of
Eforia. He claimed the area was contaminated with major radioactive
deposits that threatened the health of the inhabitants.
   Suba also complained that the results of school examinations his
elder son took were lowered to help the children of highly placed
officials. ``I was very upset about this,'' he said.
   Suba told reporters he contacted the United Kingdom Immigrants
Advisory Service, a private organization that helps would-be
immigrants, on Tuesday and mailed an application to the Home
Office, which is in charge of immigration.
   A Home Office spokesman refused to confirm whether the Subas
applied to defect to Britain.
   Suba is ranked 78th in the chess world.
   His decision to defect didn't interfere with his play at the
Lloyds Bank Masters tournament.
   He was leading the 100 players in the tournament after five
rounds on Wednesday, but a loss in the sixth round on Thursday hurt
his chances of picking up the $2,125 first prize. Soviet Vassily
Smyslov, a former world champion, was among those competing.
   The Romanian grandmaster is the latest addition to a list of
celebrated Soviet and Eastern European chess players who have
sought asylum in the West. They include Viktor Korchnoi, who now
lives in Switzerland, and Lev Alburt, the 1986 U.S. champion who
lives in New York.
   Suba, who holds a masters degree in mathematics, said he would
support himself by winning chess prizes and looking for a job in
mathematics or computers. His visa allows him to stay in Britain
until the end of the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
