<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cuba-PoisonGas     08-26 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Poison Gas,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Weekly: Cuba Using Lethal Chemicals Against Angolan Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba is using poison gas to flush out South
African-backed Angolan guerrillas from their rural strongholds,
according to a U.N. expert quoted in a British defense publication.
   Jane's Defense weekly quoted Aubin Heyndrickx, head of
toxicology at the University of Ghent in Belgium and a U.N. expert
on biological and chemical warfare, as saying evidence based on
environmental samples shows Cuba is using the lethal mixture of
mustard gas and nerve gases.
   Soil, leaf and water samples taken from Angolan battle zones in
April showed clear traces of the gases, Heyndrickx was quoted as
saying.
   Jane's Defense weekly is an authoritative publication dealing
with military matters worldwide.
   The attack must have taken place in March or April, Heyndrickx
was quoted as saying, because the nerve gases are extremely
volatile and would not remain in the environment for longer than a
few weeks.
   The professor was quoted as saying he couldn't tell exactly
which nerve gas was used, although he knows it is one of the three
neurotoxins _ Soman, Tabun or Sarin. He did not say if any rebels
were killed by the gas.
   The report came as U.S. mediators were working on a compromise
timetable for a withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
South Africa has promised to pull out its troops from Angola by
Sept. 1 and grant independence to South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia, on condition the Cubans leave.
   Heyndrickx was quoted as saying he is convinced the Cubans are
continuing to uses gases in Angola to help win the war against
rebels of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   ``I'm sure the Cubans will go ahead with this. This is the new
military tactic,'' Jane's quoted him as saying.
   The guerrillas, backed by South Africa and the United States,
have been fighting since 1975 to force the Cuban- and Soviet-backed
Angolan government to share power. The guerrillas control large
portions of southern Angola.
   The professor was quoted as saying he has gas detection kits
captured from Cuban soldiers which are designed to measure whether
levels of poison in the atmosphere are toxic for man.
   A University of Ghent team examined patients in guerrilla field
hospitals and found evidence of nerve gas attacks in 1986 and 1984,
but none of those victims showed any trace of mustard gas, he was
quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
