<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Quayle-Editorial,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Newspaper Urges Quayle To Leave Ticket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Republican vice presidential
nominee Dan Quayle headed to California for a two-day campaign
swing, the Press-Telegram joined the Des Moines Register in urging
him to leave the ticket he shares with Vice President George Bush.
   The Press-Telegram, in an editorial in today's editions, said
allegations about the Indiana senator's military record and his
link to a female lobbyist who appeared nude in Playboy are
distracting voters from the real issues in the election.
   ``If Dan Quayle remains on the Republican ticket, neither Bush
nor the nation will be well served,'' the editorial said.
   The editorial went on: ``Even when the candidates talk about
these issues, they are not heard. Media and public attention
focuses on J. Danforth Quayle, a handsome man with a short,
undistinguished record in the House and Senate and an intolerable
burden as a candidate.''
   The editorial called Quayle hypocritical for styling himself a
hawk on defense issues when he spent the Vietnam War years writing
press releases in the National Guard and imprudent for sharing a
condominium on a golfing trip with two congressional colleagues and
lobbyist Paula Parkinson.
   The editroial suggested possible replacements for Quayle as
Kansas Sen. Robert Dole, New York Rep. Jack Kemp, Indiana Sen.
Richard Lugar, or ``someone else with a deserved reputation for
integrity and leadership.''
