<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0450EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Politics     08-26 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Politics,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Go Back To Work After Opposition Walkout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers facing a Sept. 1 deadline for
certifying a new Chamber of Deputies returned to work early today
before an empty public gallery following a stormy debate that one
legislator said was proof of democracy.
   Opposition legislators walked out just before dawn Thursday
after a rowdy, all-night session of the chamber, sitting as an
electoral college to certify results of the July 6 general election.
   When the meeting resumed, the public galleries were closed,
although the press was allowed in.
   Opposition sympathizers earlier Thursday chanted, whistled,
threw coins and other objects and rose to comment on what in the
past have been staid sessions endorsing sweeping victories by the
governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
   ``Cuauhtemoc won!'' was a frequent chant.
   Presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the leader of a
democratic reform movement, claims the PRI cheated him of victory.
   His supporters form the biggest bloc of opposition legislators
in the chamber, where the PRI must now contend with the strongest
opposition in nearly 60 years.
   The head of the PRI delegation, Guillermo Jimenez Morales, said
the unprecedented debate ``shows clearly that we are living within
a democratic framework.''
   The July 6 elections were tainted by widespread accusations that
the PRI tampered with voter registration rolls, stuffed ballot
boxes and destroyed ballots for opposition candidates.
   Opposition leaders have accused the party of steamroller tactics
to speed vote certification, especially in the chamber.
   ``We have to seek new ways (of protest) because the official
party is legitimizing fraud more and more every day,'' Alfredo
Noyola of the opposition National Action Party said Thursday after
227 opposition delegates walked out, temporarily halting the
chamber's work.
   He accused PRI delegates of rejecting all opposition requests to
investigate fraud. Jimenez Morales denied the charge.
   The body, made up of newly elected or re-elected deputies
themselves, must finish its work by Sept. 1, the date of outgoing
President Miguel de la Madrid's state-of-the-union address.
   The chamber must also certify the presidential election by the
Dec. 1 inauguration day of Carlos Salinas de Gortari, the PRI
candidate.
   If the deadlines aren't met, the PRI will suffer twin
embarrassments. There will be no Chamber of Deputies to sit in
joint session with the Senate for De la Madrid's speech, and he
will be unable to follow the PRI's tradition of formally
introducing the new president.
   Jimenez Morales said Thursday the nation's ``constitutional
order'' will be shattered if the chamber does not finish by Sept. 1.
   The PRI has not lost a presidential election since it was
founded in 1929, but the July 6 balloting marked the first time the
PRI won the presidency with less than 70 percent of the votes cast.
The PRI-dominated Federal Election Commission says Salinas won with
50.36 percent of the vote.
   Cardenas, a former PRI leader who broke away to head the leftist
National Democratic Front coalition, came in second with 31.1
percent. Manuel J. Clouthier of the conservative National Action
Party came in third with 17 percent.
   Also for the first time, the PRI did not win every race for the
64-member Senate. Four opposition senators already have been
certified for their posts. The Senate, sitting as a separate
electoral college, has been meeting routinely.
   Cardenas and Clouthier have urged Mexicans to reject the
election results.
   They have also accused the government of denying the electoral
colleges access to documents from about half the nation's 55,000
polling stations. The government denies the charge.
   On Thursday the PRI majority on the Federal Election Commission
rejected an opposition proposal to let the two electoral colleges
examine the documents. PRI representative David Jimenez said it
wasn't necessary since party representatives saw them on election
day, the Excelsior news service said.
   Soldiers earlier this week blocked opposition deputies from
entering the room where ballots are under guard.
   By law, the deputies- and senators-elect sit as separate
electoral colleges to certify their own elections, and then the
500-member Chamber of Deputies sits as an electoral college to
certify the presidential election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
