<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Stalin'sVictims Bjt   08-26 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stalin's Victims, Bjt,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Discuss Plans for Monument to Stalin's Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pain and suffering were written on the face of
Emmanuel Kotlyar as he stressed to prominent political and cultural
figures the importance of building a center to chronicle the
millions _ like himself _ who fell victim to Josef Stalin.
   The frail man of 80 said he spent 14 years in a labor camp after
being arrested in 1929 on trumped-up charges, and hoped he would
live to see the building completed.
   ``We aren't doing it for us, but for the future generation,'' to
prevent a repetition of the terror, the balding Kotlyar said, his
body shaking, his voice trembling.
   Kotlyar stood with a cane at a microphone Thursday night in a
packed auditorium.
   For 2{ hours, about 200 intellectuals at the Union of Architects
headquarters brainstormed about what a monument to Stalin's victims
should look like, where it should be built and whether it should be
accompanied by a center that would study the repressions.
   No formal program or plan came out of the session, which brought
together the main forces behind the drive to put up a monument to
Stalin's victims: the informal group Memorial, officials of
theatrical, film and architect unions, Ogonyok, and the weekly
newspaper Literaturnaya Gazeta.
   There was no agenda, and those interested in speaking simply
took the microphone.
   ``We are tired of monuments,'' said Kotlyar. ``We have so many
of them. We need a center.''
   One of the center's main tasks, he said, should be to answer the
question of how many people were killed and imprisoned by Stalin
from the 1930s to 1950s.
   Those in the audience included Andrei Sakharov, one of the
founders of the country's dissident movement. Seated nearby was
Sergei Grigoryants, who publishes an unsanctioned journal called
``Glasnost,'' named after Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of openness.
   He received a fresh reminder Sunday, after a demonstration
against the Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia 20 years ago,
that even under Gorbachev, expression of dissident political views
can land a citizen in jail. Grigoryants was among dozens of
demonstrators hauled away to a police station.
   Two popular intellectuals who have used art as axes to chip away
at Stalinism, author Anatoly Rybakov and playwright Mikhail
Shatrov, also attended.
   Last winter, Memorial, a band of scholars, lawyers and history
buffs, took to the streets with a petition drive and demonstrations
that got them detentions, fines and threats. But the crackdown was
halted suddenly this summer.
   With Gorbachev's support, the Communist Party conference that
ended July 1 passed a resolution called for a monument in Moscow to
Stalin's victims, who Western specialists estimate number about 20
million.
   The Union of Architects has since proposed converting a prison
in Sukhanovo, 15 miles east of Moscow, into a complex that would
include a monument, museum and archives containing documents about
the victims.
   Sukhanovo was a monastery before Soviet rule but under Stalin
was used as a prison where inmates were routinely tortured. It is
believed to be run now by the KGB.
   A competition for the design of the memorial complex is to be
held late this year or early next year, and organizers have set up
a special bank account to accept donations from the public to
finance the project.
   Groups in the Baltic republics and the Siberian city of Chita
are raising money for local monuments to Stalin's victims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0064 </DOCNO>
