<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     08-26 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korean Talks Break Down; No More Discussions On Olympics Set</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea and South Korea today failed
to clear the way for full-scale talks on sharing the Olympics and
on a non-aggression pact, and both sides blamed each other for the
breakdown.
   The only agreement after more than three hours of talks was to
meet again Oct. 13 after the Olympics to continue talks on easing
tension.
   The two five-member delegations of legislators shook hands and
smiled before the meeting at the Panmunjom truce site, which
straddles the neutral Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas.
   But delegates later blamed each other for failing to resolve the
dispute over the Olympics, to be held in Seoul Sept. 17-Oct. 2.
   ``It has been confirmed that South Korea attempted to blow away
the Olympic question,'' the chief North Korean delegate, Chon Kum
Chol, told reporters.
   South Korean officials refused to rule out the possibility of a
last-minute bid to get the North to take part in the Games, but
they have rejected the North's demand to be a co-host of the Games.
   ``At this stage one thing is sure, that co-hosting is
impossible,'' said South Korean delegate Lee Han-dong.
   Chon denied the North would attempt to disrupt the Olympics.
South Korea fears its archrival may stage terrorist attacks during
the Games.
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics unless it is
made a co-host. The International Olympic Committee rejected the
demand, saying the Olympics are awarded to a single city and cannot
be shared.
   North Korea insists that full-scale talks should have
non-aggression as their top item. It also demands the full
parliaments of both sides take part, while the South called for
smaller delegations.
   Also disputed is a North Korean demand that the two legislatures
publish a joint declaration of non-aggression, calling for the
withdrawal of 42,000 U.S. troops based in South Korea. South Korea
considers the U.S. military presence essential to its defense.
   The chief South Korean delegate, Park Joon-kyu, told reporters
the talks should not be considered a failure, because the two sides
had agreed to another meeting.
   ``The best thing to come out of this meeting is that we continue
to have talks,'' he said.
   The two Koreas are bitter rivals with hundreds of thousands of
troops facing each other along their tense 150-mile border.
   The peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
pro-Western South Korea at the end of World War II. They fought the
Korean War from 1950 to 1953, which left more than a million people
dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BaikalSwimmer     08-26 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baikal Swimmer,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Woman Completes Swim Across Lake Baikal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American endurance swimmer Lynne Cox crossed
Siberia's Lake Baikal today in four hours and 20 minutes, the
official Tass news agency reported.
   In a brief dispatch from the city of Irkutsk near the
crescent-shaped lake that is the deepest in the world, Tass said
the 31-year-old resident of Los Alamitos, Calif., swam about 11.25
miles in 52-degree water.
   She began at Tolstoy Cap and finished at the lakeside village of
Listvyanka in good physical condition, the news agency said.
   ``It was the first time in history that such a long swim was
accomplished in the icy waters of Baikal,'' Tass said.
   Ms. Cox, who had planned to do the swim Sunday, moved up the
date because of forecasts of bad weather in the lake area next
week. She had been training by staying in Baikal waters for several
hours a day, Tass said.
   Baikal, about 1,800 miles east of Moscow and north of Mongolia,
spans a long narrow valley between mountain ranges and is noted for
severe and changeable weather. The lake holds one-fifth of the
world's fresh water and reaches a depth of 4,800 feet at some
points.
   Ms. Cox has been making long-distance swims for more than a
decade, including crossing the English Channel, the Strait of
Magellan and the Cook Strait.
   Last year she swam 2.7 miles across the frigid Bering Strait to
the Soviet Union's far eastern extreme. She has said her endurance
swim across Lake Baikal was intended to promote U.S.-Soviet
friendship, peace and sports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
