<2ND_LINE>PM-Boat Disaster,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>60 Feared Drowned As Boat Sinks Outside Dhaka</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boat carrying Moslem pilgrims sank
after it was swamped by high waves on the flooded Padma River, and
a newspaper today said that 10 bodies were recovered and 50 others
were feared dead.
   The Bangladesh Observer reported that the boat was carrying 80
villagers to a Moslem holy site 40 miles southwest of Dhaka when it
sank early Wednesday.
   Police sources in Mmanikganj District reached by phone confirmed
that a boat sank Wednesday but did not report any deaths. They
refused to elaborate.
   The paper said 20 passengers were rescued by nearby fishing
boats. It said the 10 bodies were recovered by Thursday night and
50 others were feared drowned.
   Ferry and boat accidents are quite common in Bangladesh. On
Tuesday, a boat hit by a launch sank in the same stretch of the
river and police feared that 21 people were dead.
   Another ferry sank in southern Bangladesh on Monday and at least
50 people were feared dead, according to a newspaper.
   In Bangladesh, officials usually do not confirm deaths in
accidents, although local press reports are not denied.
</TEXT>
