<2ND_LINE>PM-Angola-Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0451,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Mediators Push Compromise Plan On Cuban Withdrawal From
Angola</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE on compromise plan for Cuban
withdrawal within 18 months, details; pickup 9th graf pvs, In
Windhoek ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. mediators are working on a
compromise plan for 50,000 Cuban troops to withdraw from Angola
within 18 months, sources close to negotiations between South
Africa, Angola and Cuba said.
   But the plan, offered during talks scheduled to conclude today,
is likely to be unacceptable to the Angolans and Cubans who were
insisting on a minimum of two years, the sources said. They spoke
Thursday on condition of anonymity.
   South Africa has promised to pull its troops out of Angola by
Sept. 1 and grant independence to Angola's southern neighbor,
South-West Africa, within a year, as long as the Cubans withdraw.
   The Marxist Angolan government publicly has offered to send the
Cubans home in four years.
   On Thursday, the four parties did not meet together, leaving the
Americans to work out a compromise proposal.
   Chester Crocker, secretary of state for Africa affairs, said the
talks ``were well on their way,'' though it is ``too soon to
anticipate their results.'' He commented in an interview with Congo
radio broadcast Thursday.
   Crocker said all parties had ``adopted a serious and
constructive approach'' for the conference.
   Diplomats refused to discuss details of the talks or say whether
new proposals for the Cuban withdrawal were offered.
   The Cubans back Angola's Marxist government in a 13-year-old war
with U.S.- and South African-supported rebels.
   In Windhoek, South-West Africa, the South African-led
territorial army said Thursday that it will lift a 7-year-old
overnight curfew in the northern war zone on Sept. 1.
   The curfew will not be reimposed if pro-independence guerrillas
of the South-West African People's Organization adhere to their
offer to observe a cease-fire beginning Sept. 1, a military
statement said.
   The curfew was imposed in 1981 throughout Ovamboland, the
northernmost and most populous region of South-West Africa, which
is also known as Namibia.
</TEXT>
