<2ND_LINE>PM-Crack Ads,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crack Dealers Using Business Cards, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the classic capitalist manner, drug dealers
have begun to advertise the quality of their product and its easy
availability using business cards, police said.
   ``Their business cards say how good (the drugs) are and that
they want a nice quick transaction,'' said Lt. Michael Geraghty,
head of the Tactical Narcotics Team in southeast Queens.
   ``Most of the time the cards say what they are selling and where
and when it can be bought. Some of the cards have telephone
numbers.''
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward, at a luncheon interview
Thursday at the New York Post, also displayed a flier that exhorts
``kids'' to ``earn big bucks'' by becoming ``Crack-er Jack
Salesman.'' He noted, however, that the flier might be bogus.
   Ward appealed for support for a plan to create five more
Tactical Narcotics Teams to spread throughout the city. Mayor
Edward I. Koch is asking for $110 million for his plan to crack
down on drugs.
   The Queens team was formed after the execution-style killing of
rookie Officer Edward Byrne in February as he guarded the home of a
drug-case witness.
