<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TysonScuffle     08-26 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tyson Scuffle,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Green Drops Charges Against Tyson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boxer Mitch Green has dropped assault charges
against world heavyweight boxing champ Mike Tyson stemming from a
scuffle outside a clothing store, saying he hopes they will settle
their differences in the ring.
   Green arrived at a Harlem precinct with his lawyer David Lee on
Thursday, told police ``I'm dropping the charges,'' and left
without giving a reason for his decision, said a police spokesman,
Sgt. John Clifford.
   But outside the station, Green taunted Tyson, chanting ``Sissy,
Sissy,'' as he was booed by a pro-Tyson neighborhood crowd.
   Green, who once fought for the U.S. Boxing Association
heavyweight title and lost in the ring to Tyson two years ago, told
police Tyson knocked him down with a punch during a pre-dawn
scuffle Tuesday outside a Harlem haberdashery.
   ``Mike Tyson hit me and ran like a sissy,'' he told reporters
during a news conference, adding that Tyson hit him after he told
the champ he did not fight hard in their 1986 bout because he had
been cheated by promoter Don King.
   Tyson's description, issued a few hours later, was equally
succinct: ``He hit me first, I hit back and the fight was over ...
faster than Spinks,'' a reference to Tyson's first-round knockout
of Michael Spinks earlier this year.
   Tyson fractured a bone in his hand when he hit Green, placing in
jeopardy his title defense against Britain's Frank Bruno, scheduled
for Oct. 8.
   In his statement, Tyson dismissed Green as ``a punk and a true
coward'' who filed a criminal complaint as ``a publicity stunt.''
   ``I can beat this guy anytime, anywhere, any place,'' Tyson
boasted. ``I will teach him a lesson in the ring that he should
have learned already.''
   But first, he said, Green would have to survive ``some good
tough preliminary fights so that he's ranked again.''
   Tyson's manager Bill Cayton said a rematch would be ``absolutely
a very attractive fight.''
   Cayton told the Daily News that Green, paid just $30,000 to
Tyson's $250,000 despite a higher ranking at the time, ``deserves a
break.''
   In August 1987, Green was arrested after police found drugs in
his car and that his license had been suspended 54 times. A week
later, he was arrested and charged with disorderly conduct and
driving while intoxicated after he refused to pay a bridge toll.
</TEXT>
