<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0709EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Crossroads 1stLd-Writethru a0460 08-26 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Crossroads, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha Welcomed In Black Settlement Once Targeted For Demolition</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with Botha visit. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CROSSROADS, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since it mushroomed overnight on
Easter 1974, this black shantytown has been visited regularly by
police, bulldozers and eviction agents.
   Today, in what aides called a symbolic move, President P.W.
Botha visited the settlement outside Cape Town that his government
tried so many times to destroy.
   Each time, the shacks of plastic sheeting and corrugated tin
were smashed. Each time, they reappeared in a different sandy
field. Each time, truckloads of women and children were carted away
to rural homelands, separated from the men who had jobs in Cape
Town. Thousands more families replaced them.
   Botha, making one of his few visits to a black township in his
10 years as South Africa's head of state, was loudly cheered when
he arrived at the long-troubled area that the government is now
trying to develop for blacks who fought anti-apartheid activists.
   ``Thank you, we accept you as our leader,'' a black choir sang
in the Xhosa language.
   The group said they made up the song for Botha's visit to
Crossroads, where dozens of people were killed and 70,000 people
left homeless during unrest in May and June of 1986.
   Botha stopped at a recently established employment center, where
appointed Mayor Johnson Ngxobongwana welcomed the president ``in
the name of all Crossroads residents.''
   Not everyone was happy about Botha's visit. Jan van Eck, an
anti-apartheid member of Parliament, said of Crossroads, ``The
black community that rejects an Archbishop (Desmond) Tutu and
accepts into its midst the oppressor, Mr. P.W. Botha, is far
removed from the rest of the oppressed people of South Africa.''
   He was referring to graffiti on a wall near the main entrance to
Crossroads that says: ``No entry for Tutu'' _ the black Anglican
leader who won the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize for his fight against
apartheid, under which the black majority has no voice in national
affairs.
   Mayor Ngxobongwana headed so-called vigilantes from the oldest
section of Crossroads who burned down neighborhoods in 1986 where
militant young anti-apartheid activists held sway.
   The government is building new homes for Ngxobongwana's
supporters, while most of his displaced opponents have moved where
the government wanted them _ a massive black township called
Khayelitsha, farther from Cape Town.
   Botha said the employment center was an example of his
government's attempts to develop black areas.
   ``To boycott is easy, but it leads nowhere,'' Botha told about
200 people in the center. ``To cooperate is sometimes difficult and
to take responsibility sometimes difficult. But history remembers
only those who build, not those who destroy.''
   The center is used to train unemployed people in carpentry,
bricklaying, sewing and other skills.
   The shantytown's troubled history centers around the
white-dominated government's former policy that people of
mixed-race had preference over blacks for all jobs in the Cape Town
region and that blacks lived there only as temporary workers.
   Crossroads was born as a result of the government's attempt to
remove several ``black spots,'' where blacks lived illegally.
   When three such areas were demolished in 1974, residents packed
their few possessions and moved, but only as far as an intersection
near Cape Town's airport.
   By 1976, Crossroads was a squatter city of 60,000 people, and
the government declared it an ``emergency camp.'' Subsequent
demolitions and evictions failed to stem its growth.
   In 1984, Botha abandoned the idea that the Cape should be a
job-preference area for mixed-race people and promised a halt to
forced removals for race separation purposes.
   By 1986, an estimated 200,000 blacks were living in Crossroads'
slums.
   But during a four-week period in May and June that year, battles
broke out between factions in different neighborhoods. Scores of
people died, and 70,000 were burned out of their shacks.
   Residents and community workers said police aided the so-called
vigilantes from the oldest section of Crossroads, who burned down
neighborhoods where militant young anti-apartheid activists lived.
   Critics charged that the 1986 violence was part of a government
plan to clear out overcrowded slums so they could be rebuilt with
lower density while troublemakers were moved farther away.
   The Cape Town Supreme Court is hearing the first of more than
3,000 damage suits by those who lost their homes. They charge the
police and government with responsibilty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0081 </DOCNO>
