<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia-Rebels     08-26 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Rebels,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Stage Deadliest Raid In Years; 39 Reported Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 leftist guerrillas destroyed a
military base and police headquarters in a village attack that
killed 39 people, the deadliest raid by guerrillas in several
years, the Defense Ministry said.
   A ministry statement said Thursday that 15 guerrillas, 12
civilians, 10 soldiers and two policemen were killed. At least 10
civilians and soldiers were wounded and an unknown number were
missing after Wednesday's raid, the communique said.
   The Defense Ministry said the rebels from the Maoist People's
Liberation Army and the pro-Soviet Colombian Revolutionary Armed
Forces ambushed two security force patrols outside Saisa, a village
of 1,200 residents about 250 miles north of Bogota.
   Ten soldiers and two policemen died, the ministry said.
   Civilians in Saisa joined 15 soldiers that remained in the
village to battle the guerrillas for four hours. The battle left 15
guerrillas and 12 civilians dead, the statement said.
   The statement said civilian victims of the guerrilla attack
included a woman and her two small children who were burned alive.
   The ministry said reinforcements were sent Thursday to the area
but it was not immediately known if there was any new fighting.
   The attacks came as armed groups and the government of President
Virgilio Barco made moves to begin a new peace process. Guerrillas
have been fighting to overthrow Colombia's government for 30 years.
</TEXT>
