<HEAD>Peacekeepers Find Car Laden With Explosives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unidentified driver abandoned an
explosive-laden car near a U.N. peacekeeping checkpoint in south
Lebanon today and surrendered to Israeli-allied militiamen,
security sources said.
   A source said the driver surrendered to the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army militia shortly after parking the red Renault car near
a checkpoint manned by Fijian peacekeepers of the U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the driver
turned himself in to authorities on the northern edge of Israel's
self-proclaimed security zone. He did not elaborate.
   A UNIFIL spokesman said Fijian soldiers found the car rigged
with ``a quantity of explosives'' within yards of the Fijian
checkpoint, five miles south of this southern port city. He spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   He said UNIFIL's Swedish engineers would safely detonate the car
later in the day.
   A Lebanese car exploded near an Israeli army jeep in south
Lebanon on Aug. 19, killing its driver and a passenger and slightly
wounding three Israeli servicemen.
   A military source in Jerusalem said the car, also a Renault,
exploded about 40 yards from the jeep. He said it was not clear
whether the car was rigged with explosives or hit a mine.
