<1ST_LINE>r i PM-WestAfricaRains 1stLdWritethru a0539 08-26 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-West Africa Rains, 1st Ld Writethru, a0539,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 50 Dead In Heaviest Rains In 20 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to correct verb tense. Picks up graf 2 pvs, `The
Sahel ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heaviest rainfall in 20 years
has drenched much of West Africa, causing widespread damage and at
least 50 deaths, officials say.
   The Sahel states, impoverished nations on the southern fringe of
the Sahara Desert that have suffered recurring droughts for most of
the last 20 years, have received the heaviest rainfall, said Benoi
Cortier of AGHRY-Met, an agricultural research center in the Niger
capital of Niamey.
   Cortier, interviewed by telephone, said Thursday that the
rainfall zone extends from Mauritania along the West African coast
more than 2,400 miles to the Congo. It also stretches as far inland
to Chad, he said.
   Cortier said despite the damage caused by the rainfall that the
region should generally have a better harvest year than in recent
years.
   Since the rainy season began in June, the most rainfall in the
region was reported at a station in Guinea-Bissau, which received
56 inches. Most of the Sahel nations have received more than their
annual average rainfall the past three months.
   Niger, for example, received 27.4 inches, compared with an
annual average 22.4 inches. Rainfall in Nigeria this month was the
heaviest since 1928, the Ministry of Water Resources said.
   The Niger River overflowed, blocking many roads and leaving many
villages isolated. The only feasible transport in some areas was
the pirogue, a canoe-shaped boat.
   Nigeria reported the most damage in West Africa, with thousands
of homes destroyed in Kano and Borno states in the country's
northeast. More than 300,000 people were made homeless, the
military government said.
   The News Agency of Nigeria reported up to 50 deaths in Kano in
the first week of August and 26 deaths the following week in Borno
state.
   Chad reported eight deaths and 48 people injured when their
houses collapsed Tuesday in the capital N'djamena. Homes also were
destroyed in Ouninga Kebir, in the desert north near Libya.
Cameroon reported 1,000 homeless after heavy rains this week. It
had reported two deaths after torrential rains a week earlier.
Burkina Faso also has reported several deaths.
   Heavy rains also were reported in Timbuktu in Mali and in parts
of Senegal.
</TEXT>
