<HEAD>Bible-Quoting Kids Promise To Stop Shouting Scripture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three street-preaching youngsters who have
been repeatedly suspended from school for shouting sermons will be
taught at home and have agreed to no longer preach on school
grounds, officials say.
   The Strode children _ Duffey, 11, Pepper, 7 and Matthew, 6 _
left Eastfield Elementary School this week to begin home
instruction, after another confrontation the first day of school.
Each had been suspended five times last spring for shouting Bible
verses outside school or for refusing to enter the building.
   Their father, David Stode, had said Wednesday they would
continue to preach at school despite the agreement to have them
taught at home. But after four hours of negotiations Wednesday
night, McDowell County school Superintendent David Ricketts
announced a new agreement.
   ``We have reached a new level of trust and understanding,''
Ricketts said. ``The Strodes have agreed not to preach or disturb
our schools, not even to preach at ball games.''
   In return, Ricketts said, school officials have dropped attempts
to get Strode to sign a release absolving the schools from
litigation.
   ``They have no desire to sue us and we certainly have no desire
to sue them,'' Ricketts said.
   Barry Weaver of Black Mountain, who has been street preaching
with Strode, took part in the negotiations.
   ``I said ... `You got to understand me and Dave. When we look at
you, we don't see lawyer and Ricketts. We see the Devil,''' Weaver
said. ```Everything we deal with has to be in that Bible. If it
ain't in the Bible, it don't exist. So Dave ain't gonna sign your
paper. But just leave him alone, let him teach his kids at home and
everything will work out fine.' And that was it.''
</TEXT>
