<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AdapterRecall     08-26 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Adapter Recall,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio Shack Recalls Electrical Adapters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Shack is recalling outlet adapters, sold
since 1987 for use in operating electrical appliances overseas,
because the adapters may pose a shock hazard, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission reports.
   The adapters allow a voltage converter to be plugged into
foreign electrical outlets, allowing the use of American appliances
on foreign electrical systems.
   However, the adapters can separate from the base when pulled
from an outlet, exposing the user to possible electrical shock, the
safety commission said.
   Sets of four adapters were sold nationally under the ``Archer''
brand name for $7.95. Owners were urged to discontinue use of the
adapters and return them to any Radio Shack store for a refund.
   People needing more information can contact the commission at
1-800-638-2772.
</TEXT>
