<DOCNO> AP880826-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0936EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PornProsecution     08-26 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Porn Prosecution,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Court Bars Prosecution of Filmmaker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citing freedom of expression, the
California Supreme Court has barred the use of pandering laws to
prosecute a filmmaker whose cast performed sex acts on camera.
   The prosecution under pandering laws, which forbid the procuring
of prostitutes for pay, ``must be viewed as a somewhat transparent
`end run' around the First Amendment and the state obscenity
laws,'' Justice Marcus Kaufman said in Thursday's unanimous
decision.
   He also said pandering laws, if allowed in such cases and
applied to their limits, could be used against ``films of
unquestioned artistic and social merit, as well as films made for
medical or educational purposes.''
   Only a handful of pending prosecutions were directly affected by
the case. But lawyers said prosecutors in several counties were
following the ruling closely and would have been prepared to file
similar charges against local sex-film makers if the court had
allowed it.
   ``If they couldn't get a conviction under the obscenity section,
this (pandering) was the only thing left,'' said Stuart Goldfarb, a
lawyer for producer Harold Freeman, the defendant in the case. He
said there had been no attempt to prove that Freeman's movie,
``Caught from Behind, Part II,'' was obscene.
   Freeman was convicted of pandering for paying the cast in the
September 1983 movie to engage in sexual acts on film. Although the
pandering law requires at least a three-year prison sentence, the
judge said prison was unwarranted in Freeman's case and gave him 90
days in jail; that sentence, challenged by the prosecutor, was
never served.
   Kaufman gave two reasons for overturning the conviction:
Freeman's conduct was not covered by the pandering laws; and, if
the laws had applied, they would be unconstitutional in his case.
   The cast of the film was paid for acting, and not for ``sexual
arousal or gratification,'' so they were not prostitutes and
Freeman's hiring of them was not pandering, Kaufman said.
</TEXT>
