<HEAD>Three Killed When Plane Hits Shopping Center</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Police did ...' to insert that pilot died in
crash.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane that crashed into a
shopping center, killing three people and igniting a fire that
destroyed four stores, had been unable to gain altitude after
taking off, an investigator said.
   ``He didn't get very high, maybe 100 to 150 feet at the most,''
said Bruce Hill, an accident investigator with the National
Transportation Safety Board.
   The twin-engine Piper Aerostar broke through the roof of a print
shop Thursday afternoon and sent workers and passers-by fleeing.
One worker in the rear of the shop suffered severe burns and was in
critical condition today.
   According to witnesses and FAA reports, the six-seat plane
piloted by Lewis E. Phillips of Fort Lauderdale took off about 3:30
p.m. and circled several times before clipping power lines and
plunging into the strip shopping plaza, about a mile from the
runway.
   Phillips died in the crash; police did not immediately release
the names of the two passengers killed. All three victims were
burned beyond recognition, said police Lt. Tom Walsh.
   Damage to the shopping center was estimated at about $1 million.
   Residents and officials called for a probe into safety at North
Perry Airport, which is surrounded by densely populated
neighborhoods in this community 15 miles north of Miami. Four
people were killed in 16 collisions linked to the airport since
1982, not counting Thursday's crash.
   FAA spokesman Charles Wright in Atlanta said no flight plan was
filed and the plane's destination was unknown.
</TEXT>
