<2ND_LINE>PM-Papal Bills,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Departments Still Trying To Collect On Papal Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Pontiac has negotiated a
settlement for security costs incurred during Pope John Paul II's
visit to Oakland County last year, but local police departments
have yet to see any money.
   The tab for security and traffic control for the papal Mass at
the Pontiac Silverdome Sept. 19 was almost $50,000.
   Police from Pontiac, Auburn Hills, Waterford Township and
Bloomfield Township provided security for the Mass, attended by
90,000 people.
   In a settlement negotiated between the city of Pontiac and the
Pontiac Stadium Building Authority, each police department will be
paid half the cost of services, Pontiac Police Chief Reginald
Turner said.
   The partial payments were reasonable because of the stadium's
``economic hardship,'' Turner said.
   Other than Pontiac, none of the communities that provided police
protection was included in the negotiations, and Turner said he
still needs to contact each department concerning the settlement.
   ``The Archdiocese (of Detroit) originally committed to pay for
reasonable security costs,'' he said. ``The stadium did not collect
from the archdiocese _ the sponsor of the event.''
   The church never promised to repay the police for security or
traffic costs, said Jay Berman, spokesman for the archdiocese,
adding that the protection would be provided for any visiting head
of state.
</TEXT>
