<DOCNO> AP880826-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LuccheseTrial     08-26 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucchese Trial,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations In Longest Running Racketeering Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury resumed deliberations today on
racketeering charges against 20 men in what authorities call the
nation's longest federal criminal trial, which has had more than a
year of testimony and evidence.
   Prosecutors charge the defendants constituted the hierarchy of
the New Jersey faction of the Lucchese organized crime family. The
organization allegedly ran loan-sharking, drug-dealing, illegal
gambling and fraudulent credit card operations, the government says.
   The principal defendant is reputed crime family captain Anthony
``Tumac'' Accetturo of Hollywood, Fla., who allegedly controlled
the New Jersey faction.
   The trial, which began with jury selection in November 1986,
frequently has been characterized by courtroom outbursts, wrangling
among the attorneys and delays needed to sort problems created by
the multitude of defendants.
   That atmosphere carried over to the first day of deliberations
Thursday, when the jury asked its first question just 10 minutes
after beginning work, asking for a copy of the indictment and
transcripts of opening arguments, and the lawyers began arguing
about how much should be given to the panel.
   U.S. District Judge Harold A. Ackerman rapped his gavel and
said: ``I've asked you in the nicest way, three times. Please be
quiet!''
   The jury's indictment question was resolved when lawyers learned
that the jury already had a copy of it, along with a roomful of
exhibits, but didn't know it was there.
   Two hours later, when the transcripts issue was near resolution,
the jury sent back another note: ``Cancel request.''
   All 20 defendants are named in the first count, charging a
conspiracy to violate the federal Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt
Organizations law.
   According to the Administrative Office of the Courts in
Washington, the trial is believed to be the nation's longest
federal criminal proceeding, surpassing the so-called ``Pizza
Connection'' heroin smuggling case that ended after 17 months in
March 1987.
   The trial, which yielded more than 40,000 pages of transcripts,
850 exhibits and testimony by 89 witnesses, ended 22 months and
four days after the first of 1,500 people reported to court for
jury selection.
</TEXT>
