<HEAD>One Palestinian Wounded, One Dies; Sharon Responds To U.S. Trade
Review</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS 9 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from Shamir, details.
Picks up 6th pvs, `Israel's right-wing ...' Edits thereafter to
trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man opened fire on fellow Palestinians
blocking a West Bank road and wounded a 14-year-old boy, witnesses
and army officials said today.
   Another 14-year-old, Aymen Yammen, died today from a gunshot
wound he suffered Aug. 15 during clashes in the West Bank village
of Tal near Nablus, officials at Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital said.
   His death brought to 254 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising began Dec. 8. Four Israelis have died.
   The army maintained curfews on six towns and refugee camps in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   It also closed a trade union in Arab east Jerusalem for a year,
alleging its members held meetings to initiate anti-Israeli
protests, a spokesman said. It was the 10th union to be closed
since the Arab uprising began Dec. 8.
   Meanwhile, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said he sees ``positive
elements'' in the Palestine Liberation Organization plan to declare
a provisional government in the occupied territories, the daily
Maariv newspaper reported.
   ``The PLO is declaring its total failure in bringing about the
destruction of Israel,'' Maariv quoted Shamir as telling aides this
week. ``It is reaching a conclusion that we should be confronted on
the political level.
   ``Secondly, the PLO's recognition of Israel, no matter inside
what borders, will influence radical Arab states and push them to
accept Israel's very existence ... and maybe to direct negotiations
with Israel,'' Shamir was quoted as saying.
   Israel's right-wing Trade and Industry Minister Ariel Sharon
rejected an upcoming U.S. review of Israel's duty-free privileges
in response to alleged abuses of Palestinian workers' rights.
   Sharon alleged Palestinian trade unions are ``cover-ups for
terror organizations. They are not innocent workers' unions but
front organizations behind which the PLO's political arm has been
hiding for years.''
   The American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, a
pro-Palestinian lobby in Washington, has accused Israel of
indiscriminately closing down union offices, arresting Arab labor
activists and denying trade union protection to at least 100,000
Arabs in the territories who travel to jobs in Israel.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said Thursday he would
review Israel's duty-free trade status following the complaint,
which was filed in June.
   Sharon said: `We shall explain to our American friends that when
it comes to the lives of Jews, Israel would not be pressured by
economic sanctions.'' A country found to have abused worker rights
risks losing its rights to export products to the United States
free of charge under the Generalized System of Preferences (GSP).
In 1987, Israel exported $487 million worth of goods under the GSP
program.
   The shooting incident occured after youths manning the roadblock
in Ramallah attacked the Arab late Thursday because they suspected
him of collaborating with Israel, radio reports said. Only Arabs
who provide information to authorities are granted permission to
carry a weapon.
   But an Arab witness said the Arabs were arguing with the man
because he demanded to pass through their barricade.
   He said the man approached the barricade in his car, demanding
it be removed. When Arab youths refused and started to argue, ``He
just grabbed a pistol and shot the boy,'' said the witness, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The clash followed three attacks on suspected collaborators in
the last two days.
</TEXT>
