<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KodakContamination     08-26 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak Contamination,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Says It Won't Honor EPA Subpoena</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. has refused to honor a
second federal subpoena for information on contamination and
chemical use at a manufacturing plant because the request is too
broad, company spokesmen said.
   Kodak sent a letter Thursday to the Environmental Protection
Agency's regional headquarters in New York offering to ``sit down
and meet with them'' about the lastest subpoena, company spokesman
Paul Allen said Thursday night. ``What we need to do is find out
exactly what they want.''
   The new subpoena orders a Kodak vice president and other company
representatives to appear Tuesday before EPA officials in
Rochester. The Kodak officials were to give sworn testimony and
produce documents. The company received the subpoena Wednesday.
   Kodak earlier this month refused to honor a subpoena that
demanded documents concerning chemical spills and storage at Kodak
Park, a manufacturing area for the production of film and
photographic paper. It stretches over more than 7 miles of the city
and employs more than 30,000 people.
   The EPA action was prompted after Kodak notified the state
Department of Environmental Conservation earlier this year that its
own monitoring of groundwater had turned up low levels of
contamination at its property line. Kodak has contended that there
could be no health hazard to residents of surrounding homes because
of the low and deep levels of the contamination it found.
   The EPA, which issued the subpoenas, can ask a federal judge to
order Kodak to answer them. If ordered to comply and Kodak still
refused, the company could be held in contempt of court, EPA
spokewoman Kim Helper said.
</TEXT>
