<DOCNO> AP880826-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TMICleanup     08-26 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TMI Cleanup,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Store Unit 2 For 30 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report filed with the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission proposes sealing the crippled Three Mile
Island Unit 2 reactor for 30 years after the conclusion of a $1
billion cleanup, GPU Nuclear Corp. said.
   GPU, which oversees the two nuclear plants on Three Mile Island,
said in a statement Thursday the long-term storage of Unit 2 would
prevent exposing cleanup workers to radiation.
   As early as 1986, GPU outlined a plan for mothballing TMI-2.
However, the filing of the safety-evaluation report with the NRC
represents the first time the utility has formally specified a
30-year storage period following the conclusion of the 10-year
cleanup, said Doug Bedell, a company spokesman.
   The safety report is an elaboration of the earlier proposal, he
said.
   TMI-2 has been shut down since March 1979, when a combination of
human and mechanical errors led to a partial melting of the
reactor's nuclear fuel. The cleanup at the site is scheduled to end
next year.
   More than 99 percent of the radioactive fuel will be removed
from the plant, but some areas will remain too contaminated for
human entry.
   Over a 30-year period, exposure levels for cesium-137, the
dominant remaining isotope, would be reduced in half, the report
said.
   ``Although it would be possible to continue decontamination of
the facility, this effort would not appreciably enhance the overall
stability and maintainability of the facility nor would it add to
the overall margin of safety for the public,'' the report said.
   Further work beyond the end of the planned cleanup ``would
result in unnecessary additional occupational exposure to personnel
who would be conducting the decontamination tasks,'' the report
said.
   GPU officials previously outlined a plan for decommissioning the
Unit 2 reactor jointly with its sister plant, TMI-1, when that
plant is ready to be retired from service.
   Decommissioning is the final stage in a plant's life and
involves removing a plant from service and ensuring that any
residual radioactivity is reduced to levels that permit
unrestricted use of the site.
</TEXT>
