<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Earthquake 2ndLd-Writethru a0536 08-26 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earthquake, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0536,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Legislator Beaten by Rivals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede KATMANDU
^Eds: Leads throughout with mourners parading body of legislator
killed distributing supplies to quake victims, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BHAKTAPUR, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battered body of a former legislator
was paraded through the streets of this medieval town today, one
day after he was fatally beaten by political rivals while
distributing food and blankets to victims of a killer earthquake.
   ``Hang the murderers,'' scores of young men chanted as they
marched in front of a jeep bearing the body of Karna Hyanju, once a
sympathizer of the now-outlawed Communist Party.
   Officials say the earthquake that rocked parts of Nepal and
India last Sunday killed at least 869 people, including seven in
Bhaktapur.
   Witnesses said Hyanju was beaten with umbrellas and sticks
Thursday afternoon, then dragged through the streets for two hours
before police intervened. He died today at Bir Hospital in
Katmandu, 7 miles west of Bhaktapur.
   Uttam Dhaubanjar, a 28-year-old bank employee and neighbor of
the dead man, said Hyanju was distributing blankets, milk and other
foodstuffs in Bhaktapur when he was accosted by a group of men who
accused him of giving relief materials to his own supporters and
ignoring others.
   ``People started beating him with umbrellas,'' Dhaubanjar said.
``There were a lot of scratches on his body, and a lot of blood. It
looked like one ear was missing. Then they made a necklace of their
shoes, put it around his neck and pulled him through the streets.''
   Hyanju served in the assembly from 1981 until 1986 when he lost
the backing of the one-time Communists in Bhaktapur, traditionally
a leftist stronghold.
   Bhaktapur, a 12th-century town of ancient Hindu temples, has a
population of about 50,000. As Hyanju's body was taken through the
winding streets en route to the cremation ground, thousands of
people jammed streets, temple steps and balconies of brick and mud
houses.
   Meanwhile, reports of earthquake damage continued to arrive from
remote parts of the country today. The Home Affairs Ministry said
the confirmed death toll in Nepal had reached 673.
   The official death toll in India was 196, but survivors, news
media and opposition politicians claim the government tally is far
too low and that the actual toll in India could reach 1,500.
   Sunday's earthquake registered 6.5 on the Richter scale, which
records energy released by a tremor according to ground motion
measured by a seismograph. A reading of 6 means the quake can cause
severe damage, while 7 signifies a major quake.
   In another development, Mother Teresa arrived unheralded
Thursday night at Katmandu's airport with food for earthquake
victims in the Himalayas.
   While others go through official aid channels, the 1979 Nobel
Peace Prize winning nun simply flew into the Nepalese capital 550
pounds of powdered milk and tins of biscuits.
   ``We have to show our love for the people, no?'' the 78-year-old
nun said.
   Mother Teresa, who runs a home for the dying in Calcutta, India,
said she would consult her fellow nuns of the Missionaries of
Charity in Katmandu before setting out to meet earthquake victims.
   Her shoulders hunched, her blue cardigan buttoned to her throat
over her blue-bordered white sari, she was ushered into the
airport's VIP lounge by a staffer from Indian Airlines and promptly
started asking how one could reach the quake-stricken areas.
   ``They didn't charge me overweight,'' she said. ``They never do.
I always travel with a big amount.''
   Several international relief organizations have offered to
provide aid for earthquake victims in Nepal, but their
representatives in Katmandu said they were still awaiting word from
the government on what was needed.
   Agencies already operating in Nepal, including UNICEF, have
supplied medical teams and medicine.
   The British government has sent supplies to eastern Nepal, the
hardest hit region, where it has several projects.
   RSS, Nepal's official news agency, said Thursday night the
Japanese government will provide $150,000 worth of tents, blankets,
medicine, biscuits and powdered milk.
   The United States provided $25,000 in immediate funds available
in Katmandu and is awaiting word on further needs. The U.S. Embassy
in New Delhi provided the same amount for Indian victims of the
quake.
   The European Economic Community today approved about $330,000 in
emergency aid for the quake victims. The 12-member trading bloc
said in a statement that the money was ``destined to finance
internal transportation of international aid and eventually other
essential assistance.''
</TEXT>
