<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Djibouti-PlaneCrash     08-26 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Djibouti-Plane Crash,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Repatriating POWs Crash Lands At Djibouti Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jet charted by the Red Cross to repatriate
Ethiopian and Somalian prisoners of war and civilian internees
crash-landed at Djibouti airport today, slightly injuring 20 of the
190 people on board, the International Committee of the Red Cross
said.
   The Boeing 707 was making its sixth flight in three days between
Mogadishu, Somalia, and Dire Dawa, Ethiopia, when the front landing
gear failed. The plane made a forced landing at Djibouti airport
with only the rear landing gear functioning, Red Cross information
officer Jette Soerensen said.
   The Red Cross said it hopes to resume repatriation flights early
next week, when another plane will be available. The effort to
return 3,700 Ethiopian and Somalians to their homelands began Aug.
23 and was expected to take about 10 days.

