<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RefereeKilling     08-26 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Referee Killing,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Referee Killed For Disputed Call At Game Reportedly Sponsored By
Crack Gang</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The referee of a basketball game sponsored by
drug dealers in a city park was beaten to death over a bad call,
according to a report published today.
   The victim, an elementary school gym teacher described as a man
who devoted himself to children, apparently didn't realize who
sponsored the game, New York Newsday reported.
   The paper quoted unnamed sources as saying that the Supreme
Team, a crack gang that controls the Baisley Park housing project
in Queens, got the game up as a ``public service.''
   Greg Vaughn, 33, was killed in a park near the project when a
player, apparently angry about a call, struck him over the head the
night of July 30, police spokesman Sgt. Norris Hollomon confirmed.
   Vaughn had volunteered to referee the game at a playground a few
blocks from his home, Hollomon said. No arrests have been made.
   Capt. Joseph Hardiman, a Queens detective division commander,
was quoted by the paper as saying Vaughn apparently wasn't involved
in drugs and ``had the reputation of being a great guy.''
   Friends told Newsday that Vaughn tried to use sports to keep
drug-prone kids out of trouble.
   ``He really wanted to make a difference in kids' lives,'' said
Karen Dunston, who worked with Vaughn during his five years as
basketball coach at Medgar Evers College in Brooklyn, a post he
held along with his elementary school job.
</TEXT>
