<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shooting-Arrest     08-26 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shooting-Arrest,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wells Fargo Defendant Rearrested For Allegedly Shooting Federal
Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Puerto Rican nationalist facing trial
in the 1983 robbery of $7 million from a Wells Fargo depot has been
rearrested on charges that he shot an FBI agent in Puerto Rico when
he was arrested in 1985, officials said today.
   Filiberto Ojeda Rios was arrested in Hartford on a warrant from
Puerto Rico accusing him of shooting Special Agent Abelardo Alba on
Aug. 30, 1985, said U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy Jr. The
indictment against him was handed up in Puerto Rico on Wednesday.
   Alba survived the attack, which occurred as he and five other
agents were seeking to arrest Ojeda Rios at his home on charges in
the Sept. 12, 1983, robbery of the Wells Fargo depot in West
Hartford, according to court documents.
   More than $7 million was stolen in a robbery federal authorities
say was masterminded by Los Macheteros, a militant, sometimes
violent group seeking Puerto Rican independence.
   Sixteen people are now awaiting trial in the robbery case.
Prosecutors have said Ojeda Rios was one of the leaders of Los
Macheteros.
   The 55-year-old Ojeda Rios was released on $1 million bond in
May after a pretrial detention lasting 32 months, longer than any
other defendant in federal history. An appeals court ruled that the
detention violated his constitutional rights.
   He was released into the custody of his attorney and has been
living in a Hartford apartment. He was under a judge's order to
remain in Hartford, stay at home between 8 p.m. and 7 a.m., and
wear an electronic bracelet so authorities could monitor his
whereabouts.
   Attorney William Kunstler, who has been involved in the Wells
Fargo defense, has said Ojeda Rios fired three shots at agents who
arrested him in San Juan because he feared being killed.
   Alba was struck in the eye by a fragment of a bullet that
ricocheted off a wall in the Ojeda Rios home, authorities said.
   If convicted of the shooting, Ojeda Rios could be sentenced to
up to 60 years in prison.
</TEXT>
