<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Strike     08-26 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Strike,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Hits Major State Television Network</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of the second-largest state
broadcasting network went on strike Friday, halting several
television and radio shows.
   It was the first labor strike involving a TV or radio network in
South Korea. The strikers allege the network is biased in favor of
the government.
   The 749-member union of the Moonhwa Broadcsting Corp. demanded
the resignation of the company's president, Hwang Sun-pil, and
actions to guarantee fair reporting.
   The MBC, one of the two state networks in South Korea, could not
broadcast a regular morning news program as union members picketed
the studio.
   Management said it would stay on the air with the help of 1,400
non-union members, most of them senior news editors and technical
crews. Union members said they would start a sit-in to press their
demand.
   The union, whose members include most junior reporters,
newscasters and cameramen in the company, alleged the network has
been pro-government.
   Culture and Information Minister Chung Han-mo denounced the
strike and warned it could hurt the Sept. 17-Oct. 2 Olympics.
   Riding on a nationwide political democratization movement,
unionized reporters have recently been increasing efforts to expand
press freedom. A few pro-government newspapers have been hit by
strikes demanding more such freedom.
</TEXT>
