<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--UN-Romania     08-26 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--UN-Romania,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romanian Human Rights Expert Appeals For Right To Leave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Romanian human rights expert denied his
government's assertion that health problems prevent him traveling
to Geneva to present a report to a U.N. meeting.
   Dumitru Mazilu wrote a letter to the U.N. Subcommission on
Prevention of Discrimination and Protection of Minorities, urging
that it ``ask the Romanian authorities to put an immediate end to
the repressive measures and police terror against me and my
family.''
   Mazilu was to submit a study on youth and human rights at the
group's meeting in Geneva, but Romanian officials said he was
unable to attend and could not finish his study due to a heart
condition. They said he recently left Bucharest to be treated at a
health resort.
   The U.N. secretary-general's office is investigating.
   Mazilu, in an earlier letter to the subcommission, said the
government had forced him to drop the study and put him under
police surveillance.
   In his latest message, read aloud Thursday, Mazilu said he had
no ``personal problems'' that would keep him from presenting the
report.
