<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Under Policeman's Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILBAO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded under a policeman's car in
this northern city Friday, and the mayor of a nearby town said she
received telephone threats for her stand against an attack by
Basque separatists.
   The police officer was not in the car when the blast occurred
shortly after midnight, ripping apart the front seats, dislodging
the engine and shattering nearby windows. No injuries were reported.
   On Thursday, Basque separatists claimed responsibility for a
bombing Sunday that killed two civil guards in Estella. Mayor Rosa
Lopez told Spanish National Radio she had been threatened because
she engineered the ouster of a town councilor who refused to sign a
resolution condemning the bombing.
   The former councilor belongs to Herri Batasuna, the political
wing of the separatist group ETA, which claimed responsibility for
the Estella bombing.
   ETA, whose name stands for Homeland and Liberty in the Basque
language, seeks independence for the three-province Basque region
and Navarre, the neighboring region where the civil guards were
killed.
   ETA has claimed responsibility for killing more than 600 people,
mostly civil guard, military and police officers, since taking up
arms in 1968. It has killed eight people this year.
</TEXT>
