<DOCNO> AP880826-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1236EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     08-26 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Will Appeal to Supreme Court If Marcos Ordered Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of President Corazon
Aquino will appeal to the Supreme Court if a lower tribunal rules
that Ferdinand Marcos can come home to face an accuser, the chief
prosecutor said Friday.
   Solicitor-General Francisco Chavez made the statement to
reporters after a meeting between Mrs. Aquino and chief legal
advisers to study implications of a petition filed by the former
president to return when a former Cabinet minister testifies
against him in November.
   Marcos petitioned the anti-graft court Wednesday to allow him to
return so he could defend himself when Baltazar Aquino, the former
Public Works Minister, gives a deposition on alleged kickbacks by
Japanese firms during the previous administration.
   Last week, the anti-graft court said Marcos had the right to be
present and cross-examine Aquino if the testimony was to be used in
criminal proceedings. Aquino is no relation to the president.
   But the anti-corruption court stopped short of ordering Marcos
to return. Chavez said he will file a motion next week asking the
court to reject Marcos' petition.
   ``If our position is not upheld, then we will elevate the matter
to the Supreme Court,'' Chavez said. He added that he expected
Marcos to do the same if the lower court rejects the petition.
   The government was trying to reconcile ``the demands of the
judiciary and the demands of national security,'' presidential
spokesman Teodoro Benigno said.
   Mrs. Aquino cited national security as the main reason for
preventing Marcos from coming back from his exile in Hawaii, where
he fled after the February 1986 uprising that toppled his 20-year
administration.
   But she has also pledged to abide by the decision of the courts,
even if they order Marcos home.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos said the military has begun
preparing security plans in the event that Marcos returns.
   Pro-Marcos groups within the armed forces have been responsible
for at least two of the half dozen major coup attempts against the
Aquino government. Key leaders of those coup attempts remain at
large.
   The Philippine government claims Marcos embezzled up to $10
billion during his graft-ridden administration.
</TEXT>
