<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Profiles     08-26 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Profiles,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Meet in Historic Chamber Seeking Peace in Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-Talks Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq are
conducting their search for peace, with the aid of the U.N.
secretary-general, in a historic conference room decorated with
murals depicting human proress.
   The Council Chamber of the Palais des Nations has witnessed such
other events as the signing last April of the Afghanistan agrement,
the conference on Laos in 1961-62, the conference of foreign
ministers on Berlin in 1958, the Big Four summit of 1955, and the
conferences on Korea and Indochina in 1954.
   This time, the goal is ending an 8-year-old war that has taken
up to 1 million lives and cost hundreds of billions of dollars.
   Here are brief profiles of the participants:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ALI AKBAR VELAYATI _ Iran's foreign minister is a 42-year-old
pediatrician who studied briefly at Johns Hopkins University in the
United States. He is regarded as a moderate and has pressed for an
end to Iran's isolation.
   Velayati has the support of Hashemi Rafsanjani, the parliament
speaker and acting military commander who was behind Iran's
acceptance of a cease-fire, and presumably that of revolutionary
patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   He spoke against the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi as a young
man and spent time in jail for anti-government activities. Velayati
was instrumental in preparing Khomeini's return from exile in the
revolution that ousted the shah in 1979, and became foreign
minister in 1981.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   TARIQ AZIZ _ The foreign minister and deputy premier of Iraq,
51, is a close associate of President Saddam Hussein and among the
nation's most influential figures. He is a leader of the ruling
Baath Party and a member of the governing Revolutionary Command
Council.
   Aziz, a Christian in an overwhelmingly Moslem nation, is
considered one of the government's most articulate spokesmen. He
obtained a bachelor's degree in English literature from Baghdad
University, joined the Baath Party as a young man and worked for
Iraqi newspapers and television.
   He became editor of the party newspaper, Al-Thawra, and was
named informatrion minister in 1981, a year after escaping a bomb
assassination attempt blamed on pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems. It was
one of several attacks on Iraqi officials before the war began in
September 1980.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JAVIER PEREZ DE CUELLAR _ The U.N. secretary-general is 68 and
in his second five-yer term. He is soft-spoken and given to
understatement, known more for discretion than dynamism.
   Perez de Cuellar is fond of the French saying: ``The melody
makes the song, not a loud voice.''
   He was Peru's ambassador to the United Nations in 1971-75 and
special U.N. representative to Cyprus from 1975-77, became
undersecretary-general for special political affairs in 1979 and
served as special representative to Afghanistan in 1981.
   In the first recent success for U.N. diplomacy, his special
representative Diego Cordovez mediated the Afghanistan settlement
signed in April.
</TEXT>
