<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Copper-7Trial     08-26 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copper-7 Trial,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberating Copper-7 Case; Asked To Award $16.5 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury began deliberating today whether
the Copper-7 intrauterine device caused sterility in a 30-year-old
Minnesota woman.
   The plaintiffs, Esther Kociemba of Elk River and her husband,
William, asked the jury Thursday to penalize Copper-7 maker G.D.
Searle & Co. by awarding at least $16.5 million, far more than any
jury has awarded in 18 similar cases.
   ``You are going to have the ability to step right into that
board room and send a message ...,'' Michael Ciresi, the Kociembas'
attorney, told the jury. ``Maybe they'll learn a lesson.''
   Ciresi, who spearheaded litigation against A.H. Robins that
resulted in a settlement of $38 million for 198 users of the Dalkon
Shield IUD, maintained during the three-month trial that the
Copper-7 caused pelvic inflammatory disease that rendered Mrs.
Kociemba sterile. The Chicago-based Searle improperly tested the
device, he argued.
   ``The Copper-7 was a time bomb ticking away in women's wombs,''
Ciresi told the jury. ``Searle knew and concealed the dangers of
that device from the medical community.''
   But Paul Strain, a lawyer for Searle, said the company exceeded
U.S. Food and Drug Administration requirements in marketing
Copper-7, which was once the most widely used IUD in America.
   He attacked the credibility of the plaintiffs' witnesses and
said Ciresi did not even prove that Mrs. Kociemba suffered from
pelvic infection, let alone that it was caused by the Copper-7.
   ``Time and again the Searle doctors did more than they had to do
to ensure the safety of the women who were going to use the
Copper-7,'' Strain said. ``The medical literature fortifies the
judgment that the Copper-7 is safe and effective.''
   Strain termed ``raw and mean'' allegations that Searle concealed
evidence about the Copper-7 ``to hurt women'' and said one expert
witness for the other side had testified in many trials and ``would
always blame an IUD unless a woman had a gunshot wound to the
abdomen.''
   Strain cautioned the jury to base its decision on facts instead
of sympathy for Mrs. Kociemba, who wept quietly for much of the day.
</TEXT>
