<1ST_LINE>r w AM-USAir-FlightAttendants     08-26 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USAir-Flight Attendants,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Accord Reached Covering Former PSA Attendants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After months of wrangling that included a job
action which forced 170 flight cancellations, USAir and its flight
attendants' union have hammered out a tentative agreement on wage
parity for former Pacific Southwest Airlines attendants.
   Officials for the airline and the Association of Flight
Attendants said Friday the accord also extends for another year,
with some minor modifications, a contract covering a total of 4,203
attendants. The current contract was up for renewal and amendment
Sept. 1.
   The new contract, which has to be ratified by the union members,
was reached late Thursday in Pittsburgh after 10 days of intense
negotiations there, said Judy Stack, an official of the Association
of Flight Attendants.
   USAir acquired Pacific Southwest in May 1987 but operated it as
a separate subsidiary until last April before merging the two
operations.
   The 961 former Pacific Southwest attendants had been represented
by the Teamsters but voted to switch to the Association of Flight
Attendants just prior to USAir's acquisition of PSA.
   Stack said the former PSA attendants generally were on pay
scales about 10 percent less than those at USAir. The company had
offered to bring the two groups of workers to parity over a
three-year period.
   The union had wanted that accomplished faster. When the two
sides reached an impasse last spring, many attendants refused to
work overtime on the Memorial Day weekend, forcing USAir to cancel
some 170 flights then.
   Neither Stack nor David Shipley, a spokesman for the airline,
would disclose details of the agreement. They said completion of
the ratification vote is expected in late September.
   The union and the company now have to go through the same
process to integrate a contract covering some 3,000 flight
attendants at Piedmont Airlines into the USAir accord.
   USAir purchased Piedmont last November and hopes to merge their
operations next March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
