<HEAD>Congressman Leaves Hospital After Bypass Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Richard Cheney, R-Wyo., a member of the
House Republican leadership, was released from George Washington
University Hospital on Friday, a week after undergoing coronary
bypass surgery.
   Cheney, 47, who served as White House chief of staff during the
Ford administration, had suffered three reportedly mild heart
attacks in 1978, 1984 and in June of this year.
   A spokesman, Pete Williams, said Cheney had been advised by his
physician that if he underwent the operation he could remain
physically active and reduce the possibility of further heart
attacks.
   Cheney, chairman of the House Republican Conference, left last
week's GOP convention in New Orleans a day early and underwent
surgery on Friday.
   Williams said Cheney will rest at home for the next two weeks
and return to work at the end of the congressional summer recess,
on Sept. 7.
