<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1316EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfTalks 3rdLd-Writethru a0550 08-26 0875</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Talks, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0550,0898</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran, Iraq Resume Direct Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads throughout with talks resuming in joint session,
settlement depends on resolving border treaty, details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian envoy took a hard line today at the
second day of the Iran-Iraq peace talks, saying a lasting
settlement to the prolonged dispute depends on observance of a 1975
border treaty repudiated by Iraq.
   The joint face-to-face session between foreign ministers was
temporarily abandoned this morning. U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar said it was difficult for the bitter rivals to
continue meeting. They met instead in separate rooms for about two
hours.
   But in the afternoon, the face-to-face session was resumed by
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati and Iraqi Foreign
Minister Tariq Aziz, flanked by their delegations. There was no
immediate word on progress.
   However, Velayati delivered a strong statement after the morning
session about the validity of the 1975 Algiers Treaty on Iran-Iraq
boundaries. The issue poses a major stumbling block in the
negotiations.
   Emerging from the morning session, Velayati told reporters,
``For reaching this comprehensive, just and honorable solution, we
have valid criteria ... (United Nations) Resolution 598, (the)
outline plan of the secretary-general and the 1975 treaty between
Iran and Iraq.''
   In September 1980, President Saddam Hussein renounced that
treaty, which gave Iran rights to the disputed Shatt-Al-Arab
waterway, and five days later invaded Iraq.
   The border issue and treaty are considered critical to a peace
settlement because Resolution 598 requires troop withdrawal to
mutually recognized boundaries. Iraq now says the boundaries are in
question.
   Iraqi officials recently reaffirmed their repudiation of that
treaty.
   Earlier in the day, Perez de Cuellar told reporters that
problems between Iran and Iraq have lasted centuries, ``and then it
is not in one afternoon that we can decide.''
   The session began Thursday with a joint session led by the
secretary-general, and both sides addressed each other through
intepreters. It was the first face-to-face meeting of foreign
ministers since the Persian Gulf war began almost eight years ago.
   But after two hours the session was suspended, and both sides
met in separate chambers for three more hours, with U.N. officials
meeting them and reporting to Perez de Cuellar.
   The format of separate rooms was continued today, U.N. spokesman
Francois Giuliani said. The secretary-general first met separately
with each minister, then the delegations consulted in separate
rooms, he said.
   U.N. officials, based in another room, occasionally visited the
delegations and Perez de Cuellar at times met the delegations
separately.
   Meanwhile, a small group of Iraqi Kurds and other Iraqi
opposition groups demonstrated outside the building and protested
the Baghdad government's use of chemical weapons on its rebellious
Kurdish minority.
   Iraq had demanded the direct, face-to-face talks before a
cease-fire to test Iran's intentions. Iran refused and both sides
agreed on direct talks shortly after the halt in hostilities.
   ``I am sure the parties sincerely want to solve the problem,''
Perez de Cuellar said today. ``(But) I think we have to be a little
patient.''
   He said the arrangement was made at the request of the two
countries. ``I would prefer to have them all the time in the main
room with me.'' But, he said, ``I have to accommodate myself to the
wish of the parties.''
   The talks began about one hour late. Velayati declined to answer
questions from reporters at the entrance of the building. The bulk
of the Iranian delegation had arrived earlier, on time for the
meeting.
   Giuliani denied reports by U.N. officials that the
secretary-general was considering appointing former Swiss President
Kurt Furgler as his special representative to continue the
Iran-Iraq talks.
   He also dismissed a Swiss Radio report that Edouard Brunner, the
No. 2 in the Swiss Foreign Ministry, would be appointed. He said if
Brunner is appointed Swiss ambassador to Washington, ``There is no
question of the secretary-general appointing him as his personal
representative,'' Giuliani said.
   Brunner is being considered for the post, but if appointed, he
would not take the position until next year.
   The peace process is expected to be long and difficult, possibly
lasting years. The direct talks were made possible after Iran and
Iraq both accepted U.N. Security Council Resolution 598, calling
for a cease-fire.
   Before the talks began, Perez de Cuellar held several meetings
with Aziz and Velayati in New York. The warring sides agreed to
hold direct talks following a cease-fire that began Aug. 20.
   The truce appeared to be holding. Saeem Fahmawi, a spokesman for
the 350 U.N. observers monitoring the 733-mile Iraq-Iran warfront,
said in Baghdad there have been no major violations.
   The Iranian and Iraqi delegations in Geneva include political
figures, military representatives and legal experts on war relief,
prisoner repatriation and reparations.
   The agenda was not disclosed, but the secretary-general said the
talks were aimed at carrying out the cease-fire resolution, which
also calls for troop withdrawal to international boundaries, return
of war prisoners, reparations and a comprehensive peace.
   It also calls for an impartial body to determine which side
started the war.
   Repatriation of POWs is any thorny issue. Many of the 80,000 war
prisoners are expected to refuse repatriation because they have
publicly supported the detaining country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
