<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KoreanProtest     08-26 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korean Protest,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Activists Campaign to Release South Korean Political Prisoners.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. peace activists announced Friday they are
forming an international campaign to secure the release of all
political prisoners in South Korea after two Americans were
arrested for participating in a recent Seoul rally.
   Susan Bailey of the People's Anti-War Mobilization, a New
York-based group that opposes the U.S. military presence in South
Korea, also called for the withdrawal of the 45,000 American troops
stationed there.
   Bailey told a news conference that she and another American,
Charles Scheiner, were arrested Aug. 20 at a rally held five days
earlier by supporters of the movement to unify North and South
Korea.
   ``I was surrounded by plainclothes police on foot,'' Bailey
said. ``They began screaming at us, forcibly grabbed us, picked us
up and threw us in the back seat of unmarked cars.''
   Bailey maintains that she and Scheiner were held by the Seoul
Metropolitan Police and by immigration authorites for 55 hours
without being allowed to contact U.S. Embassy officials, and then
were deported without being charged with a crime.
   South Korean government officials told embassy representatives
that Bailey and Scheiner violated laws prohibiting tourists from
participating in political demonstrations, according to the State
Department.
   Bailey also contends that Young Sook, a South Korean woman who
had served as her hostess and interpreter, was jailed after
authorities charged she was associating with political subversives.
   Bailey, a secretary at the University of Maryland, said her
interpreter's jailing is meant to have a chilling effect on South
Korean political activists.
   ``Clearly, the South Korean government is intent on making an
example out of Young Sook as a way to discourage contact between
the South Korean government and the international community,''
Bailey said.
   Several international human rights organizations, as well as
former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark, are working to secure
Sook's release, Bailey said.
   State Department officials did not have information on Young
Sook's case, and calls to the South Korean embassy in Washington
were not returned immediately.
</TEXT>
