<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BurdickHospitalized     08-26 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burdick Hospitalized,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Burdick Recovers From Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF MEYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Quentin Burdick should make a full
recovery from an operation in which part of his colon was removed
as a precaution against cancer, aides and his doctor said.
   ``We obviously think this will be a short-term problem, but we
feel as the senator recovers and returns to work he will
demonstrate his vigor and vitality,'' Burdick's chief of staff,
David Strauss, said Thursday after the surgery.
   The 80-year-old North Dakota Democrat has served in the Senate
since 1960, when he won a special election, and is running for
re-election this year to a fifth full term. He faces Republican
Earl Strinden in November.
   An 18-inch section of Burdick's colon was removed during a
2{-hour operation at Bethesda Naval Hospital in Maryland, and the
procedure was a ``complete success,'' said Charles Blankenship, who
performed the surgery.
   No cancer was apparent in the excised colon tissue, but tests
will determine if any was present, the doctor said in a telephone
interview.
   Three polyps were removed from Burdick's colon during a routine
screening in July and one was found to be cancerous, according to a
statement issued by Burdick's office.
   There was a slight chance the cancer could have spread to his
lymph nodes, so the section of the colon where the cancerous polyp
was found was removed as a precaution, Blankenship said.
   Following the surgery, Burdick was conscious and appeared
``normal for an 80-year-old man after a major operation,'' the
doctor said.
   Burdick is expected to remain in the hospital for seven to 10
days and resume a full schedule Sept. 7, Strauss said.
   The operation was similar to one President Reagan underwent in
July 1985, when two feet of his colon was removed, Strauss said.
   Burdick has tried to deflect talk about his age and health with
a public relations campaign emphasizing his commitment to fitness.
He has been photographed wearing a karate outfit and once offered
to fight the candidates for the Republican Senate nomination ``toe
to toe, any rules you want.''
   Party activists last year urged Burdick to step down because of
his age in favor of a Senate bid by Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.
Burdick rejected the idea and eventually won the party's
endorsement after Dorgan declined to challenge him.
</TEXT>
