<DOCNO> AP880826-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--MilitaryVoting     08-26 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Military Voting,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voting Information Center Set Up For Military Personnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Defense announced Friday it
will set up a voting information center where military personnel
can dial in to learn about the top candidates for state and
national offices.
   Callers need only enter a two-letter abbreviation for their home
state to hear recorded two-minute messages from the presidential
and vice presidential candidates, as well 90-second messages from
congressional and gubernatorial candidates.
   The center, located at the headquarters of the Non-Commissioned
Officers Association in Alexandria, Va., will also provide callers
with voter registration assistance and answer any questions not
covered by the taped messages.
   The officer's association has conducted a voter registration
drive on military bases and ships worldwide since January. It
expects to register more than 250,000 servicemen and women,
according to C.R. Jackson, the association's executive vice
president.
   The center will operate from Aug. 29 through Election Day.
   Callers using the Defense Department telephone network will be
able to reach the service by dialing (8) 285-4333 on touch tone
phones or (8) 221-6100 on rotary dial phones.
</TEXT>
