<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Questions     08-26 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Questions,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Questions & Answers on Labor Unrest in Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a week of labor unrest is
putting pictures of Lech Walesa and striking Polish workers back
into newspapers and on television screens. Here, in
question-and-answer format, is some background on the unrest:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q. What are the issues this time?
   A. In the approximately 20 strikes since Aug. 16, the chief
demand has been to make legal the banned trade union Solidarity,
followed by calls for higher wages.
   Solidarity was suppressed and then outlawed following the
imposition of martial law in Dec. 13, 1981. But it has remained
active, at first mainly as an underground organization but in
recent years more openly as the government has become less
restrictive.
   Poland's faltering economy has given new impetus to strike
actions, and when strikes broke out in April and again this month,
Solidarity activists led the protests.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q. What is the state of the economy?
   A. The government this year launched its ``second stage'' of
economic reform that aims to reduce government subsidies, eliminate
inefficient enterprises, give managers more autonomy, remove
obstacles to private enterprise and make wages more dependent on
individual performance.
   Broad price increases were announced as part of the program,
which sent inflation rocketing from about 25 percent a year to
about 60 percent. Wages were raised, too _ even higher than
inflation according to the government _ but many workers felt that
their incomes have not kept up with prices.
   Meanwhile, supplies of consumer goods to the stores have been
even more erratic than usual, partly because of adjustments to the
reform program.
   After a wave of strikes in April and May, the government
announced the price-increase program had been handled poorly and
its top priority now would be controlling inflation and improving
the availability of consumer goods.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q. What are the workers' complaints?
   A. Average wages in Poland are low, about $100 a month at the
official rate of exchange. Many industrial workers say they are
forced to work long hours and on weekends just to make ends meet.
About two pounds of meat costs about one day's wages and a color
television about four months' wages.
   Young workers, who have dominated the strikes, want affordable
housng. The waiting period for cooperative apartments can be 20 to
30 years in some parts of the country and private housing is beyond
their means.
   After Solidarity was crushed, the government set up an official
trade union federation which has shown some militancy on behalf of
workers.
   But because the head of the federation is a member of the ruling
Politburo and it tends to be dominated by the party, many workers
do not trust the federation and want Solidarity restored.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q. What does Solidarity want?
   A. Legal status and talks with the government about restoring
the economy.
   Solidarity says econmic reform is necessary but it should be
done with the consent and guidance of the workers. But even
Solidarity admits that many of the goals of the reform require
sacrifices.
   While the union wants to encourage economic reform, it also
wants to preserve aspects of the socialized economy that benefit
workers: subsidized housing, generous vacations and cradle-to-grave
security.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q. Why won't the government recognize Solidarity?
   A. The government says Solidarity started out with broad popular
support but was hijacked by radicals who oppose Poland's communist
system and is supported by money from abroad. It says the ``former
union'' is now a wholly political group with only about 30,000
supporters nationwide, compared with 10 million members in 1981.
The new official unions, with 7 million members, are the legitimate
representatives of workers, it says.
   The government says it is willing to talk to former Solidarity
members who are interested in constructive change, but not while
they are leading illegal strikes and not if they oppose Poland's
Constitution, which gives the Communist Party the ``leading role''
in Poland.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q. What is Lech Walesa's role?
   A. Walesa is Solidarity's national chairman and is keeping in
touch with strikers nationwide while leading the strike at the
Lenin shipyard in Gdansk, where he works as an electrician.
   He has advisers with him in Gdansk, including some intellectuals
like historian Adam Michnik. Other Solidarity activists are running
a nationwide information network to make sure the union's side of
the strike is publicized.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Q. Why is 1988 different from 1980?
   A. Strikes in Poland this year have not sparked the same degree
of public enthusiasm as in 1980, when virtually the entire nation
went on strike and an unbridled national euphoria gave rise to
Solidarity.
   After the experience of martial law and eight years of economic
decline, the attitude expressed by many Poles, even among some
sympathetic to Solidarity's goals, is ``Strikes are useless. What
good will it do?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
