<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Eastern     08-26 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sides With Unions Fighting for Jobs at Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY WINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today extended his earlier
action to bar Eastern Airlines from firing 4,000 workers and said
he would detail his objections to the company's reorganization and
cutback plans by Tuesday.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington D. Parker issued a terse,
two-page ruling saying that the three unions fighting Eastern's
plans ``are entitled to preliminary injunctive relief.''
   The financially troubled airline, a subsidiary of Texas Air
Corp., said it anticipated an appeal of Parker's actions.
   The scope of the ruling was not immediately clear. Parker's
ruling said a full opinion would be issued setting forth ``the
limits of the the preliminary injunctive relief.'' Earlier this
month, the judge issued a restraining order blocking the carrier's
plans to reduce its service and close its Kansas City hub Sept. 1.
   A spokeswoman for the Miami-based Eastern, Karen Ceremsak, said
in a statement that the company believes the unions ``are not
entitled to relief of any sort and we expect we will be filing an
appeal at the appropriate time.''
   The statement said the airline would take no action against the
employees ``pending clarifications of what our obligation will be
under terms of the ruling.''
   The Eastern plan, announced July 22, also calls for elimination
of 140 of its 1,225 daily flights to trim costs.
   The three unions _ the Airline Pilots Association, the
International Association of Machinists and the Transport Workers
Union _ contend the layoffs can't take place until the carrier
negotiates with its employees under the Railway Labor Act.
   Eastern, which has lost about $1 billion over the last decade,
says the cuts are necessary to prevent further losses.
   The unions allege the reductions are a part of a plan to move
Eastern's assets to Continental Airlines, another subsidiary of
Texas Air Corp.
   At a hearing before Parker earlier this month, union attorneys
produced a draft of a speech that Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo
was to give to Japanese investors in 1986 after Texas Air acquired
Eastern.
   The draft said the purchase of Eastern gave Texas Air a better
bargaining position against its unions. ``Eastern's airplanes can
be repainted and moved over to Continental, where they will be
flown by non-union pilots,'' the speech draft said.
   Lorenzo said the draft was prepared by an investment banking
firm. It was unclear from court testimony whether Lorenzo ever
delivered that portion of the speech.
</TEXT>
