<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Pacific     08-26 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Pacific,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pacific Island Nations Seek Stronger Ties, Cooperation With Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives from 10 island nations in the South
Pacific and related organizations began talks Friday to strengthen
ties and to find ways to cooperate with Japan.
   It was the first such conference held in Japan since World War
II, said Takeju Ogata, general manager of the Sasakawa Peace
Foundation, which sponsored the two-day meeting that drew 46
representatives.
   ``The nations of the Pacific island region hold great potential
across the broad spectrum of political, economic, and cultural
endeavors, and in recent years, the world's attentions for this
region have risen,'' Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said in a
message read to the gathering.
   Heads of state or ministers from Fiji, Kiribati, Micronesia,
Papua New Guinea, the Solomon Islands, Tonga, Tuvalu, Vanuatu,
Western Samoa and the Cook Islands and officials and
representatives from eight other countries including Australia, New
Zealand, Indonesia and France met in a Tokyo hotel.
   Tuilaepa Sailele, finance minister of Western Samoa, said in a
speech that the Pacific region ``is becoming the focus of
superpower rivalry.''
   ``With the declaration of this decade as the `decade of the
Pacific,' it is certainly opportune that we ought to gather here to
debate its future development,'' he said.
   About 450 people, including 150 invited guests and officials of
the Japanese government and businesses, attended Friday's session,
Ogata said.
   Sasakawa Peace Foundation, set up by Ryoichi Sasakawa, chairman
of the Japan Shipbuilding Industry Association in 1986, is
supported by revenues of the Japan Motorboat Racing Associaton,
which he also heads.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
