<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1443EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-26 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tennessee Valley Authority is
scrapping its employee suggestion program until somebody can
suggest a more economical way to run it.
   TVA set up the program last fall to encourage cost-saving ideas,
but the operation cost the federal utility more to administer than
it saved.
   ``The idea of the program was good, but what we ended up with
was a bureaucratic, convoluted system that took so long to review
the suggestions that it proved to be ineffective,'' said Sue
Wallace, acting director of TVA's human resources department.
   TVA received nearly 1,000 suggestions from employees over 10
months, including 46 that collectively saved about $580,000. Ten
percent of that savings was paid to the employees as a bonuses for
their ideas.
   The problem was that TVA spent about $700,000 on the program,
including $514,000 in staff expenses, said Ms. Wallace.
   Among other things, there was a two-inch-thick handbook of rules
specifying who and what could be included in the program to qualify
for the bonuses.
   TVA directors voted earlier this week to end the program, and a
group of managers and employees is working on a new system.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Indiana State Fair has changed a lot
since Lincoln D. Stafford attended his first one, in 1915, when he
had to hoe corn on his grandfather's farm to make money to go the
big event.
   ``I worked a whole 10 days for $5. I spent $4.95 the last day
(at the fair) and went home with a nickel,'' Stafford said this
week at the fairgrounds.
   Stafford, now 90 and pastor at the Gospel Chapel in Linton, says
it's amusing to hear today's fairgoers complain about the lack of
air conditioning at the fairgrounds.
   ``It hadn't been invented when I first came,'' he said.
   The content of the fairs also has changed during the last seven
decades.
   ``A lot of the focus was on different sports _ baseball, horse
pulls, basketball _ and other farm-related contests,'' he said.
   But there's been an even a more dramatic change in the fairgoers.
   ``I like to study people at the fair,'' Stafford said. ``And in
1915, people wore clothes. Now they don't.''
</TEXT>
