<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrainWreck     08-26 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Wreck,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LIRR Expected Back to Normal After Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crash that disrupted Long Island Rail
Road service will cost the commuter rail system an estimated $2.6
million, a spokeswoman said Friday.
   The railroad should be back on a normal schedule Saturday. A
train Thursday night rammed a tractor-trailer rig stuck at a
crossing. Train service was canceled on one branch of the railroad.
   Eighteen people were injured, none seriously.
   The LIRR expected to repair damaged tracks and remove the
derailed cars by late Friday or early Saturday, according to
spokeswoman Susan McGowan.
   Ms. McGowan said Friday's morning rush hour went as well as
could be expected.
   ``There wasn't much confusion,'' she said, adding that commuters
used another branch of the LIRR and buses.
   A witness to the crash said the driver of the tractor-trailer
rig frantically tried to warn the train but then stood clear as the
locomotive slammed into his flatbed trailer, which was carrying a
bulldozer.
   The collision caused the engine to flip on its side, spilling
diesel fuel. The engine and the second car ended up in a lumberyard
adjacent to the tracks, Ms. McGowan said.
   Three other cars derailed and two cars that were being stored on
a siding were sideswiped and derailed, she added.
   LIRR spokesman Mike Charles said investigators would try to
determine why the train did not stop in time. Among the questions,
he said, is how fast it was going and ``whether or not indeed the
truck driver did try to flag the train down.''
</TEXT>
