<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Merriam     08-26 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Merriam,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Alderman Who Ran Against Daley Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert E. Merriam, a former alderman who lost to
Richard J. Daley in the 1955 mayoral race and then became adviser
to three presidents, has died of a heart attack. He was 69.
   Merriam, who died at home Thursday, also wrote ``Dark
December,'' a popular account of his Army recollections of the
World War II Battle of the Bulge.
   The son of a reform alderman and 1911 mayor candidate, Merriam
switched to the Republican Party in 1947 and was elected alderman
of the 5th Ward.
   After he lost to Daley in the 1955 race by more than 125,000
votes, Merriam remained an outspoken critic of the mayor and his
patronage system. Daley remained in office from 1955 until his
death in 1976.
   Merriam also came to the attention of President Dwight D.
Eisenhower, who appointed him assistant director of the Bureau of
the Budget. He later served under presidents Richard Nixon and
Gerald Ford as chairman of the President's Advisory Commission on
Intergovernmental Affairs.
   He also was executive vice president for Urban Investment &
Development Co. from 1971 to 1976, when he became partner in
Alexander Proudfoot and Co., a consulting firm.
   He is survived by his wife, Marguerite; two daughters; and a
son. Funeral arrangements were pending.
</TEXT>
