<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GreekShip     08-26 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greek Ship,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship Leaves Port With Korean Crewman Who Asked To Get Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek freighter left for its next port
still carrying seven Korean crewmen who wanted off because they
didn't like the food.
   The Koreans had complained of mistreatment to Savannah's port
chaplain, saying the Greek food served on board deprived them of
the vegetables and rice to which they are accustomed, said the
chaplain, the Rev. Mario Balbi.
   The seamen sent a telex to the ship's owner asking for
permission to leave because of ``suffering conditions,'' but there
was no response from Good Faith Shipping Co. of Greece before the
refrigerated cargo ship left Wednesday for Tunisia, Balbi said.
   ``They are now out in the middle of the ocean,'' the chaplain
said Thursday. ``I don't know if they will hear back from the owner
at sea or when they arrive in Tunisia.''
   Without permission to leave, the seamen would not have been paid
the wages owed them and could not have afforded to return home.
   The ship's captain and top officers are Greek, and Balbi said
the Korean crewmen told him the captain bought only Greek food each
time the ship called on ports in various countries, including
Greece, Turkey, Algeria and the United States.
   The Atlantic, with a crew of 25, docked in Savannah on Monday.
Balbi said the ship's master would not discuss the complaints with
him.
