the house during this visit to Los Angeles.
   The spokesman, asked why the president appeared to be
disinterested in a home he'll live in, said, ``He probably is
interested.''
   ``I don't know what his familiarity is with the house,''
Fitzwater said, adding that he knows the president is familiar with
the neighborhood.
   The $2.5 million ranch-style home is owned by Wall Management
Services, a group of about 20 unidentified Reagan friends who
bought it with the Reagans in mind, according to Mrs. Reagan's
spokeswoman, Elaine Crispen.
   The three-year lease gives the Reagans the option to renew the
lease or purchase the property.
   The extate includes 1.4 acres of grounds and a 35-year-old house
with 7,192 sware feet of living space, as well as a pool.
   More than any other vacation trip, Reagan has devoted time to
helping boost Bush's quest for the White House, as well as the
campaign coffers of state Republican candidates.
   On Tuesday, Reagan traveled to Orange County for a $500-a-plate
GOP fundraiser for Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., and one day later
appeared with Bush at a pep rally on Wednesday.
   Reagan is scheduled to attend two more fundraisers on Saturday
on his way north to his 688-acre ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains.
