<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Chief Assures Change to Civilian Rule in Pakistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new army chief told military
officers he would try to ensure an orderly transition to civilian
rule after the death of President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, official
media reported Friday.
   Gen. Aslam Beg said the Aug. 17 plane crash that killed Zia was
``a conspiracy,'' according to the Associated Press of Pakistan.
   He stopped short of laying blame, but pointed to warnings from
Moscow and New Delhi in the days preceding the crash of the C-130
transport plane. Also killed were U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel, a
U.S. Army general and 27 others.
   The Soviet Union said Aug. 13 it would not tolerate Pakistan's
continued support of anti-communist guerrillas in Afghanistan.
Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi warned Pakistan on Aug. 15 over
its alleged aid to Sikh separatists in western India.
   Beg was the No. 2 man on the army staff, which was headed by
Zia. He said the armed forces had no desire to meddle in politics,
APP reported.
   Beg said he and the armed services chiefs agreed to form an
emergency council with acting President Ghulam Ishaq Khan to
maintain law and order until after general elections on Nov. 16.
   ``We accepted the responsibility for the sole reason that no one
was (to be) allowed to exploit the situation to meet his nefarious
designs of harming the country,'' Beg was quoted as saying.
   Ishaq Khan, former senate chairman, promised to continue
preparations for the Nov. 16 polls. He said he had no objection to
candidates running as political parties.
   Zia, who seized power in a 1977 military coup, banned party
tickets in 1985 elections, prompting a boycott by most opposition
groups.
   He allowed formation of a civilian government among those who
did participate, but fired it last May for alleged corruption and
incompetence.
   Ishaq Khan's interpretation of the election rules has given new
hope to political leaders such as Benazir Bhutto of the
left-leaning Pakistan People's Party and to former Prime Minister
Mohammad Khan Junejo of the center-right Muslim League.
   The Movement for the Restoration of Democracy, an opposition
alliance that includes Ms. Bhutto's party, scheduled a rally for
Saturday in the southwestern city of Quetta.
   U.S. and Pakistani investigators continued to try to figure out
what made Zia's plane explode and crash.
   Ishaq Khan, Beg and others have said they are convinced it was
sabotage but have withheld comment on how it was done or by whom.
</TEXT>
