<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Workers'Search     08-26 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Workers' Search,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crew Outraged at Construction Site Drug Search</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 workers at a city construction
project were forced to kneel before drug-sniffing dogs or lose
their jobs, an experience one angry union official likened to
slavery.
   Municipal officials and representatives of the project's
construction manager said Thursday that the Aug. 18 search at the
city's $81 million Morton H. Meyerson Symphony Center turned up
nothing.
   ``When they make you get down in front of an animal on your
knees, that's getting back into slavery,'' said Bill Hawkins,
business manager of Ironworkers Local 481.
   Bruce Lady, senior vice president for J.W. Bateson Co., the
company that is serving as construction manager, said he and other
managers knew about the search and submitted to it.
   Workers and managers were invidually taken to a room and asked
to squat on one knee while a dog sniffed them.
   The search, which involved more than 200 workers, was undertaken
after a former employee reported that drugs were allegedly being
used at the construction site. ``The construction industry has a
certain amount of risk and danger to it, and that has to be
controlled,'' Lady said.
   Clifford Keheley, Dallas Public Works director, said he
authorized the search the day before it was conducted without
consulting any other city officials.
   ``They wanted our concurrence and we, of course, gave it
immediately,'' Keheley said. ``I would have seen a bigger problem
of not doing it. If there's any suspicion at all of illegal
activity on that site, we don't want it.''
   Several workers said they would gladly have submitted to blood
tests or other samples if there had been probable cause to suspect
drug use.
   ``This is the only major construction job going on (in Dallas)
right now _ and if you didn't submit to that search, you got kicked
off your job,'' Scott Alcox, a 28-year-old flagman, said. ``It is
degrading to have to get down on your knees to keep your job.''
</TEXT>
