<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama     08-26 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers Trade Gunfire in Panama; Army To Cut Tour Length</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A squad of Army Special Operations soldiers on
a routine patrol at Howard Air Force Base, Panama, traded gunfire
with a small group of intruders but no one was hurt, Pentagon
officials said Friday.
   The Thursday night incident came as the Army was poised to cut
the required tour length in Panama, part of a continuing effort to
reduce the number of military dependents in the troubled Central
American nation.
   The service hopes to encourage more soldiers to opt for
so-called ``unaccompanied tours'' _ leaving their families behind _
by reducing the tour commitment, said Defense officials, who asked
not to be named.
   The exchange of gunfire, which occurred Thursday evening near an
oil tank farm, was the first such incident in nearly three weeks.
   The officials said American soldiers spotted two or three
intruders before nightfall Thursday, drawing fire from the
unidentified men but not returning it. Later, around 9 p.m., the
soldiers were patrolling the tank farm area and again spotted
intruders, who again fired. This time they returned the gunfire.
   The intruders immediately ``broke contact'' and slipped into the
jungle, the sources said.
   The pending tour reduction plan, stemming in part from a
campaign of harrassment against Americans, would allow Pentagon
officials to move more military families from civilian housing in
and around Panama City to military housing on U.S. bases.
   According to the sources, the plan is awaiting final approval
from Gen. Carl Vuono, the Army's chief of staff, and Army Secretary
John Marsh. That should come early next week, the officials said
Friday.
   Once the Army acts, the other three military services are almost
certain to follow suit, predicted one official.
   Currently, soldiers deployed to Panama are expected to serve for
three years if accompanied by their family and two years if
unaccompanied. The new plan would reduce an accompanied tour to 2{
years and slash the minimum unaccompanied tour to just 15 months.
   ``Given all the turmoil, we're hoping more soldiers will decide
they can go unaccompanied and stick it out for 15 months,'' said
one official.
   Over the past five months, the Pentagon has succeeded in
reducing by 50 percent the number of military families living
outside U.S. bases in Panama _ dropping the total still off-base to
about 1,130. The effort has taken on more momentum this summer
because of what the United States describes as a deliberate
campaign of harrassing Americans.
   U.S. officials in Panama City said Aug. 21 that American
personnel had reported at least 240 incidents of harassment by
Panamanian authorities this year, including attempts to extort
bribes for traffic violations and the stoppage of mail.
   The harassment comes at a time when the United States is
continuing to press economic sanctions against Panama in a bid to
oust the country's leader, military strongman Manuel A. Noriega.
Noriega has been indicted by two federal grand juries in Florida on
drug trafficking charges.
   Panama is the home of the U.S. Southern Command, the
organization responsible for all U.S. military forces in Central
and South America. There are about 10,000 American servicemen
stationed permanently in Panama, plus about 2,200 servicemen who
have been assigned there on a temporary basis since the spring to
upgrade security at American bases.
   Sources said the move to reduce tour lengths for soldiers in
Panama comes amid rumors that Noriega's government intends to
cancel the leases on 100 off-base housing units rented by the Army
itself for military families.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0168 </DOCNO>
