<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tenerife-Controllers     08-26 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tenerife-Controllers,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canary Islands Air Controllers Call Off Planned Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ DE TENERIFE, Canary Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air traffic
controllers canceled planned strikes after the government pledged
to improve airport equipment, union leaders said Friday.
   The decision came a week after controllers in Catalonia agreed
to cancel three days of strikes in return for government promises
to raise pay for all 940 controllers in Spain and eliminate
regional salary differences.
   The strikes would have affected Spain's busiest holiday routes
and collapsed its Mediterranean airports, already overburdened by
summer travelers.
   The Tenerife controllers called off the strike after Civil
Aviation chief Manuel Mederos pledged to install a new radar system
at Reina Sofia airport and improve the control tower at Los Rodeos
airport, the leaders said.
   They said Mederos also agreed negotiate raises for controllers
at Los Rodeos.
   In the world's worst airplane crash, 580 people were killed at
Los Rodeos when two Boeing 747 airliners collided on the runway on
March 27, 1977.
   Spanish news reports said government concessions to the
controllers nationwide would cost $3 million and raise salaries by
an average of 17 percent.
</TEXT>
