<2ND_LINE>AM-Police-Muslim Clash,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police, Muslims Clash in Streetwalking Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officials said Friday they were
investigating a fight that broke out between police officers and
followers of black Muslim leader Louis Farrakhan who were trying to
drive prostitutes from the capital's red-light district.
   The trouble began about 11:30 p.m. Thursday, when officers
noticed about 25 members of the Nation of Islam shouting insults at
streetwalkers and trying to disrupt their contact with passing
motorists, said police spokesman Joseph Gentile.
   Officers patrolling the intersection just five blocks from the
White House repeatedly warned the Muslims not to jaywalk or step in
front of moving vehicles, Gentile said.
   When one officer attempted to issue a jaywalking citation to one
of the Muslims, several of the man's friends began to push the
officer, who called for help from colleagues, the spokesman said.
   When order was restored 20 minutes later, three police officers
and four Muslims had been hurt, none seriously, and eight of
Farrakhan's followers had been arrested.
   Seven were charged with disorderly conduct and one with
assaulting a police officer, Gentile said. He said officials were
investigating the incident.
   Earlier this year, members of the Nation of Islam beat a
television reporter and cameraman after they refused to turn over
videotapes that reportedly showed several Muslims assaulting a
suspected drug dealer. No charges were filed.
   Police later acknowledged that patrols by Farrakhan's followers
helped reduce narcotics trafficking at an apartment complex that
was one of Washington's most notorious drug marketplaces.
</TEXT>
