<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greenpeace     08-26 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greenpeace,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greenpeace Blocks Company Entrance in Baltic Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greenpeace activists dumped a pile of
dead fish in front of a chemical factory Friday and then chained
themselves to the gate to protest its discharges into the Baltic
Sea.
   Greenpeace member Ingrid Jutting told The Associated Press the
waste from the Kemira Oy company is killing fish in the Gulf of
Bothnia on Finland's southwestern coast.
   ``We don't deny that we are dumping 50,000 tons of ferrous
sulfate and other heavy metals and impurities into the sea,'' said
company spokesman Kalevi Tiihonen. He said the level was within
legal limits and would be reduced in the next four years.
   The Vuorikemia plant on the island of Reposaari produces 84,000
tons of titanium dioxide a year for use in paint, paper, plastic
and cosmetics. ``The problem is that with every ton of titanium
dioxide, over eight tons of sulfur dioxide waste is produced, which
Kemira dumps into the sea,'' Ms. Jutting said.
   ``Fishermen have reported that as much as 80 percent of their
catch has to be thrown away,'' said Ms. Jutting. ``The fish,
herring in particular, are often dead, deformed or too small to
eat.''
</TEXT>
