<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-US     08-26 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Says `Hostile Policy' Must Be Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's foreign minister said Friday
the United States must end what he called its ``hostile policy''
against his country before Hanoi will resume cooperation on
humanitarian issues.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said he sent a letter Aug. 10
to retired Gen. John W. Vessey, a special U.S. presidential envoy,
reaffirming Vietnam's opposition to congressional testimony July 28
by U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Gaston Sigur.
   Sigur had called for continued isolation of Vietnam until it
ends its decade-old occupation of Cambodia.
   Thach spoke with reporters after talks with Thai Prime Minister
Chatichai Choonhavan and Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila on the
last day of a five-day visit. He later flew home.
   Thach gave no details of his letter to Vessey, but said, ``The
cause (of suspension of cooperation) is there so to resume
(cooperation), you must liquidate the cause.''
   Vietnam said Aug. 3 it was temporarily halting participation in
efforts to account for U.S. servicemen missing in the war and in
resettling former political prisoners in the United States, despite
recent agreements on those issues.
   It cited Sigur's testimony as the reason for its decision.
   In his testimony Sigur argued against a congressional resolution
urging the establishment of ``interest sections'' _ diplomatic
missions below the level of embassies _ in Hanoi and Washington,
saying the move would not improve cooperation on humanitarian
issues.
   Thach and Vessey agreed a year ago that Vietnam would accelerate
its accounting of nearly 1,800 Americans missing in action, and in
return the United States would help Vietnam with its humanitarian
problems.
   Thach told Vessey in July that Vietnam would try to resolve 70
top priority MIA cases by year's end, and welcomed joint
excavations for remains between August and October.
   Also last month, the two countries held talks on a U.S. offer to
resettle former U.S. government employees and officials of the
American-backed South Vietnam government who were sent to
``re-education camps'' after the 1975 North Vietnamese victory.
   Thach said that in talks with the Thai foriegn minister he
reaffirmed Hanoi's willingness to take back Vietnamese refugees who
want to return and who pose ``the biggest burden to Thailand.'' But
he noted that ``forced mass repatriation is not humanitarian.''
</TEXT>
