<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Eckersley     08-26 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Eckersley,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Posponed for Brother of Oakland Pitcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A kidnapping and attempted murder
trial was postponed after the defendant's lawyer said it would hurt
the Oakland Athletics pennant chances and harm the career of his
client's brother, star pitcher Dennis Eckersley.
   A new trial date has been set Dec. 12 for Eckersley's older
brother, Wallace, 35, who is charged with the 1987 choking, beating
and stabbing of a 59-year-old woman and leaving her for dead.
   The trial was set Aug. 22, but a motion to postpone was filed
Aug. 4. District Court Judge James Franklin granted the motion
after a hearing and set the new trial date.
   The motion said a defense investigator recently visited
California ``following leads and witnesses in order to support the
defense of intoxication'' and had uncovered more potential
witnesses. Wallace Eckersley lives in Los Angeles.
   Wallace Eckersley's lawyer, Dennis Hartley, contended the motion
for postponement rested largely on the need for more time to
prepare a defense.
   But the two-page motion also dealt with Dennis Eckersley, 33,
and the effect the trial might have on his career if he were called
in midseason to testify.
   The document said Eckersley will be a ``critical'' defense
witness.
   ``Dennis Eckersley's ball club is in first place in their major
league division and will go to the playoffs in all likelihood,''
the court document said. ``The management of the club is absolutely
opposed to his appearance as a witness until after the baseball
season.
   ``The calling of Dennis Eckersley would cause tremendous adverse
publicity for his ball club and for himself and could have a
substantial effect on his major league career and this season in
particular. It would be grossly unfair to potentially ruin another
life or career in this situation,'' the document said.
   ``I think it's very interesting about this baseball,'' said the
victim, Sigrid Marie Griswold of Colorado Springs. ``When I read
the motion and found three paragraphs devoted to the baseball
issue, I was shocked.''
   Daniel Immel of Denver pleaded guilty to kidnapping in the case
and was sentenced in November to 48 years in prison. Wallace
Eckersley also pleaded guilty but changed his mind after Immel's
sentencing and asked for a trial.
   Reached by telephone in Oakland, Calif., Athletics General
Manager Sandy Alderson said Thursday he was not aware of a motion
to postpone and had not been contacted about the possibility of
Dennis Eckersley testifying.
   ``We were vaguely aware of something involving his brother,''
Alderson said. ``But we were not specifically aware of a trial
pending.''
   But Alderson added that ``clearly something of this sort would
be a distraction to Dennis during the course of the season. From
our standpoint, it would certainly be in our best interest that
Dennis not be involved.''
</TEXT>
