<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1557EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Portugal-Fire     08-26 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portugal-Fire,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Risk Of Collapsing Buildings Prevents Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoldering fires and the risk of
collapsing buildings Friday prevented investigators from finding
the cause of a blaze that destroyed much of the historic Chiado
shopping district.
   Civil engineers and other experts were told their inquiry would
have to wait until the fire completely subsided in the cellars of
the 150- and 200-year-old buildings that were used to store highly
combustible materials such as textiles and paper.
   Firefighters also said the burned-out shells of the Armazens do
Grandela and the Grandes Armazens do Chiado department stores were
probably beyond propping up and could collapse at any minute.
   The fire broke out in the Armazens do Grandela early Thursday
and in the next four hours swept through buildings on the narrow
streets of the neighborhood known for its speciality shops and
cafes where artists and writers gathered.
   One man died and 43 people, six of whom remained hospitalized
Friday, were injured.
   Fire officials say they don't know what caused the blaze, the
worst in the capital in 200 years. News reports raised the
possibility of arson.
   Union representatives said about 2,000 people, mostly clerical
and shop workers, lost their jobs.
   Lisbon Shopowners Association President Jose Ferreira de Matos
put damages at $600 million, nearly double the estimate of
insurance adjustors.
   He told a news conference that stores in the entire downtown
area would suffer from the effects of the fire despite official
promises to rebuild the Chiado.
   ``We fear that people will change their shopping habits,'' he
said. ``Remember that it took 14 years to restore the National
Theater after it burned.''
   Matos said 40 stores were destroyed, not counting the offices of
many lawyers and accountants on upper floors.
   Lisbon Mayor Nuno Kruz Abecasis, who met Thursday night with
architects, urban planners and cultural officials, told reporters
it would be a year before reconstruction of the area could begin.
   Matos called the old, battered state of the equipment used by
firefighters ``shameful.''
   The daily Correiro de Manha said reporters sent to the central
fire station discovered that none of the buildings destroyed in the
Chiado was connected to the department's centralized alert system.
   Neither of the two department stores had sprinkler systems
installed, and no recent fire inspections had been carried out in
the area's shops, the paper said.
   The weekly Sabado said the most serious outcome of the fire was
that Lisbon citizens, ``who have long lived with the impression
that their city is under permanent threat ... are now aware how
little is done to avoid such disasters.''
   Jorge Monteiro, owner of three stores destroyed in the Chiado
fire, urged Matos to demand an impartial inquiry into why the mayor
had ignored shopowners' protests and built stone planters and
tables in the middle of the Rua do Carmo that prevented
fire-fighting equipment from reaching the Armazens do Grandela
store.
   The Chiado district is in a part of Lisbon that was rebuilt
following a disastrous 1755 earthquake and fire that destroyed much
of the medieval part of the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1755EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SummerJobs     08-26 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summer Jobs,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Employment Rate At Record High; Blacks Show No Improvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young workers this summer are experiencing the
lowest unemployment rate since 1969 with a record 68.5 percent of
the nation's youths holding jobs, the Labor Department said Friday.
   The unemployment rate among workers aged 16-24 was 10.9 percent
in July compared with 11.7 percent a year ago, the department said.
   But all of the improvement was among whites; blacks did not
share in any of it, the government said. Only about half of the
nation's black youths have jobs this summer, compared with
three-fourths of white youths.
   ``Black youths continued to be about twice as likely as whites
to work in government jobs,'' said the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
``Their proportion in these jobs, however _ 12.6 percent this
summer _ has dropped 4 full percentage points from the high reached
two summers ago.''
   The jobless rate for white youths in July was 8.9 percent,
compared with 9.7 percent a year earlier. The rate among black
youths was almost three times higher _ 25.3 percent, the same as in
July 1987.
   The proportion of youths either working or looking for work
climbed to an all-time high of 78.6 percent in July, 0.6 percentage
point above what it was a year ago.
   But because of the continuing decline in the size of the youth
population, the actual number of young workers in the labor force
has fallen by 270,000 in the past year to 25.3 million, the
department said.
   Labor force participation among white youths has reached a
record 79.4 percent this summer after hovering around 78.6 percent
the past four years.
   ``In marked contrast,'' the government said, ``labor force
participation for black youths, which had dropped more than 2
percentage points between 1986 and 1987, held steady at 65.7
percent in July.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
