<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Miners     08-26 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Miners,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Meets Mine Strikers' Demands, Promises Tax Law
Amendments</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday described a
rare strike this week by 300 miners as ``regrettable'' but
understandable in view of economic hardships under an austerity
program.
   It said some of the workers' demands were met.
   State-run newspapers said the cabinet met Thursday and decided
to change regulations regarding sick leave pay to eliminate
contradictions the miners had asked be done away with.
   Judit Csehak, minister of social-welfare and health, said the
new regulations which would reduce sick pay received since Jan. 1
by about 10 percent would go into effect Oct. 1.
   The miners at the Komlo mine in southern Hungary had complained
that because of a quirk in tax laws introduced at the beginning of
this year, workers on sick leave could earn more than those working
regularly.
   Government spokesman Gyorgy Marosan said the government
considered the 20-hour strike ``regrettable and avoidable'' but
understandable ``under the circumstances,'' newspapers reported.
   The official news agency MTI reported that the government would
ask parliament to consider amendments to the tax bills before the
end of this year, but gave no details.
   In a letter to the government, the miners warned that the tax
``does not stimulate increased production or the undertaking of
extra shifts.''
</TEXT>
