<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Strike,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director Punishes Strikers by Locking Them Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of a textile plant
tried to discipline strikers by locking them up, it was reported
Friday.
   About 5,000 workers at the Makedonka plant in Stip in in the
southern republic of Macedonia staged a four-day strike this month
to protest low wages and living conditions, the Belgrade daily
Politika said.
   Ljiljana Velkova of the ready-made clothes department addressed
the workers and complained that she and 20 other workers were
locked in a room by director Livanta Naseva, the newspaper said.
   Ms. Velkova was in an advanced stage of pregnancy and became ill
while locked up, requiring hospitalization.
   Factory officials insisted that Ms. Naseva locked the door for
only five minutes, but Ms. Velkova was rushed to hospital 3{ hours
later, the paper said.

