<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 2033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Japan     08-26 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Japan,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zhao Tells Japan's Leader That China Has No Selfish Interests In
Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Soviet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leader Zhao Ziyang told Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita of Japan on Friday that China will never
seek to establish a sphere of influence in Cambodia.
   Zhao also urged Japan to invest more in China's coastal areas
and said an economically strong China will benefit Japan and the
rest of Asia.
   Takeshita's meeting with Zhao concluded two days of extensive
talks with Chinese leaders that both sides said heralded a new era
of close relations between the two Asian countries.
   Takeshita met earlier Friday with President Yang Shangkun and
senior leader Deng Xiaoping, who said their countries should seek a
``new type of relationship'' based on mutual trust, Japanese
officials and the official Xinhua News Agency reported.
   Zhao said China, main backers of the Khmer Rouge and other
anti-Vietnamese guerrillas in Cambodia, supports a democratic,
neutral government in the Southeast Asian nation.
   He said China ``has no selfish interests'' in Cambodia and would
not approve a return to power by the Khmer Rouge, who killed
hundreds of thousands of people during its 1975-78 rule.
   The national evening news quoted Zhao as saying a greater danger
was that the pro-Vietnam government of Hun Sen would use its
military strength to gain sole power.
   Zhao said China demands that Vietnam, which toppled the Khmer
Rouge in 1978 and installed Hun Sen, withdraw all its troops.
Vietnam has agreed to pull out its estimated 100,000 troops by 1990.
   Zhao said China seeks the formation of a four-party coalition,
including Hun Sen and the three-party resistance, headed by
resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Sihanouk, frequently at odds with his resistance partners, has
suggested he might seek a government with Hun Sen that would shut
out the Khmer Rouge.
   Zhao said the four factions should disband their armies and
establish a unified national defense army with each faction
contributing equal numbers of troops, the evening news said.
   Japanese officials said Takeshita agreed with China's approach
and was considering ways to contribute to a political settlement in
Cambodia. Japan has suggested it might help finance an
international peacekeeping force.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Takeshita did not offer to act as a mediator in the Cambodian
conflict.
   On Sunday, Foreign Ministry officials from China and the Soviet
Union, the main backer of Vietnam, will meet for the first time in
Beijing to probe ways to end the Vietnamese occupation and bring
peace to Cambodia.
   The Japanese officials said Zhao thanked Takeshita for Japan's
economic assistance and pushed for Japanese participation in his
pet project, the development of China's coastal areas into a vast
economic zone for export-oriented processing industries.
   On Thursday, at a meeting with Premier Li Peng, Takeshita
announced that Japan will provide $6.4 billion in loans for about
40 Chinese development projects in the 1990-95 period.
   Japan accounts for only about 8 percent of foreign investment in
China, well below Hong Kong and the United States, and China has
complained the Japanese are too cautious about putting their money
into Chinese projects.
</TEXT>
