<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Liberty-DrugTests 1stLd-Writethru a0594 08-26 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberty-Drug Tests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberty Students Face Mandatory Drug Tests</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Falwell comment; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LYNCHBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell said Friday he will
lead the way as faculty and administrators voluntarily submit to
the drug screening required this year of Liberty University's 6,000
students.
   ``All of us have agreed to voluntary drug testing at random and
several of us at the top, myself included, will be drug tested,''
said Falwell, the school's founder and chancellor.
   He said he knows of no other U.S. college or university that
tests all students for drugs. ``I'm hopeful they will watch what
we're doing and follow suit,'' he said.
   Liberty students were notified by mail over the summer and each
has signed a waiver agreeing to submit to urine screening.
   ``We have checked with thousands of young people and haven't
received a complaint,'' said Falwell, a television evangelist and
founder of the Moral Majority conservative lobbying organization.
   Urine-testing could begin next week and will include all
students during the program's first year, said Dr. Gregg Albers,
the school's director of health services.
   There are no plans to test employees of Falwell's other
organizations.
   Tests will be given to about 200 students a week in a special
bathroom designed to make it difficult for anyone to alter the
urine sample.
   The urine will be screened three times with the last test
breaking it down to the molecular level. Testing will be done for
illegal and abusable prescription drugs and will be used to spot
other health problems, Albers said.
   Students who test positive will be offered counseling, and
possibly a second chance.
   ``While the school takes a very strong position against drugs,
we're not going to be unreasonable in our methds,'' said Falwell
spokesman Mark DeMoss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
