<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Panama-Visas     08-26 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Visas,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Fires Consul Used by State Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian military leader Manuel Antonio
Noriega has fired the Panamanian consul in Tampa, Fla., whose
office had been used by State Department envoys for obtaining visas
for travel to that country, a Panamanian diplomat said Friday.
   The Noriega government has been rejecting visas approved by
Panama's consulate in Washington because it is staffed by officials
loyal to ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   As an alternative, American diplomats had been obtaining travel
documents from the Tampa consul, Elizabeth Martinez, who had
maintained ties with both the Noriega government and Delvalle
loyalists.
   But a Panamanian diplomat in Washington, a supporter of
Delvalle, said Ms. Martinez was fired this week by Noriega.
   A receptionist at the Tampa consulate, reached by telephone,
said Ms. Martinez was ill on Friday. She said she was unaware of
the report that Ms. Martinez had been removed from her post.
   A State Department official could not confirm that Ms. Martinez
had been fired but said the Noriega government was no longer
accepting visas signed by the Tampa consulate. The official and the
Panamanian diplomat insisted on anonymity.
   Another department official said U.S. diplomats have
alternatives other than the Tampa consulate for obtaining visas but
he refused to elaborate.
   The Reagan administration has declined to recognize the Noriega
government and regards Delvalle as the legitimate authority in
Panama even though he was ousted six months ago and has been in
hiding in Panama ever since.
   It also recognizes Delvalle's ambassador to Washington, Juan B.
Sosa, as the official Panamanian representative in the United
States.
   Sosa, who has ignored attempts by Noriega to replace him, told a
news conference Thursday that the embassy officially recognizes the
Tampa consulate, implying that Ms. Martinez had broken with Noriega.
   The New York Times said in its editions of last Sunday that the
Tampa consulate recently had approved visas for 14 American
officials who were either serving in Panama on expired visas or
recently assigned to Panama.
   The administration has barred its diplomats from having official
dealings with representatives of the Noriega government. As a
result, U.S. diplomats have been prevented from obtaining visas
from consuls loyal to Noriega.
</TEXT>
