<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Prisoner-AIDS     08-26 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prisoner-AIDS,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Indicted On Attempted Murder Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison inmate who tested positive for
the AIDS virus and allegedly spit on a correctional officer has
been indicted on a charge of attempted murder.
   Curtis Weeks, 27, who was serving a robbery sentence, told
several prison guards at the Department of Corrections Diagnostic
Center that he had AIDS and threatened to infect them, said David
Weeks, a special prosecutor. Curtis and David Weeks are not related.
   ``He carried it out by spitting on the officer,'' the prosecutor
said. ``This guy has a disease and he's using it aggressively
against other people.''
   Grand jurors who handed up the indictment Tuesday saw a video
recording of the prisoner's actions.
   Doctors said Curtis Weeks tested positive for HIV, which causes
the fatal acquired immune deficiency syndrome. There is no known
cure for the disease. Chances of AIDS transmission by saliva are
extremely low, said David Weeks.
   ``But the crux of the matter is his intent, even though he may
not be able to carry it out by that means,'' he said.
   The guard has experienced a ``great deal of trauma'' and must
have periodic blood tests to check for the presence of the virus,
said the prosecutor.
   Curtis Weeks faces a possible sentence of 25 years to life in
prison if found guilty of attempted murder.
</TEXT>
