<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-Kurds     08-26 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-Kurds,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kurds Claim 88 Civilians Killed In Iraqi Gas Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for Kurdish rebels said
Friday that 88 civilians were killed and 500 people injured when
Iraqi warplanes dropped poison gas bombs on five Kurdish villages
in northern Iraq a day before.
   Western diplomats in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad confirmed that
Iraq has launched a major assault on the Kurdish guerrillas now
that it has been freed from fighting Iran by a week-old cease-fire.
   Iraq's 3.5 million Kurds have been fighting for an independent
homeland for more than 50 years. The guerrillas formed an alliance
with Iran two years ago, opening a second war front that pinned
down tens of thousands of Iraqi troops badly needed in the main
battlefields to the south.
   Thursday's reported attacks on the Kurds came as Iranian and
Iraqi leaders met in Geneva for talks to end the nearly 8-year-old
war. Kurdish and Iranian officials have said Iraq has used an Aug.
20 cease-fire to intensify its campaign against the guerrillas,
while Iraq claims Iran is using the truce to regroup shattered
forces.
   Six fighter-bombers carried out the attack on five villages in
the Zakho and Amadiyah regions of northern Iraq near the Turkish
border, said the spokesman for the Kurdish Democratic Party. The
spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said 88 people died and 500 were
injured.
   The rebel spokesman called The Associated Press bureau in
Nicosia from a West European capital, which he refused to be
identified for ``security reasons.''
   The use of chemical weapons is outlawed under a 1925 Geneva
agreement.
   ``We appeal to the United Nations and the International
Committee of the Red Cross to offer their humanitarian assistance
to the gas victims through the Turkish Red Crescent,'' that
country's equivalent of the Red Cross, said the spokesman.
</TEXT>
