<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     08-26 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis is Lax on Crime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONGVIEW, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush on Friday accused
Michael Dukakis of lax crime policies, turning the tables on the
Democrat's criticism of Reagan administration drug efforts a day
before.
   During a campaign trip in his adopted home state, Bush also took
up the defense of his embattled running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle of
Indiana, telling a rally that Quayle would be ``an outstanding vice
president.''
   Bush told the rally in Eastern Texas that it was ``an insult''
for Dukakis to refer to President Reagan's drug policies as
``criminal'' and ``absurd'' when thousands of federal and local law
enforcement officials ``are putting their lives on the line every
single day to stop the narcotics flow.''
   Dukakis, Bush said, ``is the governor who vetoed the mandatory
sentencing for drug dealers. He opposes capital punishment for drug
king pins. And he fought tooth and nail to keep that outrageous
furlough program that lets murderers, rapists and drug dealers out
on appeal.''
   As to his own plans to combat drugs, Bush, who headed a Reagan
task force on drugs, said ``one way we must do it is support our
local law enforcement officers who are out there every day.''
   Bush also repeated his support for Quayle, who he has not
mentioned by name in two previous days of campaigning.
   Bush touted the congressional qualifications that the Bush
campaign had hoped to emphasize before Quayle became embroiled in
questions about using his family influence to join the National
Guard rather than be drafted during the Vietnam War.
   ``Here's a man elected twice to the Congress, twice to the
Senate, a wonderfully thoughtful person who has taken a leadership
role in job retraining ... but also is a member of the Armed
Services Committee, knows as I do that only a strong America can
prevent expansion of totalitarianism around the world,'' Bush told
a hall filled with about 2,500 supporters.
   ``He'll be an outstanding vice president.''
   Bush telephoned Quayle from his plane Friday morning, said Bush
chief of staff Craig Fuller. The vice president told Quayle, ``I
think things are going very well.''
   Bush last spoke to his 41-year-old running mate two days
earlier, said press secretary Shiela Tate, who said the two ``keep
in touch.''
   Bush aides said the campaign believes the firestorm over Quayle
has peaked. Quayle himself now refuses to answer further questions
about his National Guard service.
   Bush is pushing hard to tout his credentials as a Texan, a state
where he moved 40 years ago to go into the oil business and later
served as a member of the House.
   ``This is a key state and I'm not going to let them take it away
from me,'' he told the Longview rally. ``It's my state ... I
understand this state.''
   At the end of his speech, Bush briefly donned a white 10-gallon
hat. He put it on again at the airport before leaving Longview and
when he stepped off Air Force Two in Houston.
   He told the Texans he would do more for them than Dukakis,
highlighting their differences on energy, defense and gun control.
   ``My opponent opposes offshore drilling, and I support it,''
Bush said.
   He also called for a tax credit for oil exploration to increase
the industry drilling rig count, adding ``and I do know what a rig
count is.''
   He reiterated his support for the Strategic Defense Initiative
which Dukakis opposes. ``He says it is fantasy. I say it is
essential. I will support research vigorously and fully and when it
is ready I will deploy it,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
