<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DeSillers     08-26 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DeSillers,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seizure Ordered Of Jewelry, Other Items Bought By DeSillers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Friday ordered the seizure of jewelry and
other luxury items that Maria DeSillers allegedly bought with some
of the $690,000 donated by strangers last year for her dying son's
liver transplants.
   Dade Probate Judge Francis Christie granted a request from
lawyers for a court-appointed curator of the estate of Ronnie
DeSillers, who died in April 1987 at age 7. The order also struck
Ms. DeSillers' $150,000 claim on the estate.
   ``I'm going to ruin you, lady,'' a furious Ms. DeSillers said as
the curator, Karen Gievers, left the judge's chamber Friday. Ms.
Gievers ignored the comments and declined to say anything about
them later.
   ``You call this justice? She'll never run for public office in
this state,'' Ms. DeSillers said loudly as her attorneys sought to
quiet her.
   In a separate ruling Thursday, Christie dismissed Ms. Gievers'
request to hold Ms. DeSillers in contempt for not handing over
records of her purchases and the disputed items themselves, which
include a diamond-sapphire ring and diamond-studded gold cross.
   Being forced under threat of jail to turn over the records and
purchases could violate Ms. DeSillers' right against
self-incrimination, because criminal investigations are under way
in Dade and Broward counties, the judge had ruled Thursday.
   Michael Dribin, an attorney for Ms. Gievers, said having a third
party seize the items did not expose Ms. DeSillers to
self-incrimination. Friday's order does not cover the records, only
the disputed items.
   Ms. Gievers has estimated that the amount of donations that Ms.
DeSillers may have improperly spent on herself, family and friends
was $200,000.
   The seizure order does not list any dollar value for the items.
Besides the ring and the cross, it includes such things as an IBM
computer, a diamond-studded gold bracelet, about $4,000 in
furniture, a car phone and a gold watch.
   Ms. Gievers declined to say when the seizure might take place.
   The national spotlight turned on Ms. DeSillers in early 1987
after the theft of $4,000 raised by Ronnie's classmates for a
needed transplant. Donations poured in, including $1,000 from
President Reagan and $200,000 from Miami Beach millionaire Victor
Posner.
   Ronnie died after three failed liver transplants at Pittsburgh
Children's Hospital. His mother has refused to pay the $262,000
balance of his medical bill, claiming the boy received inadequate
care, a charge the hospital denies vehemently.
   Ms. Gievers, an attorney, was appointed curator of the child's
estate in March, after Ms. DeSillers' handling of the donations
came under fire when it was learned she rented an apartment in a
posh, waterfront apartment building and had purchased a used BMW
for $13,500.
   Roy Black, one of Ms. DeSillers' lawyers, 33, says some of his
client's purchases may not be improper as claimed because some of
the donations were given for her personal use.
   Black said his client has been unfairly portrayed as ``greedy
and grasping'' when she gave thousands of dollars to poor families
with sick children.
</TEXT>
