<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-26 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fair Weather Over Most Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The sky was clear and sunny over much of the nation Saturday
with only widely scattered precipitation.
   At midday, showers were scattered from central Arizona into
southern Nevada, over northwestern Montana and western South
Dakota, and across Florida and eastern Georgia.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms developed over New England.
   During the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 1.48 inches of rain fell
at Brunswick, Ga., but rain elsewhere was lighter.
   During the night, a severe storm spun off high wind that ripped
out windows and walls and cut power at the southern California town
of Baker, in the Mojave Desert.
   No injuries were reported but several mobile homes were damaged,
windows at numerous businesses were blown out and the back wall of
an auto service garage was knocked down, collapsing its roof, said
Baker firefighter James Meral.
   Officials estimated damage at $500,000 to $1 million. There was
no official reading on wind speed in the town 150 miles northeast
of Los Angeles.
   Midday temperatures Friday reached 100 over central Texas and
the desert Southwest, and near 100 from north-central Texas into
south-central Oklahoma.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 105 at Palm Springs, Calif.
Friday's low for the 48 states was 40 degrees at Aberdeen, S.D.,
and Bismarck, N.D.
   For Saturday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast over the
Florida Peninsula, from Michigan and Wisconsin into southeastern
Minnesota and northern Indiana, over Missouri, eastern Kansas and
Oklahoma, from southeastern Wyoming across Colorado, and from
central Arizona into southwestern Utah. Scattered showers were
forecast along the Virginia coast.
   High in the 60s were predicted over North Dakota and northern
Minnesota; in the 70s and 80s from New England into the Carolinas,
and over southern Florida, the remainder of the Great Lakes, across
the Ohio Valley, over the remainder of the northern half of the
Mississippi Valley, from South Dakota across northern Kansas, from
Montana across northern New Mexico, across the Pacific Northwest,
and along the California coast; from near 100 to about 105 over the
southern Plains; around 110 through the desert Southwest; and
generally in the 90s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
