<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Irish     08-26 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Found on Policeman's Car and Defused</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policeman spotted a bomb
attached to his car Friday and British army explosives experts
defused it, authorities reported.
   No group claimed responsibility for the bomb, but suspicion fell
on the Irish Republican Army.
   The officer, who was not identified, found the bomb while his
car was parked at his home in Sion Hills near Strabane in County
Tyrone, 115 miles west of Belfast.
   Later Friday, a court in the Irish Republic refused to block
extradition of Robert Russell to Northern Ireland, where he will
resume a 20-year prison sentence imposed in 1978 for the attempted
murder of a policeman.
   Russell, 30, is suspected of membership in the IRA, which is
outlawed on both sides of the border. He escaped from the Maze
Prison in Northern Ireland during a mass breakout in 1983 and has
fought extradition since.
   Members of Sinn Fein, the IRA's legal political wing, held a
vigil at Dublin's Mountjoy jail Friday to protest the decision.
   Police said the car bomb defused in Sion Hills contained three
pounds of the lightweight explosive called Semtex, which is made in
Czechoslovakia and has been used by the IRA in its current wave of
attacks on soldiers and other security personnel.
   About 150 families were evacuated from nearby homes while the
bomb squad conducted carefully controlled explosions over five
hours to make the device harmless, police said.
   The British Broadcasting Corp. reported Friday that
Czechoslovakia has promised to stop Semtex from reaching the IRA.
Security forces have said in the past the explosive was included in
arms shipments from Libya.
   A car bomb using Semtex killed a Royal Navy recruiting officer
Monday as he drove home from his office in Belfast.
   On the British mainland, funerals were held for six of eight
soldiers killed Aug. 19 in the IRA bombing of a bus near Omagh,
County Tyrone.
   ``The hope for Ireland is her ordinary people, who will never be
daunted by the men and women of violence,'' the Rev. Robert Ray
told 400 mourners at the funeral of Pvt. Jason Winter, 19, in
Lyngford, 120 miles west of London.
   About 10 miles farther west, leather-jacketed motorcyclists
accompanied the hearse of Pvt. Peter Bullock, 21, a fellow member
of the Somerset Sickle Bikers Club, to the cemetery at Stoke sub
Hamdon, Somerset.
   The bikers sent a wreath in the shape of a motorcycle wheel. It
joined another wreath, one of six sent to the funerals bearing the
message, ``From the people of County Tyrone.''
   Twenty-seven military personnel have been killed this summer by
IRA attacks in Northern Ireland, mainland Britain and continental
Europe. The bus attack was the deadliest since 1982.
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the republic,
which is overwhelmingly Roman Catholic.
   Labor Party lawmaker Tony Benn, who is making a left-wing
challenge to Neil Kinnock for the party leadership, said in
Glasgow, Scotland, that Britain should leave in January 1990.
   ``If a peacekeeping force is needed to cover the transition, it
should be a United Nations force,'' he said. ``The argument that
British troops must remain to stop bloodshed is completely invalid,
for these troops are a central part of the problem.''
</TEXT>
