<DOCNO> AP880826-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 2118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlaneCrash     08-26 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crash,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Investigators Combing Through Plane Crash Rubble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEMBROKE PINES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local officials have asked the
Federal Aviation Administration to investigate North Perry Airport
after a small plane crash killed three people, the latest in a
string of accidents at the airport, a county spokesman said Friday.
   Meanwhile, federal investigators were at the printing shop that
was destroyed when a twin-engine Piper Aerostar crashed shortly
after takeoff Thursday and exploded into flames. All three people
aboard the plane were killed.
   ``They are still there completing the on-scene investigation and
getting ready to move some of the wreckage,'' said George Prellezo
of the National Transportation Safety Board office in Miami. FAA
officials also are examining the wreckage.
   Before Thursday's crash, four people had been killed in 16
accidents involving planes taking off or landing at the airport in
this Fort Lauderdale suburb since 1982, Broward County spokesman
Ron Gardner said. The airport is used mainly by small planes.
   Gardner said FAA officials in Florida had agreed to the county
Aviation Department's request for an investigation. He also said
the department had asked the national Aircraft Owners and Pilots
Association and the North Perry Airport Safety Committee to examine
the airport's operations.
   Jack Barker, an FAA spokesman in Atlanta, said he was not aware
of plans to investigate the airport. Nevertheless, he said a
special FAA inspection of the facility in May found fewer safety
problems than a similar inspection a year before.
   County officials recently announced a $575,000 plan to add 1,000
feet to the 3,000-foot airport runways.
   ``This will put aircraft at a higher altitude when they cross
the airport's boundaries, and this gives a pilot who gets in
trouble the maneuverability area to possibly turn back to the
airport,'' Gardner said.
   Some residents of the densely populated neighborhoods
surrounding the airport strongly oppose to the small aircraft
traffic.
   ``I'm going to start a petition to get those small planes out of
here,'' said real estate broker Jeanette Piazza. ``I'm serious
about this.''
   According to witnesses and FAA reports, the six-seat Piper
circled several times before clipping power lines and plunging into
a strip shopping plaza about a mile from the runway.
   ``He didn't get very high, maybe 100 to 150 feet at the most,''
said Bruce Hill, an accident investigator with the NTSB.
   FAA spokesman Charles Wright in Atlanta said no flight plan was
filed and the plane's destination was unknown. But Gardner said
flight plans aren't required for many local flights.
   The dead pilot was identified as Lewis Phillips, 55, who owns
Lauderdale Aviation at North Perry. Names of his two passengers
were not immediately released.
   A typesetter at the printing shop, Kelli Crist, 24, suffered
burns over 27 percent of her body and was in critical condition at
Jackson Memorial Hospital in Miami, said spokesman Michael Mirando.
   Three other stores in the shopping center were destroyed.
Officials estimate the damage at about $1 million.
   ``I'm a pilot myself,'' said Phillips' widow, Pat. ``I know
there's been a lot of problems at that airport and I don't want it
to look bad or I don't want my husband to look bad.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
