<DOCNO> AP880826-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 2119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DroughtRelief     08-26 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Relief,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ag Department: Drought-Stricken Farmers Can't Collect Twice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers suffering drought losses will not be
allowed to double up on benefits under ongoing emergency livestock
feed provisions and the new disaster payment program, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Undersecretary Roland R. Vautour said that if a farmer has a
crop loss that would qualify him for both programs, he cannot
collect on the same loss twice.
   ``However, a livestock producer who has a loss of 1988 crop corn
production could receive emergency livestock feed assistance based
on part of his loss and disaster payments based on the remainder,''
Vautour said.
   The basic restrictions are spelled out by the Disaster
Assistance Act of 1988. Vautour said the while the statutory
provisions of the new law went into effect on Friday, the
regulations and operating procedures which will implement these
provisions have not been completed.
   ``Producers should start assembling their sales receipts and
other data to substantiate their actual production information,''
he said.
   Department officials have said they hope to begin actual
operation of the $3.9 billion drought-aid law by Oct. 1. At that
time, they hope, farmers can begin applying at country offices of
the department's Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation
Service for benefits.
</TEXT>
