<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Simon     08-26 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Simon,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Defends Sanctions Against South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Paul Simon defended U.S.
sanctions against South Africa on Friday, the end of a five-day
visit, and contended that most blacks support the measures.
   Simon, an Illinois Democrat who ran unsuccessfully earlier this
year for his party's presidential nomination, said the United
States has the responsibility to protest South Africa's system of
race discrimination.
   Referring to silence in America when Adolf Hitler first began
persecuting Jews, he said, ``We don't want to repeat that.''
   Simon heads the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on African
affairs and will have a major role in debate on pending legislation
to stiffen U.S. sanctions.
   At a news conference Friday Simon said Washington should wait
for greater political change before easing sanctions even if South
Africa's white authorities free Nelson Mandela, the African
National Congress leader who is serving a life prison sentence.
   ``One of the ways that dismay will be expressed is through
sanctions, by my country and increasingly by other nations also,''
Simon said.
   ``We find no pleasure in imposing sanctions. It is not done as
punishment, but as the only clear signal we know how to send that
we want this great country of yours to also become a just country.''
   Simon met with both government and opposition leaders during his
tour.
   He said some blacks he met opposed sanctions, but he said a
majority support them. Many Americans who oppose sanctions say they
hurt South African blacks more than the government, and South
Africa has made similar arguments.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   Government officials say they are pursuing gradual race reforms
and will not be hurried by sanctions.
   The sanctions approved by the U.S. Congress in 1986 forbid all
new public and private loans to this nation and bar trade in
certain products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
