<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Maotai     08-26 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maotai,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Stops Serving Liquor at State Banquets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fiery sorghum liquor maotai no longer will be
served at state banquets, the official media said Friday.
   Xinhua, the news agency, said the Foreign Ministry has decided
to stop serving hard liquor at banquets for foreign dignitaries.
Only wines were served Thursday night at a dinner given by Premier
Li Peng for Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita of Japan, the report
said.
   The government is conducting a campaign against public waste and
extravagance. The banquet, a popular function in China, is a prime
target.
   Menus now are to be held to four courses, not the customary 10
or 15, and feasting is expected to end in 1{ hours. The rule on
liquor follows removal of price controls on maotai and other
liquors, which caused huge price increases.
   A bottle of maotai, previously set at $5.40 but accessible only
to people with good connections, now costs more than $40.
</TEXT>
