<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Seals 1stLd-Writethru a0635 08-26 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seals, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0635,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say Seals Not Killed By Virus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with higher estimate of dead seals,
new seal deaths off Britain, upcoming meeting</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers have determined
something other than a viral epidemic killed thousands of North Sea
seals, but a government spokesman making the announcement Friday
refused to give the cause.
   Officials in London said seals had begun to die in British
waters and estimated more than 10,000 of the marine mammals have
died in recent months.
   If accurate, that estimate would represent a major increase in
the number. Scientists elsewhere in Western Europe have estimated
the number about 3,000 lower.
   Animal health experts and environmentalists had speculated
chemical pollution in the water may have lowered the seals' ability
to fight disease.
   The Dutch National Institute for Public Health and Environmental
Protection has determined what caused the seal deaths and is
working on a cure, according to a Health Ministry official who
spoke Friday on condition of anonymity. She said the researchers
would disclose their findings next week.
   Neither the herpes nor the picorna viruses widely held
responsible for the seal deaths are the main cause, the spokeswoman
said, adding that the findings resulted from months of research by
the institute and the Seal Clinic in the nothern Dutch village of
Pieterburen, western Europe's biggest hospital for seals.
   She said the researchers ``have proved it was one definite
factor'' that killed the seals. Although other factors may have
contributed to the disease, the spokeswoman said, ``it was the
straw that broke the camel's back. ... All the dead seals had it.''
   The disease apparently undermines the mammals' disease-fighting
immune system and they usually die of pneumonia or liver infection.
``Whether environmental pollution has played a role I don't know,''
she said.
   According to the spokewoman, the researchers are expecting to
disclose details of a possible cure for the disease when they
publish their findings Thursday in the British scientific magazine
Nature.
   ``All I'm allowed to say is that I'm very happy,'' Seal Clinic
director Lenie't Hart told The Associated Press.
   Since May 1, a total of 216 seals died along Britain's coasts
and 18 perished killed off Northern Ireland, officials of the
government-run Natural Environment Research Council said Friday in
London.
   Officials of the council's Sea Mammal Research Unit said more
than 10,000 seals have died in the North Sea. They estimated the
world population at 500,000.
   Previous estimates said up to 3,500 seals have died in West
German coastal waters and 3,000 more deaths had cut the Danish seal
population in half. More than 800 were reported to have died off
Norway and the Netherlands.
   Britain's Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals
said it had organized a conference for next Tuesday to formulate
plans to handle the immediate problems created by dead and dying
seals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
