<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VFW-Fonda 1stLd-Writethru   08-26 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-VFW-Fonda, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0676,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>VFW Calls for Jane Fonda To Be Tried for Treason</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `Fonda's spokesman...' with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with publicist's comment and background on agreement Fonda
reached with Justice Department in 1972; picks up 8th graf pvs,
`One resolution.'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane Fonda's apology for supporting North Vietnam
during the Vietnam War has failed to impress the Veterans of
Foreign Wars, who voted to ask Congress to try her for treason.
   During their 89th annual convention this week, 13,400 VFW
delegates adopted three resolutions concerning Fonda, including one
saying ``a mere apology is not enough to redeem the situation.''
   The VFW also denounced her upcoming movie ``Union Street,'' and
called for her ``to be tried by the United States government as a
traitor.'' The last resolution passed unanimously by voice vote.
   ``How do you go back 20 years and make amends?'' VFW spokesman
Vern Pall said. ``What is this woman really after? This is no way
to redeem the hurt and pain she caused those troops in Vietnam.''
   Fonda, an ardent opponent of U.S. involvement in Vietnam, took a
highly publicized trip to Hanoi in 1972.
   Last June, at her request, she appeared on the ABC program
``20-20,'' saying she was ``very sorry for some of what I did.''
   Fonda's publicist, Steve Rivers, said Friday from Los Angeles,
``The Justice Department stated in 1972 that Jane hadn't done
anything wrong.''
   Fonda reached an out-of-court settlement with the federal
government in 1979 in which she agreed not to press a $1 million
lawsuit, in exchange for the FBI's admission that it spied on her
improperly and its promise to adhere to Justice Department
guidelines in the future.
   One resolution passed by the group Wednesday said the VFW ``is
not insensitive to a sincere expression of contrition.''
   ``But the VFW wants to be assured that the `apology' is not
simply a means of bolstering her sagging career and political
fortunes,'' it said.
   Fonda's husband, California Assemblyman and former anti-war
activist Tom Hayden, has faced similar campaigns, including an
unsuccessful attempt by veterans groups to have him ousted from the
legislature as a ``traitor'' in 1986.
</TEXT>
