<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0630 08-26 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0630,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moslem Areas on Strike over Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with two bomb attacks, ADD
background on Syrian troops, picks up graf 8 pvs `Parliament
failed...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs jolted the Moslem part of the
city Friday and residents joined a strike against what they view as
Israeli and U.S. support for Christian militias blocking election
of a pro-Syrian president.
   The bombs exploded in west Beirut in the early evening within
hours of each other, police said, but no casualties were reported.
   One went off at a garbage dump and the other in a narrow street
off a commercial district. They shattered windows and wrecked
shutters of shops in both areas. No group claimed responsibility.
   In South Lebanon, U.N. peacekeeping troops what they suspected
of being a car bomb but the vehicle did not contain explosives.
   The strike closed government offices, banks, shops, restaurants,
gasoline stations, amusement centers and other businesses in west
Beirut and areas policed by Syrian soldiers. Sponsors said
bakeries, pharmacies, hospitals and the news media were exempt.
   However, life was normal in Christian east Beirut and the
385-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of the capital, police
said.
   The Lebanese Forces, the main Christian militia, opposed the
strike and a spokesman described it as ``a reflection of Syria's
hegemony.''
   ``The Syrians have forced their surrogates to call the strike
after the defeat of their candidate in the first round of the
presidential elections,'' the Lebanese Forces official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Syria is Lebanon's main power broker. It has 40,000 soldiers
stationed in the north and south and in sections of Beirut.
   Parliament failed Aug. 18 to muster the needed quorum to elect a
president. The only serious candidate was Suleiman Franjieh,
Syria's closest Christian ally in Lebanon and a personal friend of
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   Leftists and Moslem militia leaders have blamed Parliament's
failure to elect Franjieh, 78, on American and Israeli opposition.
   Beirut's leading independent daily paper An-Nahar said last week
the quorum was not achieved because the United States opposed the
election of a ``confrontational candidate.''
   Several businessmen in west Beirut voiced doubt that the strike
would lead to the election of a new head of state before the
six-year term of President Amin Gemayel expires Sept. 23.
   ``This is playacting,'' said a grocer who identified himself
only as Abu Musbah. ``I don't believe that a president brought in
by a strike would be good for a country which has been on strike
for years.''
   He was referring to the 13-year-old civil war, which has claimed
more than 130,000 lives and shattered the nation's economy, once
the most flourishing in the Middle East.
   A spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon said Fijian
soldiers found the red Renault deserted a few yards from their
checkpoint and reported it was rigged with ``a quantity of
explosives.''
   The peacekeepers' Swedish engineers fired two anti-tank shells
at the car almost seven hours after it was discovered deserted, the
spokesman said.
   ``The shells exploded destroying the vehicle. There was no other
explosion, apparently the car didn't contain any explosives,'' said
the spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   U.N. troops sealed off the area and blocked traffic along the
coastal highway south of the port of Tyre after the car was
discovered.
</TEXT>
