<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-ChemicalWeapons 1stLd-Writethru a0748 08-26 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Chemical Weapons, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0748,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Condemns Chemical Attacks Against Iranians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, Kurds have ... UPDATING
with British ambassador's comment, preamble text expressing dismay.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, Iraq admitted ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf-Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council condemned on Friday
the use of chemical weapons in the Iran-Iraq war, expressing deep
dismay over their ``more intense and frequent'' use against Iran.
   The 15 council members voted unanimously to condemn the use of
chemical weapons a violation of a 1925 Geneva protocol.
   The British-sponsored resolution did not name Iraq as the
attacker but cited reports by U.N. chemical weapons experts
accusing the government in Baghdad of using poison gas, including a
mustard gas attack on an Iranian city Aug. 2.
   At that time, both Iran and Iraq had accepted Security Council
Resolution 598 demanding a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war, but no
truce date had been set.
   Peace talks opened Thursday in Geneva. A Kurdish guerrilla
group, the Kurdish Democratic Party, claims Iraq dropped poison gas
bombs on six Kurdish villages in northern Iraq that day.
   Kurds have been fighting Iraq, Iran and Turkey for more than 50
years for a separate homeland.
   Sir Crispin Tickell, the British ambassador to the United
Nations, said, ``There are extremely delicate discussions taking
place in Geneva at the moment. We would not wish to do anything to
upset those discussions.
   ``The resolution makes perfectly clear in the preamble who we
think has been using chemical weapons, and I think it's best for
the moment to leave it at that.''
   The preamble notes the Security Council is ``deeply dismayed by
the (investigative) missions' conclusions that there had been
continued use of chemical weapons in the conflict between Iran and
Iraq and that such use against Iranians had become more intense and
frequent.''
   Iraq admitted last month that it had used chemical weapons, but
claimed Iran used them first. Iran says it has the ability to
produce such weapons but has not done so.
   The resolution asked other nations to halt the export of
chemicals used to produce such weapons, and encouraged
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar to promptly investigate
allegations of the use of chemical weapons.
   It noted the continuing negotiations of the Conference on
Disarmament in Geneva on banning the development, production and
stockpiling of chemical weapons and arranging the destruction of
current stockpiles.
   The 1925 Geneva protocol bans the use of chemical and biological
weapons but does not prohibit their manufacture.
   The Security Council passed a similar resolution in May, but
that one did not specifically cite the use of chemical weapons
against Iranians.
   On Tuesday, the Security Council released a report by U.N.
investigators that blamed Iraq for using mustard gas Aug. 2 in an
air raid on Oshnaviyah, an Iranian city near the northeast corner
of Iraq.
   U.N. experts found chemical and medical evidence of mustard gas
use, and found splinters of shells similar to those found after
attacks on Iranian civilians in 1984, 1986, 1987 and earlier this
year, ``indicating their utilization during an Iraqi air attack on
Oshnaviyeh.''
   Iranian authorities said the air raid injured 2,680 civilians.
No deaths were reported. The U.N. experts interviewed 24 patients
who were still hospitalized when they visited the areas Aug. 12-14.
   Council members stood for a minute of silence at the opening of
their meeting Friday in memory of Pakistan's President Mohammad Zia
ul-Haq, who died in a plane crash Aug. 17.
</TEXT>
