<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FreezerMurder 1stLd-Writethru a0672 08-26 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Freezer Murder, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts In Murder Of Woman Who Was Dismembered, Frozen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with jury recommendation for
sentence. Picks up 4th graf, `Bailey's 14-year-old...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Friday convicted a man of murdering
and dismembering a prostitute whose remains were discovered three
years later, stuffed in a back porch freezer.
   The 12-member panel later returned to deliberations and
unanimously recommended James Warren Bailey, 45, of Tampa be
electrocuted for the March 1985 slaying of Kimberly Ann Hanlon.
   In Florida, a jury recommendation is not binding on the judge,
who in capital cases has the final say between life in prison and
death. Hillsborough Circuit Judge Richard Lazzara set sentencing
for Sept. 26.
   The jury convicted Bailey after more than five hours
deliberations over two days.
   Hanlon, 27, was shot once in the back of the head. Her limbs and
head were then severed with a power saw.
   Bailey's 14-year-old daughter tipped police after she and a
friend found the frozen body on the family's cluttered back porch
in March.
   The state argued that Hanlon was killed because she was dealing
drugs for Bailey and he thought she had cheated him.
   James A. Whyte, 26, a two-time Florida felon with an admitted
drug problem, testified for the prosecution that he helped hold the
woman at Bailey's home while she was beaten and raped by Bailey and
co-defendant Irvin George Riley, a 28-year-old former Martins
Ferry, Ohio, resident who is schedued for trial on the same charges
later this year.
   Whyte testified that Riley, on Bailey's orders, shot Ms. Hanlon
as Bailey held down her arms and Whyte laid across her legs. Bailey
then cut off her arms, legs and head with a power saw, Whyte said.
   Whyte was promised 25 years probation in a plea bargain with
prosecutors for his testimony.
   ``It must be clear to you that I don't like making deals with
people like Mr. Whyte,'' Assistant Hillsborough State Attorney Mike
Benito told jurors in closing arguments. ``I made a deal with this
guy so you would hear what Mr. Bailey did to Kimberly Hanlon. I
think you needed to know that.''
   Defense attorney Bob Fraser noted that after Bailey was arrested
in March authorities had only a circumstantial case until Whyte
voluntarily contacted police four months later and offered details.
   ``He probably knew there was a body in the freezer. He must
have,'' Fraser said in his closing statement. ``But that doesn't
mean he killed it. ... Whoever killed her loathed her ... For you
to convict my client on Whyte's testimony is preposterous.''
   Bailey did not take the stand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
