<DOCNO> AP880826-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Shroud 1stLd-Writethru a0729 08-26 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Shroud, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0729,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Dismiss Newspaper Report that Shroud Of Turin Is A Fake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout, UPDATING with
coordinator of tests saying nothing final yet. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY21</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British newspaper reported Friday that the
Shroud of Turin, said to have been wrapped around Jesus after his
crucifixion, is a fake but experts discounted the newspaper report
as unsubstantiated rumor.
   ``As yet, we do not have a final figure,'' Dr. Michael Tite said
Friday night in an interview on Independent Television News.
   The 14-foot cloth kept in Turin Cathedral in Italy bears the
image of a bearded, crucified man.
   Tite is coordinater of radio-carbon dating tests made on the
cloth by Oxford University, the University of Arizona at Tucson,
and the Federal Polytechnic in Zurich, Switzerland.
   He said results from each testing center have been circulated to
the others ``with a proposal for a coordinated date on the shroud
from the samples, but I haven't heard from anyone as of yet.''
   Tite is keeper of the British Museum's research laboratory and
supervised the Oxford tests.
   The London Evening Standard reported without attribution Friday
that radio-carbon dating tests conducted by scientists at Oxford
University showed the shroud was made about 1350.
   However, it quoted Dr. Richard Luckett of Magdalene College,
Cambridge University, as saying: ``I think that as far as seems
possible the scientific argument is now settled and the shroud is a
fake. I suppose there will be certain people who will never believe
it but it seems unlikely'' that the tests could be 1,300 years off.
   ``This report is without any serious foundation,'' said Susan
Black of the British Society for the Holy Shroud of Turin,
established 10 years ago to pursue investigations into the cloth.
   ``There have been so many of these type of reports and they're
all rumors. It's all got totally out of hand.''
   All three institutions conducting tests agreed to keep their
findings secret and forward them to the Roman Catholic Church in
Italy for an official announcement in September or early October.
   Both Luckett and Professor Robert Hedges, head of the
radio-carbon dating laboratory at Oxford which was responsible for
the tests, were unavailable for comment Friday.
   Luckett, whose university is an ancient rival of Oxford, was not
connected with the tests but has been associated with
investigations of its history.
   In Turin, Professor Luigi Gonella, the liaison between Cardinal
Anastasio Ballestrero of Turin and the three laboratories, said he
had received no word from Oxford and was ``amazed'' by the Evening
Standard report.
   Gonella said Oxford scientists made blind-tests on three samples.
   ``They were asked to date the three samples, not to determine
which of them belongs to the shroud,'' he said.
   He confirmed that the Oxford experiments were completed but said
results wouldn't be released until after scientists from the three
laboratories met to coordinate them.
   Tite said earlier Friday that an announcement on results ``will
be made in September or early October by Turin via the Vatican
press office.''
   He said each laboratory received three samples of cloth, but
were not told what they were. He said samples were taken from the
shroud and from medieval and other cloths.
   ``It was blind-testing,'' he said.
   Announcement of the results is expected to come from
Ballestrero, who authorized thumbnail-size samples to be cut from
the shroud kept in his cathedral.
   University of Arizona geoscientist Paul E. Damon and physicist
Douglas J. Donahue headed the Arizona study of the shroud, but
declined comment.
   Spokeswoman Janet Bingham said she was ``pretty sure our guys do
not know the results from the other institutions,'' and that the
Arizona scientists ``just can't make any comments until it's the
official announcment. They will not comment on any rumors.''
   Ms. Bingham said she had spoken with Tite, who ``assures me that
they have not released any information.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
