<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 2145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan     08-26 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Calls Press Censorship a Mistake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi said
censoring foreign media this week was an overreaction to
unfavorable coverage of floods and Sudan's lagging relief efforts.
The restrictions are being dropped.
   He told an Italian television interviewer Thursday that
falsehoods had been written about the situation in Sudan but the
censorship was a mistake.
   Abdullah Jallab, acting undersecretary in the Information
Ministry, told The Associated Press on Friday: ``We do not have
censorship, and we do not believe in its effectiveness.''
   Information Minister el-Sayed Abdallah Mohammed Ahmed, ordered
foreign journalists and photographers Wednesday to take pictures
and interviews only while accompanied by a ministry representative.
He also said news or photos could not be sent from Sudan without a
censor's stamp.
   El-Mahdi said Thursday that Sudan ``is a free country with an
independent judiciary'' and anyone whose rights are violated by the
press has recourse to the courts.
   Jallab, interviewed in English, said Friday: ``The prime
minister is the highest executive ... so his statement would
eventually cancel any previous measures.''
   Sudanese officials, including the prime minister have denounced
stories in foreign news media attributing corruption and
incompetence to the relief effort for 1.5 million people left
homeless by three weeks of flooding in the Khartoum area.
   Jallab said no journalist had been censored and none would be.
He said ministry representatives assigned to accompany
photographers and television crews were there to help with
logistics, not to censor.
   ``We are only facilitating their missions. We do not tell them
what to do,'' Jallab said. ``One of the reasons that led to the
ouster of the former regime was the lack of press freedom.''
   The measures Ahmed outlined were similar to those in effect
during most of the 16-year rule of Gaafar Nimeiri, whose presidency
ended in a military coup in April 1985.
   El-Mahdi's civilian government took over a year later and has
maintained some of the most liberal press laws in Africa.
</TEXT>
