<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-Politics     08-26 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Politics,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Opposition Spars With Governing Party Over Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CONCEPCION BADILLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition lawmakers showed up Friday at the
House of Deputies for a continuing session to certify the results
of July elections, and a governing party leader threatened to go
ahead without them if necessary.
   Opposition deputies had walked out of the session early Thursday
to protest what they view as the governing party's unwillingness to
check reports of voting fraud in the elections. They returned to
the chamber Thursday afternoon.
   Lawmakers pledged Friday to work round-the-clock if need be to
install a new national House of Deputies in time for outgoing
president Miguel de la Madrid's state-of-the union address Thursday
to a joint session of lawmakers.
   The political sparring reflects a new atmosphere resulting from
the elections. The opposition made major gains against the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known by its Spanish initials
PRI, which has dominated national politics for nearly 50 years.
   President Miguel de la Madrid is expected on Sept. 1 to formally
present his successor elected in July, Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
Salinas officially takes over for a single six-year term in
December.
   Opposition leaders say the voting was riddled with fraud and
challenge the official results that give Salinas a victory with 50
percent of the vote. His two leading challengers have barnstormed
the country urging people to reject the election results.
   ``The pressure for time is on, and this will oblige the deputies
to sit continuously in the House,'' congressional spokesman Pedro
Pablo Trevino said in a telephone interview.
   Trevino said a majority of deputies had agreed to stay
round-the-clock in permanent session through the weekend if
necessary to certify the vote count.
   The proceedings have unfolded in a raucous atmosphere, with
opposition sympathizers chanting, whistling, and throwing coins and
other objects from the public galleries. The session resumed Friday
with all public but the news media excluded.
   The deputies are sitting as an electoral college to certify the
results of their own elections, and the Senate members have been
doing the same. The House later will certify the presidential vote
count.
   Guillermo Jimenez Morales, leader of the PRI bloc, told
reporters that if necessary, the PRI can muster a bare majority of
one vote, install the lower chamber and proceed with business
without the opposition.
   According to the preliminary vote count, the PRI should get 247
of 500 House seats and the opposition 227, with 26 seats undecided.
   The PRI has never lost a major election since it was formed in
1929 years ago and usually won the presidential race by more than
70 percent of the votes cast.
   Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, a dissident who broke away from the PRI in
November to demand a cleaner electoral process, came in second on
the leftist National Democratic Front ticket with 31 percent. He
claims he actually won the election.
   The conservative National Action Party's Manuel J. Clouthier
came in third with 17 percent.
   Also, for the first time in six decades, the PRI lost four seats
in the Senate _ all to the Cardenas coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
