<DOCNO> AP880826-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 2014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LastTemptation     08-26 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Temptation,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Last Temptation Of Christ' Comes To Utah</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for ATLANTA-dated item on AMs News Advisory.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The opening of ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' in Salt Lake
City was delayed Friday because someone broke into the movie
theater, stole the film and slashed a screen, police said.
   The Centre Theatre canceled the first showing of Martin
Scorsese's film, but found another copy and held its second
scheduled showing, said Salt Lake City Detective Lt. Mel Shields.
   The movie also made its debut Friday in Atlanta, the heart of
the Bible Belt, with about 300 protesters singing and praying
outside. In Denver, 50 protesters sang hymns and preached in an
attempt to dissuade the nearly 300 people who attended the first
showing there.
   In Atlanta, the movie showed on two screens in a theater complex
at Phipps Plaza, in trendy Buckhead, north of downtown. A short
line began forming two hours before the first show, a mall official
said.
   The movie opened last week in Texas, Arizona and Michigan,
attracting hundreds of pickets. The previous week, the movie opened
in seven U.S. cities, attracting thousands of demonstrators.
   Protesters have objected to the film's portrayal of Christ. The
movie's last scene depicts Christ, while hanging on the cross,
hallucinating about abandoning his role as Savior, having sex with
Mary Magdalene and raising a family. He rejects the temptation.
   The movie has been condemned by Utah's predominant Mormon Church
and other conservative religious denominations nationwide. Some
groups have called for a boycott of the film, and of MCA, the
parent company of Universal Pictures.
   In Salt Lake City, an employee at the theater referred questions
to Cineplex-Odeon spokeswoman Linda Friendly in Toronto, but a
secretary said she had left the office for the day.
   Shields said there were signs that a side door to the downtown
theater was forced. Inside, police found 5-foot-long slashes on the
theater's screen.
   It was not known how the film was shown.
   Police had no suspects, Shields said.
   ``I don't understand what all the big deal is about,'' Kirk
Smith, 30, of Atlanta said after watching the movie there. He said
he had wanted to see it ``before all the hullabaloo started, but
after that started I just wanted to see it more.''
   The protesters marched, sang religious songs, prayed and held a
rally in an area in front of the mall that had been cordoned off
for them.
   Entertainer Pat Boone, in Atlanta for an appearance at an
amusement park, stopped by. ``I don't need to see the film,'' he
told demonstrators. He said he had begun to read the novel on which
the film is based years ago, ``and when I saw where it was going I
put it down.''
   Mall management not only cordoned off an area for the
protesters, but also provided them with portable lavatories and
power for their sound system.
   ``It's because we realize everyone in this issue has rights,''
said Mark Craft, a spokesman for MSA Managment, which runs the mall.
   Craft said business had not been hurt by the controversy. ``If
anything, business is up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
