<HEAD>Man Accused Of Threatening President Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man arrested after allegedly making threats
on President Reagan's life was admitted Friday to a psychiatric
hospital for observation and treatment.
   Frank Colby Sills, 35, was transferred to the Clifton T. Perkins
Hospital on the recommendation of two doctors who examined him
under a court order issued earlier in the day, said Mercy Hospital
spokesman Chris Zang.
   U.S. Magistrate Paul Rosenberg said he was ``satisfied that the
individual may be suffering from a serious mental illness which may
require immediate treatment, in that there is a reasonable cause to
believe that as a result of the mental illness the individual may
be dangerous to himself and others.''
   The arrest came after the Secret Service was contacted Thursday
evening by police in Frederick, Md., who apprehended the man at a
truck stop. Officials said no decision had been made on whether to
press charges against the man.
   ``He did make threatening statements against the president to
police officers and he was subsequently taken into custody by my
agents,'' said Joseph R. Coppola, special agent in charge of the
Secret Service in Baltimore.
   ``He had been traveling in a pickup truck from Indiana to Ohio
where he met a truck driver and offered him $600 to drive him and
his truck to Washington, D.C.,'' Frederick Police Chief Richard
Ashton said. ``So he put his pickup on the back of this other guy's
truck and the closer they got to D.C., the more bizarre this guy's
behavior got. He started talking about killing President Reagan and
blowing up the Pentagon.''
   A Secret Service agent said the man claimed to be from Fort
Wayne, Ind., but the federal public defender released no
biographical information.
