<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SAfrica-BlackTownship     08-26 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Black Township,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Government Bid to Transfer Black City to Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court rejected a government
bid Friday to merge the country's second-largest black township
with an impoverished homeland 180 miles away.
   The union, decreed by President P.W. Botha last December, met
widespread opposition among the half-million residents in the
township of Botshabelo. Many feared the government would declare
the distant homeland, Qwaqwa, to be independent and deprive them of
South African citizenship.
   Botshabelo, comprised mostly of clusters of shanties spread
across a treeless plain, is in Orange Free State, the most sparsely
populated and conservative of South Africa's four provinces.
   A three-judge panel of the provincial Supreme Court declared
Botha's proclamation invalid Friday, saying it would not promote
the political development of Botshabelo's residents.
   The government issued no statement after the ruling, made in
response to a case brought by township resident Gauta Lefuo. The
government can appeal the ruling.
   Governing officials said the merger is compatible with their
longstanding policy of locating black ethnic groups in
self-governing or nominally independent homelands. Botshabelo is
made up predominantly of South Sotho people, as is Qwaqwa.
   But the judges said there were few similarities between
Botshabelo and Qwaqwa, aside from ethnicity.
   Established nine years ago, Botshabelo has been depicted by
anti-apartheid activists as a dumping ground for blacks not needed
or wanted in the rest of the Orange Free State. Most of its
residents were expelled from white-owned farms.
   The homeland policy is part of the nation's policy of racial
segregation known as apartheid. By law and custom, apartheid
establishes a racially segregated society in which South Africa's
26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools
and health services.
   After pamphlets were dropped from security force helicopters
announcing the merger, nine Botshabelo clergymen wrote to Botha.
They warned that the situation was ``a recipe for frustration and
resultant violence.''
   ``It is unfeasible that one of the poorest self-governing states
should administer and develop the second-largest black township in
South Africa,'' the clergymen said.
   Soweto, near Johannesburg, is the largest black township in the
country.
   The judgment marked the second major court defeat this year for
the government's policy of homeland consolidation.
   The country's highest court, the Appeal Court, ruled last April
that Botha had acted without proper authority when he incorporated
the 120,000-member community of Moutse into the adjoining,
semi-autonomous homeland of KwaNdebele, northeast of Pretoria.
   Most Moutse residents do not belong to the Ndebele tribe that
predominates in KwaNdebele.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
