<HEAD>President's Hearing And Allergy Conditions Unchanged</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 7 grafs to UPDATE with results of president's
hearing examination; pickup 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``Reagan is...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan continues to suffer from
mild hearing loss in his left ear and moderate hearing loss in his
right ear, his physicians reported Friday.
   ``There has been no change in the president's hearing deficit in
the past ten years,'' White House physician Dr. Larry Mohr said in
a statement issued following Reagan's annual hearing examination.
The exam was conducted at the president's penthouse suite in the
Century Plaza Hotel.
   The statement said Reagan's two hearing aids also were checked
and ``are working perfectly.'' The president wears hearing aids in
both ears and he ``continues to have the same mild hearing loss in
the left ear and moderate hearing loss in the right ear that he has
had on previous examinations,'' the statement said.
   The president was examined by three physicians, including his
longtime ear, nose and throat specialist, Dr. John House. Reagan
started to use a new type of hearing aid last year and he has had
no complaints. He can adjust the volume by using a credit card-size
control.
   Earlier Friday, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
president's allergist had determined there has been no essential
change in his sensitivity to pollen.
   Reagan, who receives weekly shots to control the allergy, has
been undergoing a battery of annual checkups in the midst of his
traditional August vacation.
   The president was examined Thursday by his longtime allergist
Dr. Ralph Bookman, and the checkup ``was routine,'' the spokesman
said.
   Reagan is spending a week of his August vacation here with his
wife, Nancy.
   Outside of appearing at campaign rallies for Vice President
George Bush and Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., the president has left
his suite only for private dinners with old friends in the evenings.
   The Reagans are scheduled to return to their ranch near Santa
Barbara on Saturday after attending fund-raising events for the
California Republican Party and for Rep. Robert Lagomarsino,
R-Calif.
   Fitzwater said the party event, in Thousand Oaks, Calif., will
be attended by 350 to 400 people who either contributed or gathered
$5,000 per person for GOP campaign coffers.
   About 1,000 people, contributing $200 apiece, were to attend the
fund-raiser for Lagomarsino near Santa Barbara, Fitzwater said.
   The Reagans have no public events scheduled next week and are to
remain at the ranch until after Labor Day, he said.
</TEXT>
