<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Israel     08-26 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Israel,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Calls for End of Palestinian Deportations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Security Council on Friday asked
Israel to stop deporting Palestinians and expressed concern over
growing violence in the Israeli-occupied territories.
   After private consultations, Council President Li Luye of China
read a statement saying, ``The members request Israel immediately
to desist from deporting any Palestinian civilians and immediately
to ensure the safe return of those already deported.''
   Since the start of the Palestinian uprising last Dec. 8, Israel
has deported 33 Palestinians and ordered another 25 expelled from
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The Israelis say those
covered by the orders helped foment the unrest, which has killed
254 Arabs and four Israelis.
   The U.N. statement said the deportations violate Security
Council resolutions and Geneva accords.
   It also said Security Council members are worried that the
violence ``has grave consequences for endeavors to achieve a
comprehensive, just and lasting peace in the Middle East.''
   The United States also has criticized Israel's deportation
policy.
</TEXT>
