<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0700 08-26 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0700,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine-Year-Old Girl Wounded, Suspected Collaborators Attacked</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 2 grafs to UPDATE with U.N. asking Israel to stop
deportations.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded a 9-year-old
Palestinian girl Friday when she violated a curfew by running out
of her West Bank home, an Arab hospital official said.
   In the Gaza Strip, a mob of Palestinians attacked a fellow Arab
alleged to have cooperated with Israeli authorities, and news
reports said another alleged collaborator opened fire a day earlier
on a Palestinian mob that was blocking his way in the West Bank,
wounding a teen-ager.
   The incidents were the latest in a series of Palestinian attacks
on suspected collaborators, including three in the past week.
   Also Friday, 14-year-old Aymen Yammen died from a gunshot wound
to the eye that he suffered during clashes last week in the West
Bank village of Tal, officials at Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital
said.
   The fatality raised the Palestinian death toll in the
8-month-old Arab uprising to 254. Four Israelis have also died.
   In Arab east Jerusalem, the army closed a trade union for a
year, alleging its members held meetings to initiate anti-Israeli
protests, an army spokesman said. It was the 10th union to be
closed since the Arab uprising began Dec. 8.
   Israel's right-wing Trade Minister Ariel Sharon accused
Palestinian trade unions of acting as ``cover-ups for terror
organizations.''
   ``They are not an innocent workers' union but front
organizations behind which the PLO's political arm has been hiding
for years,'' Sharon told Israel radio.
   Sharon also denounced an upcoming U.S. review of Israel's trade
privileges because of alleged abuses of Palestinian workers' rights.
   The American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee, a
pro-Palestinian lobby in Washington, has accused Israel of closing
down union offices indiscriminately, arresting Arab labor activists
and denying trade union protection to more than 100,000 Arabs in
the territories who travel to jobs in Israel.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said Thursday he would
review Israel's duty-free trade status following the complaint,
which was filed in June.
   A country found to have abused worker rights risks losing its
privilege to export products to the United States free of duties
under the Generalized System of Preferences. In 1987, Israel
exported $487 million in goods under the program.
   Responding to Yeutter's statement, Sharon said: ``We shall
explain to our American friends that when it comes to the lives of
Jews, Israel will not be pressured by economic sanctions.''
   An Arab hospital official said nine-year-old Marah Nadadeli was
shot in the left leg when she ran out of her house in Nablus, the
largest West Bank city.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the girl
thought she heard the army announce on loudspeakers that a curfew
was over. The announcement actually said the curfew was continuing.
   The 120,000 residents of Nablus have been confined to their
homes since Thursday.
   A 23-year-old Nablus man was also shot in the left leg by
soldiers, a hospital official said, adding that he did not know the
circumstances.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, residents of the Jabaliya refugee
camp attacked a Palestinian fireman who worked for the military
administration and his family defended him with knives and chains,
the army said.
   It said two of the Arab attackers were treated for slight
injuries and arrested.
   In Ramallah Thursday, a Palestinian also suspected of
collaborating with Israel opened fire on Arab youths who refused to
let him through a barricade, Israel radio and Arab news reports
said.
   The man was believed to be a collaborator because only Arabs who
work with the authorities are granted permission to carry a weapon,
the news reports said.
   Iyad Hassan Mahmoud Nabali, 14, who was shot in the shoulder,
told The Associated Press from his hospital bed that the man ``got
out of his car, pulled a pistol and shot me.''
   The clashes followed three attacks on suspected collaborators
over the past three days. In the worst incident, masked men broke
into the home of Saadi Hazaza in the West Bank village of Yatta
Wednesday and hacked him to death with axes.
   In another development, the Nazareth-based Arab weekly A-Sinara
said the Palestine Liberation Organization was considering forming
a provisional government next month composed of Palestinian
academics from the occupied territories, Europe and the United
States.
   The newspaper said formation of the government-in-exile would be
announced either at next month's U.N. General Assembly session in
New York or when PLO chief Yasser Arafat addresses the European
Parliament Sept. 13.
   In New York, the U.N. Security Council on Friday asked Israel to
stop deporting Palestinians and said it was was worried by growing
violence in the occupied territories.
   Since the start of the Palestinian uprising, Israel has deported
33 Palestinians and ordered another 25 expelled from the occupied
lands. The Israelis say those deported helped foment the unrest.
</TEXT>
