<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Copper-7     08-26 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Copper-7,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberating Copper-7 Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury began deliberating Friday whether
the Copper-7 intrauterine device caused sterility in a Minnesota
woman.
   Esther Kociemba, 30, and her husband, William, of Elk River, are
seeking at least $16.5 million from G.D. Searle & Co., manufacturer
of the birth-control device. The damages sought are more than any
jury has awarded in 18 similar cases.
   The jury, which has heard three months of testimony, began
deliberations Friday morning and was sent home about 5 p.m. Jurors
were instructed to return Monday.
   Michael Ciresi, the Kociembas' attorney, argued during trial
that the Copper-7 caused pelvic inflammatory disease and rendered
Mrs. Kociemba sterile. He said the Chicago-based Searle was
negligent in designing the device with a tailstring that he said
provided a haven for bacteria.
   The Copper-7 was rushed to market without proper testing and
sold to women without adequate warning that it could cause public
inflammatory disease, and without warning that it was too large for
women who had never given birth, Ciresi said.
   Searle's attorney, Paul Strain of Baltimore, said the company
exceeded U.S. Food and Drug Administration requirements in
marketing Copper-7, which was once the most widely used IUD in
America. He attacked the credibility of witnesses called by Ciresi
and said Ciresi did not even prove that Mrs. Kociemba suffered from
pelvic infection, let alone that it was caused by the Copper-7.
   Ciresi asked the jury for $15 million in punitive damages, $1.5
million to $2 million in compensatory damages for Mrs. Kociemba and
$300,000 in compensatory damages for her husband.
   The FDA approved the Copper-7 in 1974, and Searle sold between
300,000 and 400,000 of the IUDs in the United States before
withdrawing the product in the wake of numerous lawsuits.
   Ciresi's Minneapolis law firm represents more than 150 of the
500 Copper-7 users who have sued Searle and Mrs. Kociemba's case is
the first it has tried.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
