<DOCNO> AP880826-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 2148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma 2ndLd-Writethru a0769 08-26 0957</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0769,0982</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Protests, Violence Increase in Burma</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6th ``Anti-government demonstration ...'' and 13th
pvs `Rangoon radio reported ...' with 1 graf each to CORRECT
spelling to Insein Jail, sted of Inselin.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Name Gunnes is cq.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BK3,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes and violence spread in Burma and
BBC Television quoted reliable sources as saying that up to 1,000
inmates were killed when guards opened fire at Insein Jail outside
Rangoon on Friday.
   State-run Rangoon radio reported earlier that 2,000 inmates
rebelled at Insein jail on Thursday, setting buildings ablaze. It
said guards opened fire and ``some inmates and prison guards were
injured.''
   There was no immediate explanation for the discrepancy between
the Thursday date given by Rangoon radio and the Friday time given
by the British Broadcasting Corp. TV broadcast Friday night.
   Huge anti-government rallies continued in Burma Friday, and
retired ranking military officers joined those demanding immediate
democracy in the Asian nation.
   The BBC broadcast, monitored in London, said:
   ``Anti-government demonstrations are reported to have begun .. .
(at Insein Jail) early in the day when prisoners had left their
cells for breakfast. Several who tried to give speeches are said to
have been shot dead and in the chaos that followed fires were
started.
   ``As inmates fled to escape the flames, it is reported that
security guards opened fire. According to reliable sources, about
1,000 people were killed. Rangoon radio in its account said guards
fired on prisoners as they tried to open the gates to escape from
the burning building, but it speaks only of several people being
wounded.''
   The report was by BBC correspondent Christopher Gunness, who had
been in Rangoon and filed it from Dhaka, Bangladesh. The BBC told
The Associated Press it was not sure when Gunness left Rangoon.
   Gen. Tin Oo, a former defense minister, said earlier in a letter
to President Maung Maung that ``thousands of lives have been lost''
since the coup that began authoritarian military rule 26 years ago
``and the country is in the grip of a general strike paralyzing the
whole administration.''
   ``It is now long overdue to abolish one-party (government) in
favor of a multiparty system,'' he wrote. ``It is imperative to
immediately transfer power to an interim government ... composed of
people acceptable to the country.''
   A copy of the letter, dated Friday, was seen by the AP.
   Another letter urged Maung Maung, the first civilian president
since the coup, to form an interim government and release political
prisoners. It was dated Tuesday and signed by a retired brigadier
and 14 colonels.
   Rangoon radio reported two other prison riots besides that at
Insein:
   _Prisoners set fires at Bassein, 90 miles west of Rangoon, on
Wednesday, guards shot one inmate dead and about 100 prisoners
escaped.
   _At Akyab jail in Arrakan state bordering Bangladesh,
``prisoners and people outside of the prison shouted slogans,
demonstrated and started to riot'' Thursday night. Six inmates were
killed, 24 were wounded and about 1,600 escaped.
   According to the radio, all the prisoners were convicted of
crimes unrelated to the anti-government protest. It said all the
2,750 people arrested this month during demonstrations in Rangoon
had been released, except for those accused of serious crimes.
   The radio said protesters commandeered 27 buses Friday in
Rangoon, stole gasoline under threat of violence and drove the
buses around the city.
   An earlier broadcast said ``some violent incidents, looting and
destructive acts have been reported in several townships since
martial law was revoked in the Rangoon city development areas''
Wednesday, and ``hooligans'' set shanties afire in some parts of
the capital. No details were given.
   Officials said strikes halted trains and domestic flights of
Union Burma Airways on Friday; closed oil refineries at Syriam,
across the Rangoon River, and at Mann in central Burma; crippled
most factories of the Industries Ministry, and stranded foreign
ships in Rangoon port.
   Most government offices in Rangoon were empty. Friday was the
second day without newspapers because workers at the six state-run
dailies stayed home.
   People are hoarding necessities and the price of rice has soared.
   The largest and most widespread protests since the military
takeover of 1962 have had the government on the defensive for a
month. At least 112 people have been killed in Rangoon alone, by
official count, and unofficial reports put the toll much higher.
   Turmoil began when 77-year-old Ne Win, who led the coup and
imposed rigid socialist rule, resigned late in July and the ruling
Burma Socialist Program Party chose Sein Lwin to succeed him.
   Demonstrations began almost immediately against Sein Lwin, who
was blamed for the ruthless crushing of dissent, and turned bloody
Aug. 8 when security forces began shooting into crowds. Sein Lwin
resigned after 17 days and Maung Maung, the attorney general and
one of two civilians in the Cabinet, replaced him Aug. 19.
   Student-led rallies continued and protesters demanded full
democracy.
   Even Maung Maung's recommendation Wednesday that a special party
congress be held Sept. 12 to consider a referendum on one-party
rule did not end mass actions in the streets.
   Rallies have been peaceful since Sein Lwin quit, but the
situation has deteriorated since Maung Maung lifted martial law
Wednesday and security personnel virtually disappeared from the
streets.
   Police and government workers in Taunggyi joined 100,000
demonstrators Friday in demanding an interim government. Witnesses
said it was the largest rally ever in the Shan state capital, 290
miles northeast of the capital.
   In Rangoon, Aung Gyi Suu Kyi, daughter of late independence
leader Aung San, told 400,000 cheering people only immediate
democracy could end the unrest. She asked the military to be ``the
people's army'' and look after their interests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
