<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Romania 1stLd-Writethru a0671 08-26 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0671,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grosz To Meet Ceausescu On Controversial Village Razing Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th pvs `The two...' to UPDATE with
report that meeting proposed by Ceausescu Thursday, PICKS up 5th
pvs `The visit...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Karoly Grosz will meet Romanian
President Nicolae Ceausescu on Sunday, apparently to discuss a plan
to raze villages in Romania, official media said Friday.
   The terse report over Hungarian radio did not contain details,
but it was clear that Ceausescu's plan to destroy 7,000 of
Romania's 13,000 villages will be the main topic of their
discussions in Arad, Romania.
   Hungarians have complained that the move will wipe out hundreds
of ethnic Hungarian communities.
   The two leaders will hold ``a working meeting ... on the basis
of a mutual agreement,'' the report said.
   Hungarian Communist Party spokesman Laszlo Major said the
Romanian president proposed the meeting through diplomatic channels
on Thursday. Arad is about 25 miles from the Hungarian border. The
proposal was accepted in a hurriedly convened special session of
the Hungarian party's Politburo Friday, Major said.
   The visit appears to have been arranged following a Hungarian
initiative to defuse a deepening crisis between the Warsaw Pact
allies over the plan to raze the villages and resettle the tens of
thousands of residents.
   Hungary has long accused the Romanian government of
discrimination against the 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians who live
in Romania, most of them in Transylvania.
   Last weekend, Politburo member Imre Pozsgay denounced the
resettlement plan as ``a crime against mankind.''
   The meeting will be the first encounter between the two
countries' leaders in 11 years.
   In retaliation for an anti-Romanian demonstration in Budapest of
about 50,000 people in June, Ceausescu ordered the closure of a
Hungarian consulate in Cluj-Napoca and of a Hungarian culture
institute in Budapest that never started operation.
   Romanian refugees and independent Hungarian groups Monday night
started a two-week demonstration against the plan opposite the
Romanian Embassy in Budapest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
