<2ND_LINE>AM-Huey Newton,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newton Decides To Leave San Quentin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Black Panther leader Huey
Newton, who had refused parole from prison until a fellow inmate
and ex-Panther also was released, decided to leave after all,
prison officials said Friday.
   Newton, in San Quentin for two months for parole violations,
refused to leave on his scheduled release date Tuesday, demanding
that convicted murderer Elmer ``Geronimo'' Pratt also be freed.
   Newton apparently changed his mind about staying behind bars
when prison officials served him with extra conditions of parole,
including a clause that should he again decline to leave, it would
be considered a parole violation, said prison spokeswoman Jeanne
Ballatore.
   Newton's refusal to leave so far has merely been a violation of
prison rules, she said. The new clause would make it a parole
violation, a much more serious offense.
   Newton was processed Friday, she said.
   Pratt is serving a life term for the 1968 slaying of a Santa
Monica woman during a $30 robbery. He entered prison in 1972 and
lost his eighth bid parole two weeks ago for parole when a state
panel called him a ``danger to the public.''
   Pratt's supporters contend he was framed, that he's a political
prisoner and the victim of police efforts to jail Panther leaders
and dismantle the Oakland-based Black Liberation Movement of the
late 1960s and early '70s.
   Newton, 45, co-founder of the defunct Black Panthers and its
defense minister, has had two decades of scuffles with the law.
</TEXT>
