<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Cyprus     08-26 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Cyprus,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greece Says U.N.-Sponsored Cyprus Talks ``Encouraging''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greece on Friday called this week's
U.N.-sponsored talks between Cyprus President George Vassiliou and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash ``an encouraging start'' for
future negotiations.
   The two met in Geneva to try to break a three-year deadlock in
negotiations to reunite the east Mediterranean island.
   ``It is undoubtedly an encouraging start that could create the
preconditions for more concrete rapprochements between the two
sides in the future,'' government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos
said.
   Vassiliou said Thursday that his first meeting ever with
Denktash generated goodwill, ``but there is still a huge gap
between our positions.'' The two agreed to meet again Sept. 15 in
the island's capital, Nicosia.
   He repeated Greece's call for a Cyprus solution under U.N.
auspices, adding ``the Cyprus problem must also be solved within
the framework of international law.''
   Cyprus has been unofficially partitioned since 1974 when Turkey
invaded Cyprus after an abortive Athens-backed coup by supporters
of union with Greece.
</TEXT>
