<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fire Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here at a glance are major fires burning in the forests of the
West and Northwest:
   _Wyoming: Ten fires have burned an estimated 400,000 acres in
Yellowstone National Park, closing several roads and developed
communities.
   South of the park in the Bridger-Teton National Forest, the
22,811-acre Huck fire was burning to the northeast toward
Yellowstone's southern boundary.
   To the east in the Bighorn National Forest, firefighters
contained the 10,900-acre Lost fire Thursday.
   _Montana: A 36,000-acre blaze in the Absaroka-Beartooth
wilderness area in south-central Montana threatened the towns of
Cooke City and Silver Gate, just outside the northeast entrance to
Yellowstone.
   About 10 miles west, the Hellroaring Creek fire grew to about
30,900 acres.
   Southeast of Helena, fire crews were still trying to contain the
37,600-acre Warm Springs fire.
   _Oregon: In the southwest, the lightning-sparked 1,790-acre
Walker Mountain fire moved within a half-mile of a subdivision of
about 1,000 people north of Grants Pass. In the northeast, the
5,000-acre Ward Canyon fire moved to within a mile of the tiny
community of Troy. It had destroyed 15 unoccupied structures,
mostly hunting cabins. Also, the lightning-caused Teppe Butte fire
30 miles north of Enterprise ballooned to 18,000 acres from 150
acres Thursday afternoon.
   The Prophecy fire in Crater Lake National Park had burned 2,000
acres, spokeswoman Dee Westerberg said.
   _Washington: Six fires in Colville National Forest were spread
by wind overnight from 60 acres to an estimated 600 to 800 acres. A
4,000-acre fire burned out of control on the Colville Indian
Reservation with no one available to fight it.
   Lightning was blamed for at least 25 new fires in eastern
Washington.
   _Utah: The 200-acre Deer Lodge fire in Ashley National Forest
briefly threatened 15 to 20 summer homes before the wind changed. A
fire believed started by a spark from a bulldozer at the Powder
Mountain ski area grew to 450 acres.
   _Idaho: The Eagle Bar fire just east of Hells Canyon near the
Idaho-Oregon border grew to 3,000 acres; officials said wind-blown
embers started fires up to a half mile ahead of the main fire.
   _California: An 1,800-acre fire in trees, grass and brush near
Cloverdale, 65 miles northwest of San Francisco, was 90 percent
contained by fire lines and 75 percent controlled.
</TEXT>
