<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-26 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Share Prices Recover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices recovered moderately in thin trading
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange Saturday following a major decline the
previous day.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues won back 113.50
points, or 0.41 percent, to close Saturday's half-day session at
27,678.91 points.
   The index plummeted 305.03 points Friday after European
countries raised their key lending rates, depressing stock markets
around the world.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where most
major shares are listed, was a light 230 million shares.
   ``The gain in the Nikkei index is largely caused by the rebound
of major shares such as steel and electronics,'' said a dealer at
Nikko Securities Co.
   ``But the market as a whole doesn't look too good. Trading is
very thin and a small number of investors are buying a portion of
shares which suffered a big loss yesterday (Friday),'' he added,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Another dealer at a major securities firm said the Tokyo market
will be revitalized again on Monday when securities companies start
a new monthly operation.
   Transactions made after Monday will go into the September
account for securities companies, which traditionally emphasize
stock trading within the first few days of each new month, the
dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The foreign exchange market is closed Saturdays.
</TEXT>
