<1ST_LINE>a p AM-QuayleinCongress ADV29   08-26 1080</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle in Congress, ADV29,1117</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Aug 29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Straight Conservative Vote, With Some Quirky Deviations</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: This story is designed for side-by-side use with a similar
piece examining Democrat Lloyd Bentsen's congressional record,
b0481.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential nominee Dan
Quayle built up a record in Congress that departed only
occasionally from the Reagan administration's line but along the
way he took some positions he doesn't mention in his resume.
   For example, he advocated special tax breaks for smokers,
dieters, foreign golfers, batboys and batgirls for professional
baseball teams, and college football coaches.
   The tax breaks for smokers and dieters was proposed in a ```Kick
the Habit' Tax Credit Bill,'' which he sponsored and which, in the
interest of health, would have allowed a tax credit up to $150 for
half the cost of enrolling in a weight-loss or stop-smoking
program. It didn't become law.
   And Quayle once threatened to try to rename Chicago in honor of
former Sen. Vance Hartke, D-Ind., unless some Illinois lawmakers
dropped efforts to rename the Indiana Dunes National Lakeshore in
memory of the late Sen. Paul H. Douglas, D-Ill.
   During his four years in the House and almost eight years in the
Senate, the Indiana senator has been a steady advocate for military
spending and for reducing the government's role in daily life. Some
votes have put him at odds with organized labor, veterans and other
interest groups.
   Quayle sought to overhaul federal budget procedures in an effort
to cut the budget deficit. He voted for President Reagan's big 1981
tax cut and then followed that with votes to raise taxes in 1982,
1983, 1984 and 1987 _ tax increases that Reagan signed after vowing
to oppose tax increases. Quayle now is on record with his running
mate, George Bush, to oppose future tax increases.
   On May 10, 1985, Quayle and most other Senate Republicans voted
for a budget that would have eliminated the cost-of-living increase
in Social Security pensions while boosting the defense budget to
offset inflation. The vice president broke a 49-49 tie and the
budget passed. The House subsequently refused to cut the Social
Security increases.
   The 41-year-old Quayle is best known as an author of the 1982
Job Training Partnership Act, which emphasized involvement of local
government and private employers in training young and unskilled
workers. His Senate co-author was Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
whose name the Republicans invoke with ridicule on the campaign
trail.
   As a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee, Quayle
developed a reputation for learning the intricacies of the defense
budget and weapons systems. Few are more vocal in support of
Reagan's Strategic Defense Initiative _ nicknamed Star Wars.
   After some initial skepticism, he fought tirelessly for approval
earlier this year of the U.S.-Soviet arms-limitation treaty and _
to the surprise of some conservatives _ opposed most of a dozen
conservative challenges to the pact.
   Quayle fought just as consistently against another top
initiative of 1988: a Democratic-sponsored bill requiring that
large companies give workers at least 60 days' notice before a
shutdown. He voted for every effort to water down the bill.
   He voted for aid to the anti-government rebels in Nicaragua; for
a constitutional amendment allowing organized prayer in schools;
against abortion; against gun control and for capital punishment.
   Although he endorsed extension of the Voting Rights Act, he
fought restoration of some civil-rights protections that had been
nullified by a Supreme Court decision.
   Breaking with the White House, he voted to override Reagan's
vetoes of economic sanctions against South Africa and of a bill
authorizing $18 billion in clean-water projects. Last year he voted
for an $88 billion highway-mass-transit bill but would not vote to
override Reagan's veto of that measure.
   Here are some other stands taken by Quayle:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Against a bill elevating the Veterans Administration to the
president's Cabinet. (On the campaign trail last week, he said that
vote was the result of youthful indiscretion and said he now
supports the proposal.)
   _For overhaul of the welfare system.
   _Against paying reparations to Japanese-Americans interned
during World War II. He voted for the bill after efforts to
eliminate reparations failed.
   _Proposed, at the urging of management of the Indianapolis
Indians, an amendment to overturn a Labor Department ruling that
child-labor laws prohibit youths under 16 from serving as batboy or
batgirl for professional baseball teams at night games.
   _Offered an amendment to exempt foreign professional athletes
from a law under which the United States taxes the full worldwide
income of any alien who is in this country at least 180 days a
year. Quayle, an avid golfer, said the law discourages such
athletes from playing in U.S. charity tournaments.
   _Sought to allow college football coaches to qualify for
pensions through their association, rather than through a college.
   _For requiring regulation of the manufacture of armor-piercing
bullets.
   _Against allowing Jewish soldiers to wear a yarmulke while in
uniform.
   _For limiting the president to one six-year term.
   _Against restricting private employers' use of lie detectors to
examine employees.
   _Against a presumption that any disability suffered by a veteran
who took part in atmospheric nuclear tests or in the atomic bombing
of Japan was service-connected.
   _Against extending the amnesty period for aliens to apply for
legalization.
   _Against expanding Medicare to cover certain catastrophic
medical costs, a measure signed into law with much fanfare by
Reagan. Quayle's was one of only 11 votes against it.
   _For prohibiting distribution of contraceptives to unmarried
minors without parental consent.
   _Against cutting money for child nutrition.
   _For allowing religious colleges in the District of Columbia to
deny certain benefits to homosexual groups.
   _Against requiring the labeling of imported food products.
   _Against a resolution stating it would not be in the interest of
U.S. security to prosecute Lt. Col. Oliver North.
   _For sharp reductions in appropriations for administering legal
services for the poor.
   _Against banning possession of a firearm that is not detectable
by airport security machines.
   _Against requiring the president to notify Congress within 48
hours when a covert operation is under way (compared with 10 days
under current law).
   _For allowing one branch of a private educational institute to
discriminate even through another branch is receiving federal funds.
   _Against requiring small businesses to make structural changes
in their buildings to accommodate the handicapped.
   _For creating a federal holiday in memory of Martin Luther King
Jr.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Aug 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
