<NOTE>For Release Monday, Aug. 29, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Ad Agency Stocks Sidelined This Olympic Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians and Olympic sponsors usually try for
the limelight with advertising every four years, but their efforts
this year have failed to make ad company stocks stars on Wall
Street.
   Industry analysts estimate that the major advertising stocks as
a group have underperformed the broader market by about 10 percent
this year.
   They say the outlook for the group remains tied closely to the
performance of the economy next year.
   ``The industry has gone through three tough years,'' said Alan
Gottesman, who follows the ad business for the investment firm
PaineWebber.
   But he said the rigors of industry consolidation and
cost-cutting may have put the group in a position to benefit from
whatever surprises may lie ahead.
   Over the past two years, consolidation created some huge ad
holding companies _ Omnicom Group Inc., WPP Group PLC and a bigger
Saatchi & Saatchi PLC. The publicly-held ad companies also include
Interpublic Group of Companies Inc., Ogilvy Group and Foote, Cone &
Belding Communications Inc.
   Simultaneously, agencies were laying off workers and taking
other cost-cutting steps. Gottesman estimates ad industry
employment is down 3 percent to 5 percent from a year ago.
   The belt-tightening came in time for the industry to reap
earnings benefits from ad spending growth expected due to the
elections and the Olympic Games.
   But the anticipated spurt has largely failed to materialize.
   In June, the industry guru Robert J. Coen of the ad agency
McCann-Erickson scaled back his estimate of U.S. ad spending growth
for the year to 8.4 percent, down from the 9 percent gain he had
forecast six months earlier.
   Some other ad industry analysts expect even slower growth.
   James Dougherty, who follows advertising stocks for County
Securities, said ``the quadrennial year is turning out to be a big
zero.'' He expects an increase excluding direct mail spending of 5
percent to 6 percent this year.
   Dougherty said the economy is at a different stage in the
business cycle than it was when ad spending climbed at double-digit
rates in 1976 and 1984.
   ``The economic news this year hasn't been bad, but it hasn't
been as good as it was in those years at the beginning of a big
expansion,'' he said.
   Charles Crane, who follows the ad business for Prudential-Bache
Securities, said U.S. ad spending should rise about 7 percent this
year.
   He said spending didn't get its normal quadrennial lift because
consumer spending increases have been anemic. That hurt ad stocks,
he said, because ``the market has been shying away from consumer
cyclical stocks this year.''
   Looking ahead, Coen expects ad spending will grow 7.5 percent in
1989, while Dougherty and Crane expect growth roughly matching this
year's pace.
   Dougherty noted that commercial time is sold out on the summer
Olympics broadcasts, and that advance sales of time on the three
major television networks for the fall exceeded last year's strong
totals.
   But even so, he said ``I don't have anybody telling me clients
are increasing their budgets.''
   Crane said a pickup may occur in consumer spending as the trauma
of last fall's stock market crash recedes, and said that would make
the case ``for 1989 not being a bad year at all.''
   As a result he finds the ad stocks ``attractive, with the caveat
that I don't expect a recession before 1990.''
   In their search for new ways to generate revenue, some of the
major ad agencies have been buying marketing services firms that
offer the consulting, promotion and design work that ad companies
once spurned.
   Dougherty said the results from this shopping spree have been
mixed.
   Crane said a gradual movement by major advertisers away from the
flat-fee system of compensating ad agencies could be a boon to
well-managed agencies.
   Under some new methods, agencies are taking lower base rates but
get incentive payments if their advertising works, boosting sales
or market share.
   Gottesman said the recent pace of new product introductions
indicates that consumer products companies are taking risks and
becoming more agressive. That could be a plus for ad companies
because new product rollouts usually mean more advertising.
   He is not pushing the group, but feels good about it.
   ``If there are no surprises, the ad stocks go sideways,''
Gottesman said. ``But if we see some surprises, the surprises will
likely be on the good side and the stocks are going to go up.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Aug. 29</NOTE>
