<2ND_LINE>AM-News to Use, ADV31,0542</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Aug 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>By Wary of Art and Coin Investments</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Repeating to insert cycle designator.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ever alert for investment opportunities, many
Americans have been burned in recent years by unscrupulous
operators promoting overpriced art and collectors coins, the
Federal Trade Commission warns.
   While both rare coins and art can prove good investments,
avoiding mistakes requires either considerable knowledge or
reliance on a trustworthy adviser.
   Perhaps the most important thing to avoid is allowing oneself to
be pressured into a quick decision, especially by a telephone
salesperson, the FTC says.
   And do not give out credit card numbers or bank account numbers
to anyone calling you.
   Often salespeople will claim you have won some sort of contest
and the numbers are needed for ``verification.'' Don't fall for it,
the FTC warns, you risk big losses by giving out such numbers to
unfamiliar callers.
   Salespeople often try to snow buyers with tales of big increases
in the value of prints or coins.
   In the case of art they will sometimes ghoulishly claim the
artist is seriously ill and that, when he dies, the price will
skyrocket.
   But the technology for reproducing pictures is excellent today,
so that what is claimed to be a limited edition print worth $500 to
$3,500 can in fact turn out to be a good quality reproduction,
worth $50 at best.
   ``Therefore, it is very important to consult a reputable local
authority on the subject, such as an art appraiser or museum
curator, before purchasing any work of art,'' the FTC says in a new
consumer fact sheet on art fraud.
   Copies of the alert, as well as FTC investor alerts on Rare
Coins, Telephone Investment Fraud and Telemarketing Travel Fraud
can be obtained, at no charge, by writing: Public Reference,
Federal Trade Commission, Washington, D.C., 20580.
   The FTC urges consumers to be skeptical of claims of
authenticity for coins and art, noting that crooks often print up
fraudulent certificates or authenticity for art or fake coin
grading certificates. They sometimer refer buyers to ``experts''
who are actually paid by them, and may promise refunds which they
later refuse to make good on.
   It can help to check out sellers with the local Better Business
Bureau, consumer office or state attorney general's office. But
remember, it isn't unusual for a company to change its name
periodically to avoid being identified with past complaints.
   Whatever the situation, don't be rushed, the FTC urges, no offer
is so good that it cannot wait for a cool, professional examination.
   ``Ask yourself: if this offer is so good, why is a total
stranger making the effort to sell me this investment?'' the agency
suggests.
   In the case of rare coins, the FTC suggests checking with
professional organizations to see if the dealer is a member in good
standing before sending any money. These groups include the
American Numismatic Association in Colorado Springs, Colo; Industry
Council for Tangible Assets, Washington, D.C.; and Professional
Numismatists Guild in Van Nuys, Calif.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed Ams, Aug 31</NOTE>
