<1ST_LINE>s p BC-QuayleProfile ADV28-2Takes   08-26 0923</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Quayle Profile, ADV 28-2 Takes,0945</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dan Quayle: From Idyllic Hoosier Childhood To Rock-Ribbed
Republican</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle, born into a world of Indiana
privilege and conservative causes, preached the gospel of
rock-ribbed Republicanism long before he ever walked the corridors
of Congress or became George Bush's running mate.
   ``Politics comes naturally to the family,'' said Ernest
Williams, retired editor of the nearby Fort Wayne News Sentinel.
``Dan represents the fulfillment of a family dream.''
   In his road to the Republican ticket, Quayle never wavered in
his personal or political leanings: the popular fraternity boy
became an amiable candidate, the teen who learned golf made the
game his passion, the youth who displayed a Barry Goldwater sticker
on his car in the '60s proudly voted for the tenets of the Reagan
revolution from his back bench in the Senate.
   Back at DePauw University in the late 1960s, ``He was basically
a little political commentator,'' recalls Delta Kappa Epsilon
fraternity brother John Socolofsky. ``I think you genuinely could
see something light up there. There was definitely a spark.''
   ``He was really well versed,'' he added. ``It was obvious that
was the fabric of the family.''
   However, not everyone saw him quite that way. Quayle was
``undistinguished'' and ``mediocre,'' said Michael Lawrence, a
former DePauw professor who taught Quayle constitutional law. ``He
didn't work very hard. He was not very bright. He didn't get much
done.''
   Asked about Quayle being chosen for the No. 2 spot on the GOP
ticket, Lawrence said: ``It confirms what I was told when I was a
little kid, that anybody can grow up to be president.''
   In the days since Quayle was anointed by George Bush, the fabric
of his family has turned into political drama as Quayle struggled
to vindicate himself amid a torrent of controversy about his
lackluster academic career, his personal life and most of all, his
National Guard service during the Vietnam War _ and whether he used
family clout to secure bullet-free duty.
   In a matter of days, James Danforth Quayle, 41, the first baby
boomer on a national ticket, has catapulted from relative obscurity
to the withering glare of the limelight, a man on the hot seat, a
second-term senator vying to be a heartbeat away from the
presidency.
   ``From a guy who could walk down the street unrecognized, bang,
he's suddenly put in the spotlight,'' law school friend and federal
appeals Judge Dan Manion said this week. ``He was unprepared and
that's probably not a very good way to put a vice president in.''
   If this is a test of Quayle's mettle, he'll pass with flying
colors, his friends believe.
   ``From everything I have seen, he's demonstrating very definite
resilience,'' said Gerald Warren, Quayle's former economics
professor at DePauw. ``He'll survive very well.''
   Quayle surely inherited his fervor for conservative politics
from his grandfather, Eugene C. Pulliam, a media mogul who founded
a multi-million-dollar newspaper empire that includes the Arizona
Republic, Phoenix Gazette, Indianapolis Star and Indianapolis News.
   The Quayle family owns the Huntington (Ind.) Herald-Press.
Quayle's father, James, is publisher; the senator, who worked as a
young associate publisher before entering politics, is vice
president. The circulation of the paper is less than 9,000.
   Quayle spent his childhood in Indiana and Arizona, moving west
with his family as a small boy in the mid '50s when his father
helped run the Pulliam newspapers. They returned to Huntington in
1963 when Dan was a high school junior.
   For Quayle, life in this rural northeast Indiana town was filled
with penny-ante poker games with his buddies, dancing to juke box
tunes at the now-defunct Swing Inn, part of the YMCA, and cruising
down Jefferson Street, stopping at the A&W Root Beer stand and the
Penguin Point drive-in.
   ``He had a regular kid existence,'' said high school pal Taylor
Cope, now a Chicago area cardiologist. ``It's been said he was a
rich kid, but that never showed when he was a teen. He didn't have
his own car.'' He borrowed his mother's.
   As a senior in college, he was a big man on campus _ and drove a
beat-up International Scout.
   Already, his political philosophy was forming. ``He was very,
very conservative at the time. He was pro Goldwater,'' Cope
recalled. ``He was pro-war because the president was pro-war. ''
   Carla Rice, who dated Quayle in high school, told a reporter
Quayle had a bumper sticker on his car with the chemical symbols
for gold and water. ``And he said in this big voice, `And that is
the next president of the United States.'''
   The conservative sentiment, light years away from the angry
chants and window-smashing rampages of the anti-Vietnam protests,
also prevailed at DePauw, a small, upper middle-class liberal arts
college in Greencastle, where Quayle majored in political science.
   ``It was not a very controversial social environment,'' said
Socolofsky. ``The war wasn't even debated in classrooms there.''
   Michael Miller, economist with the U.S. Bureau of Labor
Statistics and a former fraternity brother, was a freshman when
Quayle was a pledge trainer.
   ``I remember the night Richard Nixon was elected in 1968. Dan
had a party in his room. There were a couple of TVs going. The only
thing I can remember he (Quayle) was at the convention _ he was an
usher to the stage _ he really got a big kick out of that.
   ``The Democrats were studying somewhere, I suppose.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-QuayleProfile ADV28-1stAdd   08-26 1011</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Quayle Profile, ADV 28-1st Add,1034</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to restore dropped matter; first take will not
be repeated</NOTE>
<HEAD>HUNTINGTON, Ind.: I suppose.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Following his father's and grandfather's footsteps, Quayle
joined Delta Kappa Epsilon _ also Bush's fraternity at Yale _ and
became vice president at the so-called campus ``animal house.''
   ``We were the beer generation,'' Socolofsky added. ``We really
enjoyed getting a keg of beer, putting some music on and having
dates.'' Whatever the trend on other campuses, Quayle has said he
never used or even experimented with marijuana.
   Quayle was popular, making friends easily. He also was a premier
golfer. But his academic record was less impressive. Quayle says he
was the ``proverbial C-plus'' student, but he flunked a
comprehensive political exam he needed to graduate. He later took a
different test and passed.
   Ted Katula, DePauw's athletic director and former golf coach,
says Quayle ``was a very tough competitor. I liked his confidence.
It gave me confidence. ... He's very aggressive. ... I'd like to
have six Dan Quayles playing for me.''
   Quayle's none-too-stellar academic career later became a touchy
topic when DePauw faculty members rejected a proposal to award the
senator an honorary law degree. They later reversed themselves
after the university president appealed.
   After college, Quayle entered the National Guard at the height
of the war. Wendell Phillippi, a former Indianapolis News editor
and a family friend, said he recommended Quayle to a top Guard
official, who asked the guard personnel office to put a slot ``on
hold'' for him. He was brought aboard as a welder before being
shifted to a public relations post.
   Questions about whether the hawkish Quayle pulled strings to
avoid the front lines have dogged the senator, who at week's end
refused to answer any more questions about it. ``I was not seeking
special treatment,'' he said. ``No rules were broken.''
   James Quayle also denied suggestions this week that clout got
his son into Indiana University School of Law when his grades
couldn't. His father told a reporter that ``Danny's (a) pretty good
salesman,'' who talked his way into law school, arguing DePauw was
tougher than other schools.
   In law school, Quayle met his wife, Marilyn, another law
student. They wed after a 10-week courtship and have three children.
   Associates say the Quayles live a middle-class existence in
suburban northern Virginia, with Marilyn cutting and styling her
husband's hair, and both sharing parental duties, such as
babysitting.
   Starting out in Indiana, Quayle worked as investigator for the
state attorney general's office, administrative assistant to the
governor and at the Huntington paper before a GOP official, Orvas
Beers, approached him to challenge Democratic eight-term Rep. Ed
Roush in 1976.
   He is ``a real charmer,'' Beers says now. ```I thought he'd get
a lot of the women's vote because of his friendliness, his
personality and his good looks.''
   Beers said Quayle took to politics naturally. ``Only one time
did I ever have to suggest anything. Danny was standing talking to
a group of people (when he was running for the first time). I said,
`Danny, get yourself out and shaking hands. He didn't argue a bit.
And he didn't stop shaking hands the rest of the campaign.''
   Quayle's former press secretary, Larry Smith, said the
blue-eyed, blond senator bristles at talk about his looks and
comparisons to matinee idol Robert Redford. ``He wanted to be taken
seriously. He wanted to be taken as a professional trying to do a
job,'' said Smith, news director of WHAS-TV in Louisville, Ky.
   One day a trade group from Indiana visited Quayle's office, and
as is custom, they were asked if they wanted a photo taken with the
senator. One woman in particular ``was thrilled,'' Smith recalls.
``She made a compliment about his beautiful blue eyes. He was very
embarrassed. He tried to lighten the moment. He said, `Larry's got
blue eyes.'''
   Quayle served two terms in the House before defeating three-term
Sen. Birch Bayh in the 1980 Reagan landslide. ``Taking on Bayh, it
gives you an idea about his competitiveness,'' Katula said. ``He's
not afraid to take a chance.''
   Quayle easily won re-election in 1986 and is known as an expert
on defense issues and an ardent supporter of Reagan's Star Wars
anti-missile shield. He also led the administration fight against
providing advance notice of plant closings and wrote the Job
Training Partnership Act, a nationwide employment program.
   Earlier in his career, Quayle was on the fringes of a scandal
that resurfaced with his nomination to the Bush ticket. In 1981, an
insurance industry lobbyist, Paula Parkinson, said she had had a
relationship with a Delaware congressman and shared a vacation
house in Florida a year earlier with him and two other House
members, one of whom was Quayle.
   Playboy magazine, for whom Parkinson subsequently posed,
reported this week that she will say in an upcoming issue that
Quayle propositioned her and she refused. Quayle has angrily denied
the accusation and said he was there on a golfing outing.
   Smith says of his ex-boss: ``I never saw Dan Quayle give a
second look to any woman. He was as straight an arrow you'd ever
want to meet.''
   Smith said Quayle has a hard time keeping on schedule. He said
one day they were running from one meeting to another and they were
trying to get to an airport. ``We passed a driving range and I'm
watching the clock.''
   Quayle made them stop. ``Dan picked up a can of balls and he
fired off a few,'' said Smith, while they anxiously waited. ``That
was his release and his relaxation.'' They made it to the airport.
   Friends say that although they're a little surprised at Quayle's
fast climb up the political ladder, he's used his assets well.
   ``What he's done shows he had some talent and organization and
friends in the right places,'' Cope says. ``His success speaks well
for himself.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Sharon Cohen is the AP Midwest regional
reporter, based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance Aug 28</NOTE>
