<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2takes   08-26 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0549</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government figures indicate the economy,
shaking off the drag caused by the drought, grew at the
surprisingly brisk annual pace of 3.3 percent in the second
quarter, while inflation hit a six-year peak of 5.1 percent.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday the gain in the gross
national product would have soared beyond the 3.3 percent clip had
it not been for a larger-than-expected $9.5 billion loss in farm
production. Without the drought impact, GNP growth from April
through June would have hit a 4.3 percent annual pace, it said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations' after-tax profits shot up 11.5
percent from April through June, the biggest advance in five years,
the government has reported.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that corporate profits
rose to an annual rate of $166.6 billion in the second quarter.
   The increase, which followed a 2.5 percent rise in the first
quarter, was the biggest gain since a 14.5 percent rise in the
second quarter of 1983.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing single-family homes, jolted
by rising mortgage rates, dropped 5 percent in July, the first
decline since January, a real estate trade group said.
   The National Association of Realtors said Thursday sales of
existing homes dropped to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.63
million units last month, following a 6.4 percent increase in June.
   Analysts blamed the setback on rising mortgage rates.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In the latest round of higher interest rates worldwide, the
central banks of Britain, West Germany and several other European
countries hiked their key rates.
   Thursday's actions rekindled fears of a global interest-rate
spiral and unnerved financial markets.
   Some analysts believe the rate hikes by West Germany's
Bundesbank, the Bank of England and other European central banks
could prompt another sharp tightening of credit in the United
States _ where the Federal Reserve pushed rates higher only a few
weeks ago.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration estimated the budget
deficit in the upcoming fiscal year would be low enough to avoid
politically painful, automatic spending cuts under the Gramm-Rudman
balanced budget law.
   But the White House budget chief also warned Thursday that
Congress had little room to enact new spending programs before the
slashes, totaling at least $10 billion, would have to be invoked.
   The Office of Management and Budget said that based on programs
enacted through Aug. 15, the fiscal 1989 deficit would be $144
billion _ $2 billion below the $146 billion level at which
across-the-board cuts would be required.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan by the Agriculture Department to change
price support loan procedures should be withdrawn, the National
Association of Wheat Growers said.
   Frank Johannsen, president of the association, said Thursday
wheat growers strongly oppose USDA's Aug. 10 proposal ``to provide
that 1987 and all subsequent crops of wheat, feed grains, rice and
soybeans would be ineligible for an extension of the original
nine-month loan.''
   The support loans are made to farmers, who then are required to
repay the loans when due or forfeit the grain to the department's
Commodity Credit Corp.
</TEXT>
