<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stadd   08-26 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st add,0530</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of U.S. agricultural exports is
expected to jump 22 percent to a four-year high of $34 billion this
fiscal year, up from $27.9 billion in 1986-87, the Agriculture
Department says.
   In terms of actual quantity, shipments were forecast Thursday at
146 million metric tons in the year that will end Sept. 30, up 13
percent from last year.
   Both the value and quantity estimates were up from the previous
USDA forecasts on May 26 of $33.5 billion and 145.5 million tons.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter has
announced he will review the duty-free privileges of six countries
accused of abusing workers' rights.
   The six include Israel, which has been charged with violating
the rights of Palestinian workers, and Syria, Burma, Haiti, Liberia
and Malaysia.
   Any country found to have abused worker rights would risk losing
its rights to export products to the United States free of charge
under a program known as the Generalized System of Preferences.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insilco Corp. says it has accepted a $1.1
billion buyout offer from two Texas oilmen, tossing aside a
previous takeover agreement with a management-led group.
   Under the arrangement, INR Holdings Inc., headed by Cyril Wagner
Jr. and Jack E. Brown of Midland, Texas, will pay $31.75 in cash
for each of Insilco's outstanding 25.6 million shares. Including
debt, the deal has an indicated value of about $1.1 billion,
Insilco said in a statement Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense contractor TRW Inc. has paid a $3
million penalty after pleading guilty to three counts of conspiring
to overcharge the federal government for military aircraft and M-1
tank parts.
   William B. Lawrence, TRW vice president and assistant secretary,
waived the company's right to a trial and entered the plea on its
behalf before U.S. District Judge George W. White on Thursday.
   TRW has estimated its Compressor Components Division overcharged
the government between $3 million and $11 million, Lawrence said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. officials say the company has set an
industry record for commercial jets ordered in a year.
   Linjeflyg, a domestic Swedish airline, ordered six 737-500
jetliners and took options on six more, giving Boeing 466 jetliner
orders for the year and breaking the old record of 461 planes
Boeing set in 178.
   The order, worth more than $175 million, boosted the dollar
value of Boeing's announced 1988 orders to $20.7 billion.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated in sluggish trading Thursday, as
concerns about rising interest rates resurfaced on the first
anniversary of the all-time peak in the Dow Jones industrial
average. The average lost 15.82 to close at 2,010.85.
   The dollar fell in heavy trading sparked by a round of interest
rate increases in Europe.
   Bond prices declined in response to the interest rate hikes and
signals of higher inflation.
   Petroleum futures prices fell; copper futures rose; precious
metals declined; cocoa futures plunged; and grain futures prices
were mixed while soybeans were mostly higher.
