<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-26 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Down Sharply In Volatile Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices finished sharply lower in
volatile trading, as the market hit a bearish downturn after
reports of higher OPEC production.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for October
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, fell 37 cents a barrel to close at $15.31 Thursday.
October crude closed 2 cents lower in Wednesday's trading.
   Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline
dropped 1.07 cents to finish at 46.44 cents a gallon. Most other
contract months for gasoline also declined. Wholesale heating oil
for September fell 1.30 cents to 42.45 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said the October contract for crude oil tumbled below a
critical technical level of $15.50 a barrel on reports that
production by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries had
surged anew.
   ``Reports that OPEC production has reached 19.5 million to 20
million barrels a day caused a sharp decline in the market today,''
said Chris McCormack, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
``The market also broke a key technical level.''
   Analysts said that once the market hit $15.50 a barrel, negative
sentiment took over, sending prices even lower.
   The oil futures market has been largely inactive in recent
weeks, without much fresh news on supply and demand to guide it.
Analysts said Thursday's reports provided the first sign of
direction in some time, and speculated that prices could weaken
further as the increased oil outflow reaches consuming nations.
   ``It looks like we're about to start a move to the down side,''
McCormack said.
   Last week, the market focused on developments in the Middle East
and a tentative cease-fire between Iran and Iraq. Analysts have
speculated that an end to the fighting between the two OPEC nations
could mean the fractious 13-member oil cartel would set production
limits, thus helping to raise world oil prices.
   But on Thursday, analysts said the market reacted to rumors that
Iran had refused to go along with a quota proposed by other OPEC
members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
