<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Boeing Bjt   08-26 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing, Bjt,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boeing Sets Industry Record For Single-Year Commercial Jet Orders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong world economies, attractive airline fares
and a movement by airlines to more fuel-efficient aircraft have
helped Boeing Co. break its own 10-year-old record for commercial
jets ordered in a year, the company says.
   Boeing announced Thursday that an Linjeflyg, a domestic Swedish
airline, had ordered six 737-500 jetliners and took options on six
more, giving Boeing 466 jetliner orders for the year.
   That broke the old record of 461 planes Boeing set in 1978.
   The order, worth more than $175 million, boosted the dollar
value of Boeing's announced 1988 orders to $20.7 billion. Boeing
several weeks ago surpassed the record of $19.9 billion in new
orders set last year.
   ``This represents four consecutive years of record orders for
Boeing,'' John Hayhurst, vice president of marketing for Boeing
Commercial Airplanes told a news conference.
   ``This has been a very good year,'' added Chris Longridge, vice
president of sales for the Boeing operating company. ``Next year,
we're forecasting to have a reasonable year, perhaps not as good as
this one.''
   Still, Hayhurst said Boeing is predicting that over the next two
decades, the world's airlines will need almost as many new planes
as the 8,171 now in service, and Boeing should continue to provide
the largest share.
   Boeing this year picked up a number of large orders, including
15 747-400 jumbo jets by Japan Air Lines, 50 757s by American
Airlines, 30 757s by United Airlines, and the biggest commercial
jetliner order ever, a $4.6 billion deal with International Lease
Finance Corp. for 100 aircraft.
   In addition, both GPA Rolls Ltd., of Shannon, Ireland, and Delta
Air Lines of Atlanta have said they may be interested in ordering
large numbers of Boeing planes, possibly this year.
   ``With the possible order of up to 50 757s pending with GPA
Rolls, a Delta order and another possible 75 jets which could be
used in the Navy's long-range anti-submarine warfare patrol
aircraft program, Boeing could keep going like gangbusters,'' said
Paul Nisbet, an aerospace analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
in New York.
   Hayhurst said Boeing has benefited from strong world economies
that permit people to travel. Airline fares also are attractive, he
said, particularly in the United States.
   Further, airlines are starting to turn to more fuel-efficient
and economical aircraft, including new Boeing planes that Hayhurst
said are significantly cheaper to operate and far quieter than
earlier jets.
   Hayhurst said Boeing predicts that air traffic growth will
continue at about 5 percent a year through 2005.
   ``All of this means a significant amount of traffic growth in
the next 17 years,'' he said. ``In fact, in the year 2005, that 5
percent traffic will mean that the traffic growth will be about 2{
times what it is today. And we forseee a requirement for about
7,400 airplanes, new airplanes, in that delivery timeframe.''
   Longridge said Boeing now has backlog of 1,036 jets, the
industry's highest, which translates to years of work on its
commercial production lines.
   Presently, Boeing is turning out 14 737s and four 757s a month
at its Renton, Wash., plant, with 757 production to increase to
five a month next February, Longridge said. The company is making
five widebody 767s and three 747s a month at its Everett, Wash.,
plant, but plans to boost that rate to five jumbo jets a month by
mid-1989, he said.
   He declined to say whether these plans mean additional hiring at
Boeing, which now employs about 92,000 people in the Puget Sound
region.
   Stockholm-based Linjeflyg, a new customer for Boeing, will take
delivery of the first of the 108-passenger 737-500s in February
1991. The new jets will be powered by CFM56-3B1 engines.
   Boeing's stock closed down 12{ cents a share Thursday, at
$58.62{, after rising $2.12{ a share Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
