<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-26 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady against major currencies in
calm European trading today as the market reassessed trends
following a round of interest rate hikes. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was weaker in early
trading in Frankfurt but was recovering later in European markets
after short-covering and profit-taking on long non-dollar positions.
   On Thursday the U.S. currency fell after the West German central
bank raised its discount rate by half a point to 3.5 percent.
France, Switzerland, the Netherlands and Austria also hiked their
key rates.
   It was also pushed lower after Deutsche Bundesbank President
Karl Otto Poehl said the West German central bank ``will continue
to do everything to stem the decline of the Deutsche mark against
the dollar.''
   One trader said Friday that the market was taking a breather
following the activity caused by interest rate increases.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.26 yen to a closing 133.50 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 133.75 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8630 West German marks, unchanged from Thursday;
1.5730 Swiss francs, up from 1.5715; 6.3332 French francs, up from
6.3275; 2.1042 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1030; 1,385.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,384.13; and 1.2365 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2342.
   In London, the British pound was trading at $1.6950, cheaper for
buyers than Thursday's late $1.6995.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $433.40 a troy ounce. At
midmorning, the City's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $433.75, up from Thursday's late bid of
$433.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $433.80, up from $433.50 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold dropped 86 cents to close at a bid
$435.24.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.72 a troy
ounce, down from $6.77 at Thursday's close.
</TEXT>
