<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-26 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Share Prices, Dollar Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Europe's decision to raise key interest rates
resulted in a plunge in share prices and the U.S. dollar on Tokyo
markets Friday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
321.47 points during the morning session, stayed almost even in the
afternoon to finish the day at 27,565.41. The market shed 305.03
points, or 1.09 percent, which is the biggest one-day decline since
Aug. 10, when it lost 615.49 points.
   ``The decision to raise key interest rates in Europe shocked
many investors and froze them,'' said a stock dealer at a major
securities firm in Tokyo.
   ``We've already had enough unfavorable external factors one
after another,'' he added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   But the market is unlikely to rebound because investors are
still waiting to see how the United States and Japan will react to
the interest rate rise in Europe, according to the dealer.
   Other dealers said the decline of New York stocks overnight and
an upward revision for the U.S. second-quarter GNP weighed on
sentiment.
   Volume traded on the first section was 450 million shares.
   The dollar, which opened at 133.58 yen, closed at 133.50 yen,
down 0.26 yen from Thursday's close of 133.76 yen. The currency
ranged between 133.35 and 133.73 yen.
   The dollar's fall was largely attributed to dollar selling in
Europe as the German Mark recovered after European countries
decided to raise their key interest rates.
   The West German Bundesbank's council meeting decided Thursday to
raise the discount rate by 0.5 percentage point to 3.5 percent, in
a coordinated move with six other European countries including
France, Switzerland and Britain.
</TEXT>
