<1ST_LINE>r f PM-China-Japan 1stLd-Writethru   08-26 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Japan, 1st Ld-Writethru,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deng Says Japanese Leader's Visit Will Lift Relations To A New
Level</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with detail with Deng meeting, Takeshita
meeting Zhao; ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping today welcomed Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita of Japan and said his visit to China will
lift relations between the two countries to a new level.
   The meeting in the Great Hall of the People came a day after
Takeshita announced Japan will provide $6.4 billion in credit for
Chinese development projects from 1990 to 1995.
   Takeshita held extensive talks with Premier Li Peng shortly
after his arrival on a six-day visit Thursday, and also met today
with President Yang Shangkun and Communist Party General Secretary
Zhao Ziyang.
   Deng, the guiding force in China's past decade of economic
reforms, said he was enthusastic about cooperation between the two
nations.
   ``With your visit, Sino-Japanese friendly relations will
certainly reach a new level,'' he said.
   The 84-year-old Deng, a military strategist in the 1937-45 war
against Japan, has been sharply critical of Japan in the past.
   Japanese officials said Deng spoke optimistically of the future
and avoided the controversial subjects that have marred bilateral
relations in recent years.
   Those include Japan's former trade surplus _ now reversed in
China's favor _ China's perception of a rise in Japanese militarism
and a court case which awarded a Kyoto student dormitory, claimed
by China, to Taiwan.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Deng
told Takeshita that China's economic reforms have now entered a
difficult phase and mentioned that prices are rising rapidly.
   The officials quoted Deng as saying China, now trying to end
price controls, will need five years to fully stabilize its pricing
system. Deng, according to the officials, said introducing more
foreign investment and technology would help China's economy.
   On Saturday, China and Japan expect to sign an investment
protection agreement which both sides hope will encourage Japanese
businesses to invest in China.
   In the past year, Deng has resigned from almost all his official
positions, although he still wields considerable influence in
government and party policy.
   The officials said Takeshita discussed Taiwan with Yang, the
81-year-old ceremonial head of state.
   Yang explained China's position of encouraging more contacts
with Taiwan, and said China would be interested in meeting directly
with officials of the rival Nationalist government, the officials
said.
   Takeshita, according to the officials, said Japan welcomes a
recent relaxation of China-Taiwan tensions, including a lifting of
Taiwan's ban on visits to the mainland.
   No details were immediately available on the meeting with Zhao.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
