<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DroughtHay     08-26 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought Hay,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowa Farmers Begin Idaho Hay Harvest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another 15,000 acres of Idaho grasslands
were opened to drought-plagued Iowa farmers for hay harvesting, but
organizers said more equipment was needed to take advantage of the
bonus.
   U.S. Soil Conservation Service officials said Thursday the
number of acres available for harvest in northern Idaho had been
increased to 20,000 from the original 4,500 acres.
   ``We have the manpower we need, but not all the equipment,''
said Mike Tracy, a spokesman for the Idaho Farm Bureau, which
organized the project in conjunction with the Iowa Farm Bureau.
Organizers said local farmers and implement dealers were continuing
to donate equipment for the harvest, but there was still a need for
swathers, hay balers and tractors, he said.
   Burlington Northern is donating railcars to ship the hay back to
Iowa.
   Farmers in the Colfax, Wash., area also donated more than 1,000
bales of their own hay to the Iowans.
   Midwestern farmers lost as much as 75 percent of their hay crop
to the worst drought in 50 years this summer.
   Tracy originally estimated as much as 5,000 tons of hay could be
harvested on the original 4,500 acres. It was not known how much
could be expected to be harvested on 20,000 acres.
   The 64 men, women and teen-agers arrived Tuesday after a
40-hour, 1,600-mile bus trip from south and central Iowa.
   After a hearty farm breakfast at a Grange hall Thursday, the
Iowans began harvesting the hay they hope will feed their hungry
livestock back home.
   ``They were really getting itchy to get some work done,'' Tracy
said.
   Hay mowers began cutting grass on fields near Deary, about 30
miles northeast of Moscow, on land set aside in a government
erosion-control program. The U.S. Department of Agriculture
recently released the Conservation Reserve Program land, which is
normally not farmed, for harvest by drought-afflicted farmers.
   The harvest could take as long as 10 days, but cutting and
baling must be finished by Aug. 31, a deadline set by the
Agriculture Department. Tracy said organizers have notified the
office of Sen. James McClure, R-Idaho, that they may have to ask
for an extension from Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng.
   The generosity of their agricultural colleagues and the Moscow
community was overwhelming, the Iowans said. Harvest equipment was
donated by local farmers and implement dealers.
   ``I'd be a bit leery if someone wanted to use my equipment,''
said Don Tibbals, a dairyman from Albia, Iowa.
</TEXT>
