<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Dukakis-Steel     08-26 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Steel,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Promises National Center For Steel Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis toured a
high-tech specialty steel plant with four other Northeastern
governors and then promised, if elected president, to create a
national center for steel technology to help the industry find new
markets.
   ``We can't have a growing national economy without a strong
steel industry,'' said Dukakis, who was in Pittsburgh on Thursday
for a two-day Conference of Northeastern Governors.
   Among flying sparks and penetrating heat, the governors toured
Allegheny Ludlum Corp.'s advanced technology steel plant in
Brackenridge, where computer-guided furnaces and machinery turn out
stainless steel for the nation's largest specialty steelmaker.
   Dukakis said he was pleased to learn from Allegheny Ludlum
Chairman Richard Simmons that the average worker at the plant,
which employs almost 2,800 about 20 miles north of Pittsburgh,
earns $31,000 a year.
   ``That's what Lloyd Bentsen and I mean when we talk about good
jobs at good wages,'' he said.
   Dukakis was joined at the plant by Pennsylvania Gov. Robert
Casey, Vermont Gov. Madeleine Kunin, Connecticut Gov. William A.
O'Neill and Rhode Island Gov. Edward D. DiPrete.
   Casey is chairman of this year's conference and selected the
theme _ ``Sustaining Northeast Manufacturing: A Key To Economic
Vitality.''
   The governors also toured the University of Pittsburgh's
Research Center in Harmarville, where they saw a demonstration of a
computerized machine that instantly analyzes the chemical
composition of materials.
   At the labs of Suprex Corp., a 6-year-old high-tech firm,
Dukakis pressed a hypodermic needle filled with liquid vinyl
plastic into a table-top machine, which then flashed its analysis
of the fluid onto a separate screen.
   The focus of the conference was to examine state economic
development strategies and the role they play in determining how
well manufacturers make the transition into the world marketplace.
   Today, the governors, including New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean and
Maine Gov. John McKernan, will participate in a roundtable
discussion on manufacturing-related concerns.
</TEXT>
