<1ST_LINE>r f BC-FAO-Locusts     08-26 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-FAO-Locusts,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency Warns of `Explosion' of Locusts in Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The desert locust plague in central and east Africa
will ``explode'' in the next two weeks, causing severe damage to
crops, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization warned Friday.
   ``The extent of infestation in certain African countries is
enormous, and we are extremely concerned,'' FAO Director-General
Edouard Saouma said in a statement. ``There is no doubt that there
will be heavy damage to crops in the middle of the agricultural
season.''
   Dr. Lukas Brader, head of the agency's emergency center for
locust operations, said that 6 to 7 million hectares (14 to 17
million acres) of land in Chad, Sudan and Niger are currently
infested with dense bands of locust larvae.
   ``They are going to explode in the next two weeks and form
massive swarms which will affect large areas of agricultural
lands,'' he said, adding that the size of each swarm could cover
hundreds of square kilometers.
   ``The plague has reached unprecedented proportions and cannot be
controlled in the near future,'' Brader said.
   Heavy rains, particulary in Sudan, have created favorable
breeding conditions for the locusts. While the situation has been
serious for several weeks in Chad and Sudan, the problem has
sharply worsened recently in Niger with some 1.7 million hectares
(4.2 million acres) infested, FAO said.
   FAO said it has convened a meeting of affected and interested
countries in Rome next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
