<DOCNO> AP880826-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AdClaims     08-26 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ad Claims,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>States Investigating Food Companies' Advertising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight states want to find out whether claims
made by dozens of food companies in advertising are misleading.
   Authorities in Minnesota, California, Massachusetts, New York,
Missouri, Texas, Iowa and Wisconsin are examining advertising that
could lead consumers to believe that some products are low in such
substances as cholesterol, sugars and fats, officials said.
   The states have been cooperating in a summerlong investigation,
Norine Olson-Elm, a Minnesota special assistant attorney general,
said Thursday.
   ``We are not challenging ingredients,'' Ms. Olson-Elm said from
her St. Paul, Minn., office. ``We are concerned about advertising
and labeling, how products are marketed and promoted to the
public.''
   The states have not decided how to proceed if they find evidence
of false or deceptive advertising, but they ultimately could sue
the companies, the attorney said.
   Fines would range from $2,500 in California to $25,000 in
Minnesota for each violation, she said.
   The states started the investigation because the claims in some
of the advertising were not covered by federal law, Ms. Olson-Elm
said.
   ``Consumers interpret light to mean low in calories rather than
light in color and texture,'' Ms. Olson-Elm said. ``Light is not
defined by federal law. Consumers have no clear perception other
than it is a reduction.''
   Five companies known to be under scrutiny are Procter & Gamble
Co., of Cincinnati; Kitchens of Sara Lee, Deerfield, Ill.; Nabisco
Brands, Inc., East Hanover, N.J.; Campbell Soup Co., Camden, N.J.;
and Louis Rich Co., Madison, Wis, the newspaper said. Such diverse
products as soup, cereal, cheesecake and meats are involved.
   Procter & Gamble has been asked to provide information
substantiating its claims that its all-vegetable Crisco shortening
contains no cholesterol.
   Spokesmen for the companies said they stand behind the
advertising.
   The investigation covers television, radio and print advertising
regarding nutrition and such ailments as heart problems, cancer and
osteoporosis.
   Companies have been asked to provide samples of advertising, Ms.
Olson-Elm said.
   ``We have set different deadlines for each company,'' she said.
``There is no one target date.''
   One concern of the states is the use of palm oil, which Ms.
Olson-Elm said is higher in saturated fat than many other oils.
   Although soybean oil is the primary ingredient in P&G's Crisco
shortening _ advertised as being cholesterol-free _ it contains
some palm oil.
   ``Studies indicate that saturated fats in palm oil will increase
cholesterol, and therefore we are concerned about palm oil being
included in products that are otherwise lower in saturated fats,''
Ms. Olson-Elm said.
   Cholesterol is a fatty substance in the blood that clogs
arteries, often contributing to heart attacks.
   Palm oil is added to Crisco to give it texture at room
temperature, Procter & Gamble spokesman Don Tassone said.
   The saturated fat content of palm oil is 40 percent. But because
of the relatively small amount of it in Crisco, the overall level
of saturated fats in Crisco is 28 percent, Tassone said. He said
palm oil, as a vegetable oil, does not contain cholesterol.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880826-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 0910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Toyota     08-26 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Toyota,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toyota's Annual Earnings Up 18.9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Corp. reported that its profit after
taxes surged 18.9 percent in its latest fiscal year from the year
before.
   Japan's largest automaker said in an annual report released
Friday that its profit rose to 238.01 billion Japanese yen, or
around $1.78 billion, in the fiscal year ended June 30 from 200.21
billion yen, or $1.50 billion, in the previous year.
   Sales for the year increased 11.1 percent _ to 6.691 trillion
yen, or around $50.04 billion, from 6.025 trillion yen, or $45.06
billion.
   Toyota's total car production for the year was 2,904,071, up 9.9
percent, while truck and bus output edged up 0.6 percent to 950,621.
   The automaker sold 3,831,454 vehicles in its fiscal 1988,
including 2,924,760 cars. The sales included exports of 1,237,867
cars.
   After posting a record profit of 648 billion yen for the fiscal
year ended June 30, 1985, Toyota sustained declines for the next
two years due to the yen's sharp rise in value against the dollar,
which made exports to the United States more expensive.
   Until 1986, Toyota had been Japan's most profitable company for
six straight years. In fiscal 1987, however, Toyota placed third
behind Nomura Securities Co. and Tokyo Electric Power Co.
</TEXT>
