<2ND_LINE>PM-Neiman Marcus-Horchow,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neiman Marcus Parent Company To Acquire Another Famous Dallas
Retailer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative agreement has been reached for the
parent of Neiman Marcus to buy Horchow Mail Order Inc., another
famous Dallas retailer, officials of Neiman Marcus Group Inc. say.
   The two companies announced Thursday they had reached a
tentative agreement for the purchase of the $100 million-plus
premier catalog sales company.
   The final terms have not been settled, officials of Neiman
Marcus Group Inc. of Chestnut Hill, Mass., a division of soft drink
and cinema conglomerate General Cinema Corp., said.
   ``The mail-order business has a lot of potential for us, and
we've said that about Neiman's mail-order business,'' said Peter
Farwell, Neiman Marcus spokesman. ``That's why we're investing in
the new distribution center in Las Colinas (near Dallas).''
   Neiman Marcus previously announced construction of a
270,000-square-foot distribution center to be opened in May 1989.
   Clay Johnson, president of Horchow, said his company's
distribution center in suburban Farmers Branch, where Horchow
orders are processed and packaged, is operating at full capacity.
Johnson declined to comment on how the company might benefit from
Neiman's additional capacity.
   Officials from both companies would not comment on how Horchow
would fit with Neiman's existing catalog operation. The Neiman
Marcus Christmas Book is expected to have a 3.2 million mailing
this year. Neiman also mails 18 other catalogs to its customers
throughout the year.
   Chairman Roger Horchow will be returning to the Neiman fold,
which he left in 1973 when he bought the mail-order business from
Kenton Corp, if the deal is completed. In his 11 years at Neiman,
Horchow had worked his way through the ranks from buyer to vice
president of the retailer's mail-order sales division.
   Horchow Mail Order, which sells luxury giftware, apparel and
other merchandise, has grown tenfold since the Dallas merchant took
over, with sales of more than $100 million.
</TEXT>
