<2ND_LINE>BC-Macmillan,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Macmillan Board Rejects Maxwell Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover target Macmillan Inc. said Friday its
board has determined that the $2.34 billion tender offer launched
earlier this month by Maxwell Communications Corp. is inadequate.
   Maxwell has offered $80 a share for Macmillan, topping a
$75-a-share tender offer begun in July by the Robert M. Bass Group
Inc. of Fort Worth, Texas.
   The New York-based publishing and information services concern
said in a statement that it has had discussions with other parties
that have led the board to believe that ``more than $80 could be
obtained'' in the event of a sale.
   Macmillan stock consistently has traded above $80 a share
recently. In trading on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday,
Macmillan lost 12.5 cents to close at $83.25 a share.
   While Macmillan said it would continue discussions with all
interested parties, the company also noted that it might improve
the restructuring program it unveiled as a counterpoint to Bass's
bid. Bass won an injunction that prevents Macmillan from proceeding
with the restructuring, but Macmillan said it will continue to
``vigorously'' appeal the ruling.
   Bass, which already owns 9.2 percent of Macmillan, opened the
bidding in May by offering to acquire the company for $64 a share.
Shortly after the group sweetened its bid to $75 a share,
London-based Maxwell entered the fray.
   Macmillan rejected the Bass tender offer as ``inadequate'' but
until Wednesday had declined to comment on the Maxwell offer.
Macmillan has denied reports that its executives have held talks
regarding a leveraged buyout.
</TEXT>
