<2ND_LINE>PM-Scherer Fight,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scherer Proxy Vote Challenged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected R.P. Scherer Corp. directors who
favor selling the gelatin capsule maker have asked a Delaware court
to seat them immediately.
   Theodore Souris, Frederick Frank and John S. Scherer filed suit
Thursday in the Court of Chancery in Delaware asking that they be
declared winners in a recent proxy contest.
   But Peter A. Dow, one of the apparent losing nominees, filed a
Chancery Court complaint contesting the proxy results. Dow argued
he should have been re-elected because the final tabulations
excluded about 310,000 votes meant for him.
   Dow backs Scherer management, led by chief executive officer
Peter Fink, which advocates keeping the company independent.
   Dow was defeated by Souris, who was backed by Karla Scherer
Fink, daughter of the company's late founder and Peter Fink's
estranged wife.
   Mrs. Fink and John Scherer, her brother, are both directors.
They control about 38 percent of the company.
   Despite John Scherer's re-election and the election of Souris
and Frank, management still maintains a 6-5 majority. Mrs. Fink
said she would seek support from other directors for her plan to
sell the company.
   In results announced Wednesday, Souris received 3,019,449 votes
to 2,670,876 for Dow.
   Dow claimed 75,000 shares voted by SLH Asset Management in favor
of Souris actually had been acquired by Bessemer Securities Corp.
He said Bessemer unsuccessfully requested that the shares be voted
for Dow.
   He also said 235,200 shares voted in his favor by a trustee,
Manufacturers National Bank of Detroit, should have been counted.
The votes weren't counted after Mrs. Fink, a beneficiary of the
trust, obtained a Michigan Court of Appeals ruling saying the
shares shouldn't be voted.
</TEXT>
