<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SEC-Karcher     08-26 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SEC-Karcher,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SEC Says Son Of Hamburger Magnate Admits Insider Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of hamburger magnate Carl N. Karcher
admitted under oath to insider trading, saying he ordered the sale
of Carl Karcher Enterprises securities when he found out the
company was about to have a drop in earnings, according to federal
documents.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said in recently filed
papers that Carl Leo Karcher hould be found guilty and fined
without a trial because the admissions clearly established guilt.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie is expected to rule on the
SEC's motion for a summary judgment on Sept 12, it was disclosed
this week.
   The younger Karcher told SEC lawyers during an out-of-court
hearing in 1985 that he didn't believe he was doing anything wrong
by selling the debentures to the company that operates the Carl's
Jr. fast-food chain four days before the firm's losses were
publicized.
   ``I firmly believe that it was my legal right to sell those ...
at the time if I was selling it at a loss,'' Karcher told the
lawyers.
   Karcher saved at least $10,500 by selling the debentures and
avoiding the drop in market price, the SEC says.
   Insider trading charges have been filed against Karcher, his
father and 13 other family members.
   The SEC alleges the elder Karcher illegally tipped off some of
his relatives in 1984 that the Anaheim-based company was headed for
a drop in earnings.
   All the defendants have denied the charges. The SEC is seeking a
summary judgment only against the younger Karcher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
