<HEAD>Drug Conglomerate Buys Small Distributor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELROSE PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis Zahn Drug Co., the leading drug
wholesaler in the Midwest, says it is being acquired by
Dallas-based FoxMeyer Drug Co.
   Melvin Zahn, the company's owner and son of its founder,
declined to give a reason for the sale or to disclose the purchase
price.
   But Marvin Kamensky, a lawyer who helped handle the sale, said
that many Zahn accouts are smaller pharmacies that find it
difficult to compete against larger, chain drugstores
   ``It's a rough business,'' he said. ``There are tremendous
pressures.''
   Privately held Zahn, founded in 1931 and based in this Chicago
suburb, had ``in excess of $200 million'' in revenues last year
through the sale of pharmaceuticals and sundries to more than 1,000
hospitals and pharmacies in Illinois, Wisconsin, Indiana and
Michigan, officials said Thursday.
   The company employs about 200 people.
   FoxMeyer, a subsidiary of National InterGroup Inc., of
Pittsburgh, had net sales of $2 billion for the year ended March 31.
   ``The acquisition of Louis Zahn Drug Co. is part of FoxMeyer's
strategy to concentrate on growing and strengthening its core drug
distribution business,'' said Howard M. Love, chairman and chief
executive officer of National InterGroup.
   In 1987, National Intergroup lost $600,000 on sales of almost
$3.4 billion.
</TEXT>
