<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-InsiderTrading     08-26 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Insider Trading,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nippon, Sankyo Employees Traded Before Deal Was Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange said Friday that 34
employees of Nippon Steel Co. and Sankyo Seiki Manufacturing Co.
bought more than 68,000 shares of Sankyo's stock before the
companies announced a business deal.
   Fifteen employees of Sankyo, a precision machinery maker, and 19
employees of Nippon Steel purchased an average of 2,000 Sankyo
shares each as early as four months before the announcement,
according to the exchange's transaction review section.
   Officials at the Finance Ministry and the exchange have been
investigating trading in Sankyo, whose stock soared hours before
Nippon, Japan's largest steelmaker, purchased an 18 percent stake
in the company.
   The exchange took the unusual move of suspending trading in
Sankyo shares on the afternoon of July 29, but the volume of Sankyo
shares traded in the morning session still was nearly 10 times the
previous day's level.
   Securities officials have said they had suspected massive
insider trading.
   The exchange refused to name any of the 34 employees or charge
them with insider trading even though it confirmed that some of
them were directly involved with coordinating the business
agreement.
   ``Under the current law, those individuals did not violate any
law, and we can not say they were involved in insider trading,''
said Takao Nojiri, a senior managing director of the exchange. ``We
believe it is not appropriate for us give out information which may
lead to identifying them.''
   But Nojiri acknowledged that there apparently was ``a leak of
insider information.''
</TEXT>
