<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in the absence of any news that
would affect prices.
   Analysts said the corn and soybean markets gradually are
shifting their focus from the dry growing season to the harvest,
when prices typically move lower.
   ``We're starting to see some corn harvest activity in the South
and two weeks from now we'll probably see it moving into the Corn
Belt,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst with the investment
firm Smith Barney, Harris & Co. in New York. ``It's pretty
difficult to buy the market when the harvest is just around the
corner.''
   The wheat market, despite today's weak opening, is preparing for
an expected increase in foreign demand, Spilka said. In particular,
wheat traders expect the United States and Soviet Union to reach
agreement soon on a new long-term grain pact.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.93 a bushel; corn was \
cent to 1} cents lower with September at $2.80\ a bushel; December
oats, the only oat contract trading early in the session, were \
cent lower at $2.60\ a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to {
cent higher with September at $8.33{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .52 cent higher with October at
72.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .90 cent higher
with September at 82.75 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .37
cent higher with October at 41.22 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .08 cent to .35 cent higher with February at 55.50
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Thursday.
