<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WarnerBankruptcy     08-26 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Warner Bankruptcy,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Warner Still Liable For $22 Million In Restitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge ruled today
that former financier Marvin L. Warner cannot escape the payment of
$22 million in restitution he was ordered to make by an Ohio court.
   Lawrence Kane Jr., special prosecutor for the state of Ohio,
said the order by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge George L. Proctor was
``very significant.''
   Proctor granted the state of Ohio's motion for summary judgment
in the case.
   Warner, 69, a former U.S. ambassador to Switzerland, owned the
Cincinnati-based Home State Savings Bank, which collapsed in 1985
after losing $144 million in investments.
   Warner was sentenced in March 1987 by an Ohio judge to 3{ years
in prison and ordered to pay $22 million in restitution after he
was convicted of six counts of unauthorized acts and three counts
of securities fraud in connection with the bank's failure. He is
appealing that conviction and sentence.
   Warner, who filed for reorganization of his finances under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code in October 1987, had
sought a ruling that he was no longer liable for restitution
ordered by the state of Ohio because he had filed for bankruptcy.
   But the judge ruled Warner ``cannot avoid the $22 million order
through the bankruptcy mechanism,'' Kane said.
   The ruling, Kane said, will allow the state of Ohio to proceed
against Warner to collect the money, including any future assets he
may obtain.
   According to Warner's financial schedules, creditors are seeking
to recover $4.5 billion from him. He claimed he has only $384
million in assets.
</TEXT>
