<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares End Lower On Concern Over Rising Interest Rates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices closed lower on the London stock exchange
Friday as concerns over rising global interest rates and poor
British trade figures continued to unsettle the market.
   Trading dwindled almost to a standstill during the afternoon as
most players covered positions ahead of the three-day bank holiday
weekend in Britain, dealers said.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index finished down
9.5 points, or .05 percent, at 1,770.7.
   Volume was a moderate 415.6 million shares, compared with the
524.1 million shares traded Thursday. However, most of the
session's volume was recorded during the course of the morning and
a scant 18.2 million shares changed hands in the last hour of
trading.
   Analysts said the market was still reeling from Thursday's news
that Britain's merchandise trade deficit widened to 2.15 billion
pounds in July, from about 1 billion pounds in June.
   The trade deficit, double the market's expectations, provoked
the Bank of England to signal a 1 percent hike in British
commercial banks' base lending rates to 12 percent.
   ``The market is clearly taking its time to absorb and adjust to
news that was as shocking as the trade figures,'' said Charles
Larkum, an equity analyst at James Capel and Co. in London.
   Larkum said little economic or corporate news was expected over
the course of the next two weeks and predicted that the FT-SE
100-stock index would remain around its current levels. The only
factor that could upset this scenario is if Wall Street pulls lower
with any significant momentum, he said.
   ``The market is bound to stay nervous until we get some more
data coming through,'' Larkum said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
