<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PrairieGourmet Bjt   08-26 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prairie Gourmet, Bjt,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rural Woman Hopes To Inspire Others To Start Businesses</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZANNE MALICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CORRELL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When she's not tending to her sheep or
horses, Sara Shaw is busy running a mail-order food business out of
her farm house that ships smoked pheasant and other locally
produced foods all over the country.
   Shaw, who was involved in the anti-war movement in the 1960s and
worked as a book designer in New York City before moving to
Minnesota in 1973, started Prairie Gourmet last summer.
   ``I don't envision myself as the head of a big corporation,''
said Shaw, whose business is located near Ortonville in western
Minnesota. ``I just want it to be a stable business that offers
employment to ... people in the area.''
   Shaw was raised in Meriden, Conn., but said she's found her
niche in rural America.
   ``This is my way of counting. Very quietly I can make a
difference by the jobs for women, by responsible agriculture,''
said Shaw, who lives in a comfortably cluttered farm house
surrounded by farm fields. ``In my own small way, I've come full
circle. Rather than thinking that I have to go out and protest,
I've chosen to come back to the country and work.''
   Shaw said she decided to start her own company following a
divorce and after hearing an inspirational speech by Texas
Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower.
   ``Hightower's talk was about how he was trying to turn around
the Texas food economy by not shipping all of their produce out to
be processed, but instead doing it in state. His talk was the basis
for my doing something like that,'' she said.
   Prairie Gourmet ships fresh and smoked pheasant, wild rice,
smoked sausage and lutefisk and lefsa as well as other foods,
including desserts. All of the foods are produced in Minnesota.
   For example, she buys her wild rice from the Leech Lake Band of
Chippewa; most of the pheasants are supplied by the Pomme de Terre
Game Farm in Morris; and area families sell Shaw the duck, wild
turkeys and mallards.
   Shaw employs two local residents part-time during the summer and
about eight during the holiday season to help with packing and
shipping.
   She called the business so far ``extremely successful'' and said
she had sales of $10,000 her first season.
   ``For the fact that I just got the business going last year, I
was just thrilled,'' said Shaw, who got started with a $5,000 loan
for computer equipment from the Big Stone County revolving loan
fund.
   It's important for lenders to support rural residents trying to
start new companies, Shaw said.
   ``I want other counties ... to understand that they have to take
risks sometimes, especially with women who are just trying to get
things going,'' she said. ``We're desperate in many situations, but
with a little help and a little confidence shown in us, we're able
to get some things off the ground.''
   Shaw said she's now working on setting up a cooperative cannery
where rural residents can sell jams and jellies.
   ``In their own gardens, they can raise a lot of these products.
I'd like ownership to be spread to different men and women within
the community, and for them to be responsible for it,'' said Shaw.
   Being a single woman was not a disadvantage in starting Prairie
Gourmet, she said.
   ``The only problems I've run into have been because of the lack
of my own experience,'' she said.
   Shaw said she plans to meet informally with women this fall to
talk to them about starting their own companies.
   ``They just need to hear from another woman and talk to someone
else to say, `Yes, you can do it. I know you're scared, I know you
don't see how in the world you're going to pull this together.'
It's amazing how much confidence you can give someone else,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
