   The stock market drifted slightly higher today
in one of the slowest sessions of the year.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which marked the first
anniverasry of its peak by falling 15.82 points on Thursday, was up
5.51 at 2,016.36 with two hours left in the session.
   Advancing issues held a narrow lead over losers among issues
listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 632 up, 612 down and
593 unchanged.
   Big Board volume amounted to 65.34 million shares as of 2 p.m.
on Wall Street compared with 91.26 million shares at the same point
Thursday.
   Worries that inflation may be accelerating at a pace that would
prompt the Federal Reserve to push interest rates higher have
weighed on the market.
   On Thursday, the government revised upward its earlier estimates
of both economic growth and inflation in the second quarter.
   But today, the government reported personal income rose by 0.6
percent in July, a bit below expectations, while personal spending
rose 0.5 percent.
   Analysts said today's report calmed worries that inflationary
pressures were continuing to build.
   Stocks were supported by a mild rally in the bond market.
   Yields on the closely-watched 30-year Treasury bond, for
instance, fell to 9.42 percent from 9.45 percent late Thursday.
   Among the most active issues on the NYSE, Sunshine Mining
slipped \ to 3~, Wickes was up } at 13}, Exxon was up { at 46\ and
