<1ST_LINE>u f BC-NymexChairman     08-26 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Nymex Chairman,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mercantile Exchange Chief Quits After Government Agency Criticizes
Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman the New York Mercantile Exchange
has resigned following an unusual criticism of him in an
investigation by the federal agency that supervises
commodities-futures trading.
   William M. Bradt, an independent energy-futures trader on the
exchange, quit after the Commodities Futures Trading Commission
said in a 98-page report that he had conducted himself
inappropriately in some exchange matters.
   The report on a previously disclosed inquiry concerning Bradt
said that he had improperly engaged in discussions on a new
business venture with Kevin P. Conway, the exchange's former
compliance director.
   The report also criticized Bradt for accepting fees from a
Chicago member firm of the exchange, evidently for his work in
helping create an oil-options contract traded there.
   Bradt announced his resignation Thursday after the commission
issued the critical report, considered highly unusual for a
government agency that historically has played a minimal
supervisory role in the markets.
   The report stopped short of asserting Bradt had broken any
rules, but recomended changes to strengthen the exchange's
standards of conduct that would avoid giving the appearance of
conflicts of interest.
   In a statement about Bradt's resignation, the exchange made no
mention of the criticism contained in the report, saying only that
it had cleared him of allegations of wrongdoing. The exchange said
Vice Chairman Zoltan Guttman replaced Bradt.
   ``I am pleased with the findings contained in the CFTC report
and that at no time were any Exchange or CFTC rules or regulations
violated,'' the statement quoted Bradt as saying. ``However, I
believe it is in the best interest of my business, my family and
the Exchange, now that I've been vindicated, to step down as
chairman.''
   The rapidly growing exchange is the world's major crude-oil
futures market. It also is an important center for contracts in
heating oil, gasoline, propane, platinum and palladium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
