<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Drift Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT wheat closing price to $3.90 sted
$8.32.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower in
light trading Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in the absence
of any news to influence the market, analysts said.
   ``It was a dull session with further erosion of values,'' said
Ben George, a Merrill Lynch Futures Inc. grain trading specialist
on the exchange floor.
   George said talk circulated that the Soviet Union was in the
market for U.S. corn, but he added the item was ``becoming almost a
daily rumor'' and had little market impact.
   Analysts said the corn and soybean markets were gradually
shifting their focus from the dry growing season to the harvest,
when prices typically move lower, .
   ``We're starting to see some corn harvest activity in the South
and two weeks from now we'll probably see it moving into the Corn
Belt,'' said Walter Spilka, a grain analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris & Co. in New York. ``It's pretty difficult to buy the market
when the harvest is just around the corner.''
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 4{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.90 a bushel; corn was 3{
cents lower to } cent higher with September at $2.77 a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with September at $2.54 a
bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 5 cents higher with
September at $8.32 a bushel.
