<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MartinMarietta 1stLd-Writethru   08-26 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Martin Marietta, 1st Ld-Writethru,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martin Marietta Settle Defense Overcharge Claims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS one graf with company comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Corp., a defense contractor,
has agreed to pay $430,000 to settle claims that the company
overbilled the Defense Department, the Justice Department said
Friday.
   Assistant Attorney General John Bolton said the charges against
the Bethesda, Md., company stemmed from claims filed in 1983.
   The government claimed Martin Marietta's aerospace division in
Baltimore, Md., improperly charged costs directly related to its
unsuccessful effort to win a major Defense Department contract for
the light assault vehicle. The costs were charged to an indirect
account that was partially reimbursed by the government.
   The government also claimed that in 1983 the company changed the
account numbers from certain independent research and development
efforts to an account that was partially reimbursed by the
government.
   A company spokesman who asked not to be named confirmed the
$430,000 settlement but added that the corporation ``believes it
did nothing wrong and specifically disputes the validity of the
Justice Department claim.''
</TEXT>
