<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1653EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-NewspageStocks     08-26 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage Stocks,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Trading Slows to Lowest Level Since Thanksgiving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One day after the anniversary of the stock
market's highest point in history, trading slowed to a trickle
Friday, with business on the New York Stock Exchange falling to its
lowest level in nine months.
   ``I looked at my calendar and thought it was a holiday,'' said
Lawrence R. Helfand, manager of retail sales at the Chicago-based
investment firm Rodman & Renshaw Inc.
   ``I just think a lot of people are finding an excuse to take
vacations or an early Labor Day,'' he said. ``There's no question
that people are just sitting on the sidelines.''
   NYSE volume totaled 89.24 million shares. That is the first time
volume has fallen below 100 million shares this year and is the
lowest since an 86.36 million share day last Nov. 27, the day after
Thanksgiving.
   Other measurements of the market's performance were considered
equally uninspiring, traders said. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 6.58 to 2,017.43. For the week, it rose 1.43
points.
   By contrast, on Aug. 25, 1987, the Dow average hit a record high
level of 2,722.42 and NYSE volume totaled 213.48 million shares. It
was from that point on that the market began a nervous decline that
led to the historic Oct. 19 crash, when the Dow average lost 508
points.
   Traders generally have blamed the stock market's performance of
late on an underlying post-crash investor apathy and concern about
rising interest rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
