<DOCNO> AP880826-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold Bjt   08-26 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold, Bjt,0832</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, But Sentiment Still Bullish</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The central banks appear to have won the latest
round in their bout to subdue the dollar, which finished lower
Friday against several key foreign currencies.
   But just how long the victory will last remains in question, as
bullish sentiment surrounding the dollar still lingers.
   Traders spent the day assessing a round of interest rate hikes
that began Thursday in West Germany and were mimicked by a number
of European countries.
   The West German mark continued to draw broad strength from the
rate hike as well as from a statement by Bundesbank President Karl
Otto Poehl, who said the central bank would do everything to
prevent the mark from weakening.
   Although the dollar moved lower against the mark and several
other major currencies, analysts said there is an underlying
favorable sentiment toward the dollar that simply won't go away.
   ``People have been buying dollars recently on the basis of
interest rate increases to come,'' said Stephen Leach, a currency
analyst at Chemical New York Capital Markets Group.
   ``They have been somewhat restrained in selling dollars because
of the view that (the dollar) will be going up later,'' he said.
Higher interest rates increase the attractiveness of
dollar-denominated securities.
   While many analysts say U.S. interest rates are taking a
breather now, they are looking for further upward moves after
November's presidential election. ``That will stop the dollar from
falling,'' said David Wyss, chief financial economist at Data
Resources, a Lexington, Mass.-based consulting firm.
   The Federal Reserve, which surprised the financial markets
earlier this month by hiking its key lending rate, is more
concerned about keeping the economy from overheating than
manipulating the level of the dollar, he noted.
   Still, keeping the dollar in a reasonable range, partly so that
the U.S. trade deficit continues to decline, requires some skilled
juggling.
   A dollar that is too high makes foreign goods cheaper, whetting
American consumers' appetite for imports. ``And you cannot solve
that by raising interest rates overseas because that slows down
other economies, and they're going to import fewer U.S. goods,''
said Frank Watson, a vice president at Swiss Bank Corp.
   Despite the much-touted rise in the dollar, analysts agree that
its climb has been pretty much confined to the European currencies,
with the exception of the British pound.
   Based on Thursday's closing rates, the dollar was up 2.7 percent
against the mark from year-ago levels, Data Resources said, but it
was off 6.1 percent against the Japanese yen and 4.2 percent
against the British pound.
   ``The huge Japanese segment of the market is quiet, and that
suggests we've come off in part because people recognize there
isn't enough momentum at this stage,'' Leach said. ``The central
banks have won this round, but it may not last very long.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell to a closing 133.50 yen from Thursday's
133.76. Later in London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 133.65
yen. And in New York the dollar closed at 133.78 yen, up from
133.44 yen on Thursday.
   Thursday's report that Britain's trade deficit swelled to 2.15
billion pounds in July from 1 billion pounds in the previous month
continued to pummel the pound. In London it cost $1.6910 to buy one
pound, cheaper than $1.6995 late Thursday. In New York, it cost
$1.6870 to buy one pound, cheaper than Thursday's $1.6965.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.8573 West German marks, down from 1.8657;
1.5681 Swiss francs, down from 1.5705; 6.3065 French francs, down
from 6.3413; 1,382.00 Italian lire, down from 1,385.00, and 1.2392
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2360.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8565 West German marks, down from 1.8630; 1.5655 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5715; 6.3010 French francs, up from 6.2375;
2.0970 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1030; 1,380.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,384.13, and 1.23725 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2342.
   Gold prices eased. Republic National Bank of New York said gold
was bid at $432 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $432.60 on
Thursday. On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for
current delivery slipped to $432.10 a troy ounce, from Thursday's
$432.80.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $431.40 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $433.50. In Zurich, gold closed at a
bid $432, compared with $433.50 late Thursday. Earlier in Hong
Kong, gold fell 86 cents to close at a bid $435.24.
   On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to
$6.655 a troy ounce, from $6.708 an ounce on Thursday. In London,
the metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.64 a troy ounce,
compared with Thursday's $6.77.
</TEXT>
