<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Griffin-Casino Bjt   08-26 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Griffin-Casino, Bjt,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postponements Delay Griffin's Deal For Resorts International</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Resorts International adjourned a
special stockholders meeting on Friday because not enough votes
were cast to approve entertainer Merv Griffin's offer to acquire
the gaming and real estate company.
   Griffin also ran into a stumbling block at a meeting of the
state Casino Control Commission, which postponed a vote on a
proposed trust agreement Griffin must have approved to take over
Resorts from developer Donald Trump.
   Griffin plans to purchase Trump's controlling Class B stock for
$135 a share and has made a tender offer for all of the company's
Class A stock at $36 a share.
   He wants to acquire the Class A and Class B stock of Resorts for
about $300 million and will pay Trump $60 million to terminate his
lucrative management contract with Resorts. After that, Trump will
pay Griffin $255 million to purchase the 1,250-room Taj Mahal
casino complex, which is under construction next door to Resorts.
   The entire deal is contingent on state approval of the trust
agreement and interim authorization for Griffin to operate the
casino.
   Friday's procedural snags left some people unhappy, namely
stockholders who had traveled a distance to attend the meeting at
Resorts in Atlantic City. The meeting was rescheduled for 3 p.m.
Tuesday.
   In explaining why the stockholders meeting would have to be
adjourned, Resorts President I.G. ``Jack'' Davis Jr. said the
American Stock Exchange erroneously reported the meeting would be
held Sept. 13, so an insufficient number of votes were cast.
   When Davis adjourned the meeting immediately after opening it,
several people among the 100 or so stockholders present protested
loudly and demanded at least an update.
   Davis, however, calmly stated, ``I've been advised by our legal
counsel that it is inappropriate and perhaps even counter to
regulations that I discuss anything relating to the merger.''
   He added that he would answer questions privately after the
meeting adjourned.
   Once he left the podium, he was immediately surrounded by
stockholders and offered his apologies.
   ``We have about 2 million proxies and we need about 2.8
million,'' he said. ``Merv Griffin isn't going to buy the stock
until the shareholders have voted on the merger.''
   Meanwhile, the Casino Control Commission delayed a vote on
Griffin's proposed trust agreement because commissioners could not
agree whether a simple majority vote of 3-2 or a more rigorous 4-1
vote was required. The panel is scheduled to vote Tuesday.
   Under the proposed trust agreement, the Griffin Co., solely
owned by the former talk show host, would take control of the
Resorts stock. The company in turn would be placed under a trust
headed by Al Luciani, a former Atlantic City casino executive now
working at the Golden Nugget casino in Las Vegas.
   The state attorney general's office has opposed that
arrangement. Deputy Attorney General Mary Jo Flaherty told the
commissioners Thursday the stock should be placed directly under
control of the trust, rather than Griffin's company.
   Unable to agree on what form of majority was necessary to
approve the trust agreement, the casino commission asked lawyers
for both sides to submit briefs.
   At Tuesday's meeting, they will vote first on the majority
question and then on the trust proposal itself, said commission
spokeswoman Carol Kokotajlo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
