<FILEID>AP-NR-08-26-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ChryslerSettlement     08-26 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chrysler Settlement,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Runs Legal Ads in 20 Markets in Odometer Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. on Friday ran legal advertisements
in the nation's 20 largest newspaper markets, detailing a proposed
settlement in a lawsuit involving cars driven with disconnected
odometers before being sold as new.
   The three-column ads would run only one day, Chrysler spokesman
Tony Cervone said. The ads are addressed to people with Chrysler
cars bought before Oct. 9, 1986 and which were involved in the
company's ``Overnight Evaluation Program.''
   A proposed settlement of the suit was filed Aug. 19 in St.
Louis, and must be approved by U.S. District Judge John F. Nangle,
who has scheduled a hearing for Oct. 11.
   Chrysler has agreed to pay more than $16 million to people who
bought the cars driven in the program. The No. 3 automaker also
said it would provide new cars to consumers who were sold cars
damaged and repaired during the program.
   The company has extended warranties on cars driven but not
damaged in the program.
   The proposed settlement says a consumer taking part in it will
be paid a minimum of $500. The exact amount depends on how many
consumers take part in the settlement.
   The ad said notices of the settlement have been sent to some
consumers, and carries an address where other consumers may send
claims to be part of the class.
   Anyone objecting to the settlement must notify Nangle's court by
Sept. 30, and anyone wanting to remove themselves from the
settlement must do so by Oct. 7.
</TEXT>
